<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-QuakeAnniversary     09-19 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Quake Anniversary,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-government Demostrations Mark Anniversary of 1985 Quake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizations formed after the 1985 earthquake
that killed more than 10,000 people marked the anniversary of the
disaster with anti-government demonstrations and memorial services
Tuesday.
   About 250 people from the Sept. 19 Seamstresses Union attended a
Mass and then briefly blocked busy San Antonio Abad Street, where
hundreds perished in garment factories that collapsed during the
quake. About 50 riot police forced the demonstrators back to the
sidewalk, allowing morning rush-hour traffic to resume.
   Several groups placed flowers at Solidarity Plaza where a hotel
burned in the quake. Residents of the Tlatelolco housing complex
attended a Mass at 7:19 a.m. _ the time the quake collapsed two of
the three sections of a 14-story apartment building.
   Organizations demanding housing for the homeless made a 20-block
march to the Zocalo, the capital's main plaza, where an estimated
12,000 people gathered for a rally.
   ``There are more than 2,000 homeless families still living in
temporary camps in the Cuahtemoc borough,'' Alejandro Varas, one of
the protest organizaers, said in an interview.
   He said there are about 1,500 housing units promised by the
government that haven't been turned over to the quake victims.
``There is open corruption in the delivery. We demand cleanliness in
the distribution of housing,'' Varas said.
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari raised the flag to half-staff
in the Zocalo earlier Tuesday, observed a minute of silence and
dedicated a new government hospital that replaced a 12-story
building that fell.
   He said the new Juarez Hospital ``comes out of the tragedy of the
September 1985 earthquakes. It is, in essence, a memorial to those
who died, and at the same time, shows us that Mexicans can convert
adversity into regeneration and above all, permanently maintain the
solidarity in benefit of all our countrymen.''
   The destroyed hospital was one of two where 19 babies survived in
the rubble for from eight hours to nearly nine days before they were
rescued.
   Dehydrated and covered with infected wounds when they were found,
the ``miracle babies'' today are active 4-year-olds.
   The government said 6,000 people perished in the earthquake and
an aftershock the next day. Others have placed the death toll as
high as 32,000.
   More than 400 buildings in Mexico City, with a population of 18
million, were destroyed and 5,700 damaged, according to the
government.
   The Sept. 19 Seamstresses' Union and the organizations for the
homeless were among groups that were organized after the quake. Many
have developed into permanent activist groups.
   In July 1988, leftist political parties with the support of many
of the groups made their strongest showing in a Mexican presidential
election, holding Salinas to just over 50 percent of the vote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
