<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 0048EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TripleHomicide 1stLd-Writethru a0665 09-19 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Triple Homicide, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0665,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-Ager Charged with Four Murders Arraigned Amid Death Threats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Fixes typo in 2nd graf; INSERTS 1 graf after 8th, `Stabbing
victim...,' to UPDATE with police saying Price implicated himself. ^By
DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARWICK, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager was arraigned under heavy
security Monday in connection with the Labor Day weekend stabbings
and beatings of a woman and her two daughters and the death of a
woman in 1987.
   Craig Price, 15, entered no plea to four counts of delinquency by
first-degree murder and two counts of burglary. Family Court Judge
Carmine DiPetrillo ordered Price held at the state Training School,
a juvenile prison ``for his protection and the protection of the
public.''
   The judge closed the second floor of the Kent County Courthouse
to all but reporters, lawyers and police because of ``certain death
threats that were made against the defendant.'' DiPetrillo and
Attorney General James E. O'Neil did not elaborate.
   Price, a former high school football player known as ``Iron Man''
who was repeating the ninth grade, said nothing during the hearing.
His mother, father and older brother attended the hearing but had no
comment.
   ``He gave a statement to the investigating detectives ... which
would very strongly implicate himself and no others in both
homicides,'' Blanchard said at a news conference after the
arraignment.
   About 30 people gathered outside the courthouse, including some
of Price's friends who claimed he could not have killed anyone.
   Price was arrested Sunday at his house, about a block from where
Joan Heaton, 39, and her daughters, Jennifer, 10, and Melissa, 8,
were found beaten and stabbed to death in their home Sept. 4.
   Stabbing victim Rebecca A. Spencer, 27, who died in July 1987,
lived two houses away from Price.
   ``He gave a statement to the investigating detectives ... which
would very strongly implicate himself and no others in both
homicides,'' police Chief Wesley Blanchard said at a news conference
after the arraignment.
   Some residents of the neighborhood said they had been wary of
letting their children play outside because of the killings, and gun
dealers and alarm companies reported increased business.
   DiPetrillo said Price was charged with three counts of deliquency
first-degree murder and one count of deliquency burglary in the
Heaton killings. He also was charged with one count each of
deliquency first-degree murder and burglary in Spencer's killing.
   O'Neil said that under the state's juvenile laws, Price, if found
delinquent, could be held at the Training School only until age 21.
The attorney general has been unsuccessfully trying to get the
General Assembly to pass legislation allowing juveniles under age 16
who face capital charges to be tried as adults.
   DiPetrillo set a probable cause hearing for Thursday at which the
state must outline its case against Price. Investigators have
declined to provide details so far.
   An autopsy revealed that Ms. Heaton and her daughters had bruises
and numerous broken bones, apparently from a struggle with their
killer, leading police to speculate the killer might have been cut
or injured.
   Scott Putnam, 18, who said he lived with the Prices until a few
days ago, said Price showed him a cut left index finger when Putnam
returned home early on Sept. 2.
   `You could see the bone on one side. It was deep,'' Putnam said.
Price said he had punched out a car window, he said.
   Richard Andrews, 18, said Price also showed him the cut, but
hours before police said they believed the Heatons were killed.
   Although Andrews described Price as a ``tough and vicious''
lineman on the football team, ``I just don't think he's capable of
it. He's not cold-hearted like that.''
</TEXT>
