<FIRST>r p AM-SeattleMayor     09-19 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seattle Mayor,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Voters Chose From 13 Mayoral Candidates in Seattle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmits a0420 to fix category code</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A city councilman bidding to become the city's
first black mayor was considered the frontrunner in Tuesday's
mayoral primary, in which 13 candidates are vying to succeed
outgoing Mayor Charles Royer.
   Polls showed City Councilman Norm Rice leading the clutch of five
political insiders who rose to the top the field. Rice, who lost to
Royer four years ago, was a last-minute entry, but quickly emerged
the favorite.
   His likely opponent in November will be either the city attorney
or a former King County executive.
   The two top finishers in the non-partisan election advance to the
November election. Among other Washington cities, mayoral primaries
will be held in Spokane and Tacoma.
   Royer is not seeking a fourth term and has accepted a top post at
Harvard University's Kennedy School of Government.
   Rice, 46, is a former broadcast reporter, Urban League official
and a banker. He said he jumped into the fray because of what he
called a divisive anti-school busing initiative. The measure will be
on the November ballot.
   Another top candidate, City Attorney Doug Jewett, is co-sponsor
of the initiative, and backers say he can ride it into the mayor's
office.
   A co-favorite for the second runoff spot is Randy Revelle, a
Seattle attorney who headed King County government for four years
after a stint on the Seattle City Council.
</TEXT>
