<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 0209EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-KingDay     09-19 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-King Day,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arizona Senators Face Martin Luther King Day Bill Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Backers of a holiday to honor assassinated civil
rights leader Martin Luther King Jr. are hoping the prospect of a
Super Bowl can succeed where convention boycotts and bad publicity
failed.
   ``Without a holiday, there is little chance in Arizona for a
Super Bowl,'' House Minority Leader Art Hamilton, a Democrat who
leads the pro-holiday forces, said Monday.
   Bill Shover, a newspaper executive who heads the booster group
Phoenix 93, agreed.
   ``We feel sure if we don't have a King holiday we won't be on a
level playing field for the '93 Super Bowl,'' said Shover, director
of community and corporate services for Phoenix Newspapers Inc.,
publishers of The Arizona Republic and The Phoenix Gazette.
   The issue comes up as part of a special session that begins
Wednesday on prison crowding, drugs and economic development, and
both sides are squirming already.
   ``If we fail again, the frustration level ... will rise,''
Hamilton said.
   But Senate President Bob Usdane, a Republican who wants the issue
referred to a general election ballot, said the bill is not
appropriate for a special session.
   ``With a special session, you want to get out quickly,'' Usdane
said. ``You don't need controversy in a special session.''
   The Republican-controlled House has voted for a King holiday in
the past, but conservative Senate Republicans have defeated the
proposal.
   The fight has been going on for years.
   Democratic Gov. Bruce Babbitt, then about to launch a
presidential campaign and frustrated by lack of progress on the King
issue, signed an executive proclamation in 1986 giving state
employees the day off.
   Republican state Attorney General Bob Corbin declared that
Babbitt lacked authority to issue such an order, however. Babbitt's
successor, Republican Evan Mecham, rescinded the proclamation before
it could take effect.
   Mecham also said he did not believe that King deserved a holiday,
and civil rights groups launched a boycott of the state as a
convention site.
   Mecham's impeachment in April 1988 on unrelated charges brought
Secretary of State Rose Mofford to power as governor. Mrs. Mofford,
a Democrat, has pledged to do whatever is necessary for a King
holiday.
   But while Mrs. Mofford has lobbied quietly for the bill since
then, most Senate Republicans have held fast against it.
   A recent study estimates the state has lost $256 million in
convention and tourist business since Mecham's order, and some Super
Bowl boosters say Phoenix's bid for the 1993 game is doomed if
there's no holiday.
   But some Senate Republicans say the holiday is a slap in the face
to Abraham Lincoln because it would follow the federal practice of
combining holidays for Lincoln and George Washington into a single
holiday in exchange for a state holiday honoring King.
   Some GOP senators have offered to vote for a bill that would
trade in Columbus Day for King Day. But Mrs. Mofford said she
rejects that option, and Democratic lawmakers say they would prefer
to avoid it, even though they consider it a possibility.
   Religious leaders and business executives have been urging
approval of the King holiday for years, but Republican lawmakers say
their constituents don't agree.
   Furthermore, they note, many of the businesses that are pushing
for the holiday don't even give their own employees the day off.
   ``They ought to take a look in the mirror,'' said Sen. Doug Todd,
a Republican who is among those targeted by the executives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
