<DOCNO> AP890919-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 0224EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Pentagon-Iowa     09-19 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pentagon-Iowa,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney: No Reason to Question Iowa Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney says he's
satisfied Navy officials investigating the explosion that killed 47
sailors on the USS Iowa did ``the best job they could.''
   Cheney told reporters Monday he had no reason to question the
finding that gunners mate Clayton Hartwig apparently caused the
blast by inserting a detonating device between bags of gunpowder in
the ship's ill-fated No.2 gun turret.
   ``I do think it's important to point out that the information or
the evidence that's available is incomplete,'' Cheney said in his
first extensive public statement about the report.
   ``We'll never know with absolute certainty exactly what
transpired because of the nature of the incident itself,'' he said.
   In the report issued earlier this month, the Navy said the blast
apparently was caused by a detonating device between bags of
gunpowder and that the Hartwig, the gun captain at the time, was the
most likely person to have sabotaged the firing. The report said
uncertainty remains, however, because all the witnesses died in the
explosion.
   Navy officials also said they had ruled out technical reason for
the blast after conducting some 20,000 tests on the gunpowder and
guns used aboard the ship.
   ``I think the Navy did the best job they could under the
circumstances on the Iowa. I think the investigation ... was a good
one,'' Cheney said.
   Cheney said the service did ``a good technical job of checking
out all conceivable possibilities by which that incident might have
occurred, such as an accident because of the gunpowder exploding
prematurely or some other such thing.''
   ``I am satisfied with that aspect of it,'' he said.
   Hartwig's family has criticized the report for singling him out,
but Cheney said Rear Adm. Richard Milligan, the investigating
officer, was required to provide his best conclusion on what
happened.
   ``That's what he's done,'' Cheney said. ``I don't have any reason
to question it.''
   Media General Newspapers reported Sunday that experiments were
being conducted on the Iowa using an improper number of powder bags
combined with the heaviest-weight type of projectile.
   The Navy confirmed Monday that experiments took place, but that
they didn't cause the explosion.
   Navy spokesman Cmdr. Craig Quigley noted Milligen had included
information about the unauthorized tests in his report, and had
mentioned the unauthorized use of five bags instead of six bags of
powder in the No. 2 gun turret, which exploded.
   ``The improper loading configuration did not cause, nor did it
contribute to, the explosion,'' Quigley said. ``Ditto for the
powder.''
   The report says such experiments had been conducted aboard the
Iowa from Nov. 4, 1987 until the day of the explosion.
   The report also notes Fred Moosally, the Iowa captain, had
approved the use of reduced charge loads, but that he thought that
meant six 55-pound bags of powder instead of the larger bags of
around 90-110 pounds.
   Moosally did not have the authority to approve such tests,
Quigley said.
   The report called for the Navy's inspector general to look into
the unauthorized tests, and Rear Adm. Ming Chang plans to do so,
Quigley said.
   Because of the many improper procedures found aboard the Iowa,
such as the gunpowder experiments, it has been left to Adm. Powell
F. Carter, the chief of the Atlantic Fleet, to decide whether
disciplinary action might be taken.
   The battleship currently is in the Mediterranean Sea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
