<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 0225EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-EducationSurvey     09-19 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Education Survey,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nation Needs to Raise Level of Learning, Build New Classrooms, Report
Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Educators already strapped by tight budgets as
they seek to improve classroom achievements face billions of dollars
in maintenance and construction costs in the next few years, the
National Governors' Association says.
   Local school districts, which historically have been responsible
for running and paying for their school buildings, have seen
maintenance costs increase 64 percent since 1983 _ to $41 billion,
according to a report the governors' association issued Monday.
   In addition, existing plans to renovate or build schools are
expected to cost $84 billion, the association's annual 50-state
survey said, warning the costs could undercut direct education
programs.
   ``The projected costs for new school construction and maintenance
and repairs for existing schools are so enormous that they can
overwhelm policy-makers,'' said the report, called ``Results in
Education: 1989.''
   ``When these estimates are broken down on a per-student or annual
basis over a 20-year period, the price tag may seem more manageable.
Still, unless addressed, the problem will mount as aging suburban
schools reach the end of their intended life span and urban and
rural schools deteriorate further.''
   The association said rural schools are particularly pressed,
noting another report that described half of the rural schools as
being unsafe, outdated and inadequate.
   In addition, the report said many school districts are seeing
money drained from their budgets to finance litigation because of
lawsuits.
   Several states are considering measures to relieve the pressure
on local officials by providing state support for school
construction costs, said the report.
   Iowa Gov. Terry E. Branstad, the association president, and New
Mexico Gov. Garrey E. Carruthers released the report a week before
the education summit the governors will have with President Bush in
Charlottesville, Va.
   ``It is time for us as governors to pay careful attention to what
is being taught in our schools and to what students are expected to
learn,'' Branstad said. ``Governors are powerful agents of change
and the report that we submit today is evidence of that fact.''
   Albert Shanker, president of the American Federation of Teachers,
said ``the heart of this report is not so much in what the states
are doing, but in the introduction and unfinished agenda sections
that tell us what we have yet to do to turn our public schools
around.''
   Key findings of the report included:
   _32 states are improving teacher recruitment and retention. Five
states now have teacher licensing boards on which a majority of the
members are administrators and teachers. Thirteen states are trying
to increase the number of minority teachers.
   _41 states report new, expanded or proposed parent involvement
policies, including 16 with programs to assist parents in becoming
effective teachers at home.
   _31 states now offer pre-school and other early childhood
programs and 34 states offer alternative programs for high schools.
   _Nearly half the states use computers to maintain student
records, train teachers, evaluate curriculum and instruct students.
   ``Simply stated, restructuring means that we are trying to find
better ways to organize our schools, to prepare our teachers and to
determine what students must know and be able to do,'' said Branstad.
</TEXT>
