<HEAD>Lawyer Jailed for Failing to Pay Fine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney who has been absent from the
``Night Stalker'' murder trial of Richard Ramirez was jailed for
failing to pay a $100 fine for contempt of court.
   Arturo Hernandez was held Monday in the hospital section of the
county's central jail and was to be released today, authorities said.
   Hernandez stopped representing Ramirez soon after a preliminary
hearing. Superior Court Judge Michael Tynan, perturbed at his
absence, ordered him back to court at one point but later agreed to
a daily telephone call from the attorney to see if he was needed.
   But Hernandez failed to do so, and was fined $100, Tynan's clerk
said.
   The court didn't receive the money. Tynan has since imposed a
$2,400 fine based on a scale for each day he failed to call. He said
Hernandez would be jailed again unless that fine is paid by Sept. 29.
   Ramirez, 29, is charged with being the devil worshipping killer
who invaded California homes in a 1985 rampage, killing 13 people.
The jury has deliberated for 20 days without a verdict.
