<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-Drugs     09-19 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Drugs,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Still Seeking Drug Spending Compromise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Meetings scheduled early afternoon EDT, top prospects uncertain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Republicans concede President Bush's
anti-drug strategy needs some work, but their talks with Democrats
have left the two sides without agreement so far on how it should be
reshaped.
   Democratic and GOP senators planned to meet again today in their
search for a package of anti-drug measures agreeable to lawmakers of
both parties. The bargaining, which began Friday, is being fueled by
both sides' claim to the lead role in attacking illegal drugs and
drug-related crimes, issues party leaders say are uppermost on the
public's mind.
   A two-hour session Monday evening produced no deal.
   Republicans emerged saying they still supported the $7.9 billion
package for fiscal 1990, beginning Oct. 1, that Bush outlined Sept.
5. And Democrats said they remained behind the $10.1 billion plan
they countered with a week later, a proposal that garnered a quick
veto threat from White House aides.
   ``I don't think we're at the point yet where we know what they're
proposing, other than the president's plan,'' Sen. Robert Byrd,
D-W.Va., author of the Democratic plan, said after the session.
   A general profile of a compromise that might ultimately arise
did, however, begin to emerge.
   Sen. Mark Hatfield of Oregon, the Republican's chief negotiator,
said GOP lawmakers ``are willing to help narrow the gap'' between
the two sides' spending proposals for treatment and prevention
programs. The Democrats want more emphasis on those initiatives than
Bush sought.
   Hatfield also said Republicans supported the Democratic concept
of paying for the extra anti-drug spending by cutting other programs
across the board. He said the amount the Democrats want to slice off
other programs would have to be reduced, and indicated other changes
in their plan might be sought as well.
   ``We agree on more than we disagree upon,'' Hatfield said.
   Bush's proposal, which would increase spending over this year's
efforts by $2.2 billion, would be weighted heavily to law
enforcement, prisons and interdiction. Prevention and treatment
programs would get 27 percent of the total.
   Byrd proposed not only beefing up the president's package but
changing the distribution. Of the $10.1 billion Byrd proposes, 65
percent would go to law enforcement and 35 percent to prevention and
treatment.
   That plan, backed by Senate Democratic leaders, would finance its
costs by snipping 0.575 percent from most of the budget. Bush
identified how he would pay for only about $750 million of his
proposal, suggesting cuts in a half-dozen other programs.
   Democrats said Bush's plan does not throw enough of a financial
punch at the problem. Before Byrd introduced his measure, some
Democrats said new taxes are needed to adequately finance anti-drug
initiatives.
   But Republicans have complained the Democratic alternative is too
costly and provides too much to prevention programs. They also
object to the $1.8 billion slice the across-the-board cuts would
take out of the Pentagon's $300 billion budget.
</TEXT>
