<SECOND>PM-Bush-Security,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Says No Hard Intelligence His Family Is Target</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says he has no ``hard
evidence'' his family has been threatened by drug lords, although
members of his family are reported to be getting extra security.
   ``I can't say I'm totally unconcerned, but I don't have any hard
evidence that should further alarm the American people in this
context,'' Bush said when asked whether he knew of threats against
his family.
   ``Clearly any such action would I think just bring down the
entire wrath of the American people and the American government,''
said Bush, in Helena on a two-day western trip.
   The Secret Service beefed up security Friday for Dorothy Bush
LeBlond, the president's daughter who lives near Portland, Maine.
   Newsweek magazine also reported in this week's editions that Bush
ordered 24-hour Secret Service protection for his five adult
children at the recommendation of the agency.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater declined comment Monday.
``We don't comment on security, period,'' he said.
   Neither Secret Service spokesman Robert Snow nor authorities in
Portland would say specifically why the action for Mrs. LeBlond was
taken. But local police said they were notified of the service's
plan to increase security for Mrs. LeBlond before five Colombian men
were arrested with a large arsenal of firearms in Canada near the
Maine border last Wednesday.
   Mrs. LeBlond, who is separated from the husband and has two
children, and her brothers and sisters did not respond to telephone
calls. The other children are Jeb in Miami, George Jr., in Dallas,
Neil in Denver and Marvin in Alexandria, Va.
   The president and his family are authorized to receive
round-the-clock Secret Service protection.
   Family members can turn down Secret Service protection with
presidential approval. A White House source who spoke on condition
on anonymity said Bush's children were not guarded on a regular
basis in the past.
