<FIRST>r w PM-MuseumRegrets     09-19 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Museum Regrets,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trustees Committee States Regrets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A trustees' committee and the director of the
Corcoran Gallery of Art are seeking to heal relations with the art
community by expressing regret for canceling a planned exhibit that
included sexually provocative photographs by Robert Mapplethorpe.
   ``Our course in the future will be to support art, artists and
freedom of artistic expression,'' they said in a statement released
Monday.
   The June cancellation was an attempt to avoid a worsening
political controversy over the use of federal funds by the National
Endowment for the Arts to back controversial works, the Corcoran's
director, Christina Orr-Cahall, has said.
   The action, however, seemed to have attracted more attention to
the issue on all sides, and many artists have denounced the
Corcoran, the nation's oldest art museum.
   Several artists have called for a boycott and two have pulled out
of Corcoran exhibits. Artist Lowell Nesbitt withdrew $1 million in
property and art he had intended to will the museum.
   The exhibit photographs by the late Mapplethorpe was staged at
the Washington Project for the Arts, meanwhile, and drew record
crowds.
   The statement from Orr-Cahall and the executive committee of the
trustees said, ``By withdrawing from the Mapplethorpe exhibition,
we, the Board of Trustees and the Director, have inadvertently
offended many members of the arts community, which we deeply
regret.''
   Endowment funds totalling $45,000 were used to prepare the
exhibition and also to show a photograph by Andre Serrano of the
crucified Christ in a jar of urine.
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., had begun a drive to bar endowment
funds to support any sexually explicit or blasphemous material. The
Senate has enacted such a provision in the endowment's
appropriations bill; the House has refused to go along and simply
voted to reduce the appropriation by $45,000. The two versions will
have to be reconciled.
</TEXT>
