<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     09-19 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Share Prices Also Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended lower against the Japanese yen
Tuesday, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index fell marginally.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 1.47 points,
or 0.004 percent, closing at 34,471.07. It had gained 70.66 points
the previous day.
   The dollar closed at 145.73 yen, down 0.70 yen from Monday's
close of 146.43 yen. It opened at 145.70 yen, and moved between
145.59 yen and 146.15 yen.
   Although the index gained some 100 points soon after the market
opened, it turned downward as some market players stopped buying and
others sold for profit-taking, said a dealer with Nikko Securities,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``There was no specific element that reversed the upswing. It
seemed that participants could not figure out what they should do
next after buying aggressively,'' he said.
   Other dealers said the index started higher as market players
were reassured by the yen's rebound against the dollar, but it fell
back due to speculative investors' selling to make technical
adjustments.
   In currency dealings, the dollar-yen rate was moving nervously
around the 146-yen level after opening lower, following a similar
downswing on overseas markets overnight, traders said.
   The dollar then rose as institutional investors bought the dollar
near its low. The majority of market players remained on the
sidelines, however, ahead of talks among the Group of Seven
industrialized nations this weekend, said a trader with the Bank of
Tokyo, speaking anonymously.
   Participating in the G-7 meeting in Washington will be monetary
officials and central bankers from the United States, West Germany,
France, Britain, Italy, Canada and Japan.
</TEXT>
