<FIRST>r a PM-ZsaZsaTrial     09-19 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Zsa Zsa Trial,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zsa Zsa Obeys Court Warning, Keeps Her Mouth Shut About Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An uncharacteristically taciturn Zsa
Zsa Gabor heeded a judge's warning to refrain from comment about
issues surrounding her cop-slapping trial.
   ``I'm under gagging order,'' Miss Gabor told reporters in the
halls of Beverly Hills Municipal Court as her trial entered its
second week Monday.
   Miss Gabor faces four misdemeanor charges: battery on a police
officer, disobeying an officer's orders, driving with an expired
license and having an open container of alcohol in her car. If
convicted, she could be sentenced to 18 months behind bars.
   Miss Gabor uttered ``no comment'' more than seven times when
questioned by reporters. She even said ``no comment'' when asked
about her ensemble of white slacks and a Navy blue blazer.
   Last week, Miss Gabor said she was afraid of going to jail
because of lesbians there. She also made unflattering remarks about
the prosecutor (``He has a Napoleon complex'') and called the
policeman she is accused of striking an ``Adonis'' and ``a liar.''
   Besides the gag order warning, Miss Gabor told reporters, ``My
mother is very upset and (sister) Eva could kill me'' regarding the
publicity accompanying the trial.
   In testimony Monday, prosecution witness Maureen Cassidy said she
was looking in her rear-view mirror when she saw Officer Paul Kramer
being struck on June 14.
   Kramer had pulled over Miss Gabor for having expired registration
tags. As he checked for other violations, Miss Gabor allegedly drove
off, was stopped again and ultimately slapped Kramer's face.
   Kramer has said the slap was unprovoked. Miss Gabor, a
foot-shorter and 100 pounds lighter than Kramer, has said she struck
in self defense.
   For the defense, a Beverly Hills physician testified that Miss
Gabor ``was hurting all over'' after her arrest.
   Harold Karpman, a cardiovascular specialist, said Miss Gabor
called him after the incident and complained of ``anxiety and
nervousness and pain and discomfort.''
   Kenneth Elconin, an orthopedic surgeon, said he saw bruises on
Miss Gabor's wrists when she visited him two days after her arrest.
   The bruises probably were caused by handcuffs, Elconin said.
   A third defense witness, Dr. Elias Cohenzadeh, said Kramer used
excessive force when he was pulled over for speeding two years ago.
``I've never felt so threatened in my life,'' Cohenzadeh said,
claiming the officer threw him down on the ground.
   The defense has contended that the officer has a history of being
abusive with people he has pulled over for traffic violations.
</TEXT>
