<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Stewart 1stLd-Writethru a0478 09-19 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Stewart, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0478,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Announcer For `Let's Make A Deal' Commits Suicide</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 13th graf, `Stewart was ...' to CORRECT to `Terre' sted
`Terra'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jay Stewart, the ebullient announcer of the
popular television game show ``Let's Make a Deal,'' shot and killed
himself at his home. He was 71.
   Officers were called to the Hollywood home after neighbors and
relatives reported hearing a gunshot, police detective Russell
Kuster said.
   Stewart, whose real name was Jay Fix, was pronounced dead at the
scene.
   ``Let's Make A Deal,'' with host Monty Hall, was first shown on
NBC in 1963 and later moved to ABC until 1976.
   The show also was seen in syndication and more recently was
revived by the USA Cable network. It is not in production now, Hall
said Monday through a spokesman.
   ``Jay Stewart was a member of our `Let's Make a Deal' family for
13 years,'' Hall said. ``His booming voice and his bubbly
personality endeared him to millions. Those of us who worked with
him on a daily basis appreciated his talents. He was more than an
announcer, he was my co-star and my friend.''
   ``Let's Make a Deal'' opened with a drum roll and Stewart's voice
over a shot of three numbered doors. Contestants were selected from
the audience, whose members wore costumes.
   A popular feature was ``Jay's Tray,'' which contained a hidden
item, sometimes valuable, sometimes not. The announcer brought the
tray to Hall, who then bargained with a contestant over its value.
   Kuster said Stewart shot himself as he stood just outside the
entrance to the detached garage of his home Sunday morning. He left
a note, and a will, said Kuster, who declined to give further
details.
   Early this year, Stewart retired from announcing and became an
agent for emcees and announcers, specializing in game shows, said
talent agent Don Pitts.
   Pitts said the death came as ``a complete shock to all of us. As
far as we knew his health was fine. ... He was always a very
positive, `up' kind of person.''
   The note left behind, according to Pitts, gave a different
perspective. ``Jay said he had been hurting for a long, long time,''
Pitts said.
   Stewart was a native of Indianapolis. His first job in radio was
at WBOW in Terre Haute, Ind. From there he went to Cincinnati's WLW
as an announcer and emcee.
   In 1943, Stewart got a job at KNX, a CBS radio station in Los
Angeles.
   During his career he announced for several radio and television
shows, including the ``Kate Smith Hour,'' ``Carnation Family
Party,'' and ``It's Fun to Be Young.''
   He is survived by his wife, Phyllis, and two daughters. Funeral
arrangements were pending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
