<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 0430EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Argentina     09-19 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Argentina,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Generals, Admirals Facing Human Rights Charges To Be Pardoned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Carlos Menem says he
will pardon 18 retired generals and admirals who face charges they
committed hundreds of human rights abuses in the 1970s during the
armed forces' war on leftists.
   The cases of six other people, including two former presidents
already convicted and sentenced, will be considered at a later date,
Menem said late Sunday in a brief interview with state-run
television.
   Menem, who took office in July, said ordered the pardon ``for the
good of my country'' and due to the ``need for reconciliation to
pacify Argentina.
   ``It is not possible to continue living in an ignominious past
that wounds us all,'' Menem told Channel 7.
   Menem's statement was the first firm indication of who would be
included in the controversial pardon, expected to be formally
announced after his return Sept. 28 from a visit to the United
States.
   ``This is getting worse and worse,'' said Hebe Bonafini, founder
of the Mothers of the Plaza de Mayo, a group made up of relatives of
people who disappeared during the 1970s. ``All the military is
responsible for what happened _ for the kidnappings, the torture and
the disappearances.''
   Sixteen retired generals and two admirals face trial in civilian
courts on hundreds of charges, including kidnapping, torture and
murder, growing out of a brutal campaign conducted against leftists
during the 1976-83 military regime.
   Six others were convicted of similar charges in 1984 and are
serving terms ranging from eight years to life at a military prison.
   They are former military presidents Gens. Jorge Videla and
Roberto Viola, former Navy commanders Adms. Emilio Massera and
Armando Lambruschini and former Buenos Aires provincial police
chiefs Gens. Ramon Camps and Osvaldo Riccheri.
   A government commission named by Menem's predecessor, former
President Raul Alfonsin, determined that at least 8,900 Argentines
disappeared during the anti-subversion campaign and were presumed
dead.
   Human rights groups have accused the armed forces of genocide.
   Menem, who took office July 8, made no reference to former
leftist guerrilla leader Mario Firmenich, now serving a 30-year
sentence for kidnapping and murder. Unconfirmed reports have
indicated his case might be considered along with those of the
convicted military men.
   Menem repeatedly has said he intends to resolve the ``military
question'' before the end of the year and put an end to
civilian-military tension stemming from the trials of officers.
   But the possibility of a pardon has angered human rights groups,
who organized a Sept. 8 opposition march in Buenos Aires and other
major cities.
   Government officials said Monday the pardon also would include
military officers facing disciplinary action for taking part in
three insurrections in April 1987 and January and December 1988,
during the Alfonsin presidency.
   The revolts, which were quelled with little bloodshed, were aimed
at ending the military trials.
   The number of those officers facing action never has been
announced, but they are estimated to total about 100, including Lt.
Col. Aldo Rico, leader of the first two revolts, and Col. Mohamed
Ali Seineldin, who led the third.
</TEXT>
