<FIRST>r a PM-NorCalStorm     09-19 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NorCal Storm,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last Day of Storm Brings Tornadoes as Grape Growers Assess Damage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms and heavy rains drenched
northern California for a third day, dashing hopes of a fruitful
grape harvest in the region's wine country.
   ``We were talking about a very large chardonnay crop this year.
We can forget about quantity now and we'll have to see about
quality,'' said Andrew Beckstoffer, the biggest wine grape supplier
in Mendocino County with 2,000 acres.
   Growers in Napa, Sonoma and Mendocino counties worked in the
fields and hoped for sunshine as the sun broke through clouds Monday
afternoon after three days of rain. The deluge drenched the
vineyards, threatening more than 11,000 acres of grapes that can
fetch about $1,800 a ton or more.
   Wine producers were most concerned about the chardonnay and
sauvignon blanc fruit, which had been close to maturity before the
storm _ the remnants of Hurricane Octave _ struck.
   The growers hoped hot, dry weather, or at least cool and windy
weather, would help negate the effects of the rain. The National
Weather Service forecast fair and warmer weather today and warm, dry
weather the rest of the week.
   ``There's going to be some rot, even if the sun comes out now and
everything turns out right,'' said Beckstoffer, whose workers began
pulling the leaves out of the bottom of the vines to help them dry
faster. ``The thing that scares me is that this (rain) might not
end. We might be in for the start of cold, wet winter.''
   At Sebastiani Vineyards in Sonoma, vice president and executive
winemaster Doug Davis said he could see some bunch rot already,
especially on the tissue-paper thin skin of chardonnay and sauvignon
blanc grapes.
   Most of the approximately 190 vineyards in Napa Valley grow the
threatened grapes. Champagne grapes, which mature earlier, escaped
the damage. Red wine grapes, harvested in October, also were
expected to be in good shape.
   The cost of picking the white wine grapes is likely to soar
because of the weather. Picking them selectively takes longer and
could push labor costs from about $100 a ton per farm worker up to
about $140 a ton.
   Alice and Ray Burch, whose family has owned Mallard Winery Inc.
in Napa for five generations, reserved helicopters to blow their
crops dry when the rain stops. They said this is the first time in
more than 10 years that they have had to use helicopters to save a
crop.
</TEXT>
