<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 0447EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-19 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed lower against the Japanese yen
today, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index declined by a tiny
fraction.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues fell 1.47 points,
or 0.004 percent, closing at 34,471.07. It had gained 70.66 points
the previous day.
   The dollar closed at 145.73 yen, down 0.70 yen from Monday's
146.43-yen finish. It opened at 145.70 yen and ranged between 145.59
yen and 146.15 yen.
   Currency trading was inactive, said Mitsuhiko Kinugasa, a senior
trader with Daiwa Bank.
   ``Although quite a few market players have had long dollar
holding positions, they didn't sell as many dollars as we had
expected, mainly because they had no dollar-selling incentives,'' he
said.
   ``The market's major concern was whether G-7 (group of seven
industrial) nations can reach agreement on how to work on
international interest rate gaps,'' Kinugasa said.
   ``The problem is that the United States doesn't seem to have made
up its mind on what to do with its interest rates and the rising
dollar,'' he added.
   Many market players remained on the sidelines ahead of a G-7
meeting this weekend, traders said.
   Participating in the meeting, opening Saturday in Washington,
will be monetary officials and central bankers from the United
States, West Germany, France, Britain, Italy, Canada and Japan.
   On the stock exchange, the market's main barometer gained about
100 points in early trading but fell back again, dealers said.
   Kazuhiro Nomura, a dealer with New Japan Securities Co., said
market players avoided major moves except for technical adjustments
involving some companies whose account settlements for the first
half of fiscal 1989 year are scheduled for Wednesday.
   ``The index rose back a bit toward the end of the afternoon
session as market players bought for their arbitrage deals,'' he
said.
   Arbitrage is a common technique to make profits out of prices gap
between the spot and futures markets.
   Nomura said many stock market players were deeply concerned about
the dollar's recent strength, which has been the major discouraging
factor in the market.
   Trading was inactive, with first section volume estimated at 650
million shares, up from Monday's 450 million.
</TEXT>
