<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS to `altered' in 1st sentence of 2nd item; fixes `created'
in 1st sentence, item 3.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ford To Fix Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. says it will repair for no
charge up to 493,000 Escorts and Mercury Lynxes with faulty emission
control systems and 67,156 Tracers with apparent seat belt defects.
   The automaker announced recalls of both sets of vehicles Monday.
Emission control improvements were offered for the 1.9-liter 1985
Ford Escort and Mercury Lynx and the 1986 Escort, Lynx and Ford EXP.
   The Environmental Protection Agency discovered excessive
emissions of hydrocarbons and carbon monoxide during routine tests
of 1985 models, agency spokeswoman Martha Casey said.
   The agency has recalled 37,537,746 vehicles for emission-control
repairs since it began the practice in 1971, Ms. Casey said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Researchers Says Altered Cells Appear To Shrink Cancer Tumors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Genetically altered cancer-fighting cells have
shrunk tumors in one patient and cells from a single injection
continue to work for at least 19 days, according to researchers.
   Five patients, all terminally ill with a cancer called malignant
melanoma, have been treated with gene-modified cells, Dr. Steven
Rosenberger, a National Cancer Institute researcher, said Monday.
   The lymphocytes, a type of cancer-fighting cell, used in the
study are natural cancer-fighting cells that had been cultured from
cells withdrawn from the woman's tumors.
   Rosenberg and his colleagues have developed a technique wherein
tumor-infiltrating lymphocytes, or TIL cells, are cultured in the
laboratory in interleukin-2, a protein that promotes lymphocyte
growth. When the cells multiply to 200 billion, they are then
reinjected into the patient's blood stream as an army of cancer
fighters.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Formed to Assess Nation's Needs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democrats have created a panel to study
the nation's housing needs and recommend reforms in the Department
of Housing and Urban Development.
   Sen. Alan Cranston of California, named to head the eight-member
task force, said Monday that one of its purposes will be to prod the
Bush administration to take a position on housing for the
disadvantaged.
   The task force will issue a report and make recommendations by
the end of the year, said Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell of
Maine. He said housing legislation ``will be a high priority for
next year.''
