<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 0514EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Hugo-Relief     09-19 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo-Relief,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relief Agencies Need Cash, Few Goods</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government, Puerto Rican communities in the United
States and voluntary relief agencies have started relief efforts to
help communities struck by Hurricane Hugo.
   The mobilization came as the storm lashed Puerto Rico after
battering the U.S. Virgin Islands and other tourist havens, leaving
at least 14 people dead and tens of thousands homeless.
   U.S. Secretary of the Interior Manuel Lujan, attending a
conference in Honolulu with top officials of U.S. territories in the
Pacific and Caribbean, said Monday $500,000 in emergency assistance
funds have been released to aid the storm-stricken areas.
   Lujan said he will leave Hawaii Wednesday night to return to
Washington to plan a tour of the devastation in the Virgin Islands.
   Gov. Rafael Hernandez-Colon of Puerto Rico said late Monday that
Hugo left at least 27,900 people homeless. He said he would ask
President Bush to declare the island a disaster area.
   In New York, bank accounts, hotlines and phone-a-thons are being
set up by the city's Puerto Rican community to aid hurricane victims.
   The Department of Puerto Rican Community Affairs in the United
States, an organization run by the Commonwealth of Puerto Rico,
began to coordinate disaster relief efforts by churches, banks and
individuals around the city.
   ``I have my whole family there _ my mother, my sister, my
friends, my aunts, my grandmother,'' said Ruth Noemi Colon, a
spokeswoman for the agency. ``I talked to them last night. I haven't
any information today. You can tell how I feel _ I'm worried.''
   Meanwhile, an organization of voluntary relief agencies urged the
public to donate cash rather than goods in an effort to avoid
problems that have occurred during several past disasters, when
agencies were inundated with unneeded goods that hampered delivery
of needed items.
   For example, people donated 1,000 pairs of high-heeled shoes to
victims of a Mexican earthquake, while boots and wool sweaters were
offered to Jamaica after a hurricane last year and earthquake
victims in Peru got 7,000 bras.
   ``Goods should not be collected or sent unless they have been
requested by the disaster-stricken country or private voluntary
organizations,'' said InterAction, a membership group of relief
agencies.
   When a need is identified following a disaster, local American
Red Cross chapters can help report which supplies are needed,
InterAction suggested.
   Otherwise, cash is the best way to make a contribution, because
relief workers can then purchase goods that are actually needed,
officials said.
   InterAction represents about 120 voluntary relief organizations,
including American Red Cross, CARE, Save the Children, World Vision,
Oxfam and the Christian Children's Fund.
   New Yorkers with roots in Puerto Rico hoped for the best. Pilar
Alamo, who has lived in the city for five years, said she last spoke
to her family Sunday.
   ``They had candles and a small gas stove and tried to board up a
couple of glass windows,'' said Alamo, whose siblings, parents and
grandparents live together in Bayamon. ``They live in a cement house
but it's always worse in the poorer communities where they live in
shacks or wooden houses.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
