<FIRST>r a PM-MissAmerica-Oklahoma     09-19 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Miss America-Oklahoma,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miss Oklahoma Says Pageant Officials Herded Contestants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The contestant likely to be remembered in
Miss America Pageant history as the one who got plunked on the head
with a beer bottle said she detested the way pageant officials
treated the women.
   ``I hated being herded around with 50 other women,'' said Tamara
Toshiba Marler, Miss Oklahoma, in an interview with The Daily
Oklahoman on Monday. ``We were intelligent, professional women and
we were treated like little girls.''
   Ms. Marler, one of 10 finalists, suffered a concussion when
struck by the bottle during Friday night's parade along Atlantic
City, N.J.'s Boardwalk.
   She spent the night in the hospital but competed in Saturday
night's competition.
   ``The pageant officials wouldn't even let me talk to the media
while I was in the hospital,'' she said. ``They were afraid of the
bad publicity.''
   Ms. Marler, a University of Tulsa marketing graduate, said she
thought she had been shot when the bottle bonked her on the head.
   ``Blood was gushing all over me,'' she said. ``People were trying
to cover me, and there was broken glass all over the place.''
   Ms. Marler said she felt light-headed Saturday night, but didn't
think the injury affected her performance.
   ``I think the judges might have been more affected by the
incident than I was,'' she said. ``They may have decided not to give
me any sympathy points, but we'll never know for sure.''
