<FIRST>r a PM-NerveGas     09-19 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nerve Gas,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nerve Gas Conspirator Sentenced to 30 Months in Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A businessman has been sentenced to 30 months
in prison for conspiring to send Iran deadly nerve gas, which the
prosecutor called a weapon of genocide.
   Juwhan Yun, 48, will serve no more than 22 months because U.S.
District Judge H. Lee Sarokin gave him credit for time served after
the Jan. 12 arrest.
   Yun was convicted May 19 of conspiring to export arms illegally.
   In his sentencing Monday, Sarokin said the weapon _ the nerve gas
sarin _ had the capability of inflicting massive casualties.
   But the judge noted that there was no chance of the gas ever
leaving the United States because Yun's arms contact was in fact an
undercover Customs Service agent.
   He also said it was questionable whether Yun ever would have
committed a crime if the agent, Richard Kennan, had not intervened.
   Yun, in addressing Sarokin, blamed Kennan for his troubles.
   ``I still believe I am victim of Mr. Kennan, for his achievement
and advancement,'' he said. Yun also accused the government of
racism in targeting him, a Korean-American, because of his heavy
accent.
   Customs agents were tipped off by a former agent then working for
a legitimate New York arms company who had been telephoned by Yun
regarding an ammunition deal.
   Yun, who owned a trading company called Komex International Corp.
in Summit, conspired to ship 500 quarter-ton bombs to Iran through a
British arms dealer, Charles Caplan.
   ``I think we were outraged by the charge he was targeted because
he was an Oriental. There was a good reason for starting this
investigation,'' said U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito Jr., who called
the sentence fair and appropriate.
   Defense attorney Stephen Dratch promised to appeal the conviction
and sentence.
   Yun showed no reaction when Sarokin announced the sentence, but
family members wept loudly. In the hallway, Yun's elderly mother
fell writhing to the ground. Yun's wife sat throughout with her eyes
closed, as she had during most of the case's proceedings.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Mark S. Olinsky called the gas the ``most
heinous weapon, or close to it, in the history of mankind.'' He
noted it was developed by the Nazis, who experimented with it on
concentration camp victims.
   The substance is an odorless, colorless poison that enters the
body by inhalation, absorption or injection and causes a painful
death.
   Yun described himself as an honest businessman who emigrated to
this country in 1972 seeking opportunity.
   ``I came to the States for better education, more to enjoy
freedom and justice and to make money more honestly.''
</TEXT>
