<FIRST>r a PM-BeachBoySuit     09-19 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Beach Boy Suit,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beach Boy's Wilson Sues for Rights to Songs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beach Boy's founder Brian Wilson filed a $100
million civil suit to recover copyrights to songs that his father
sold to A&amp;M Records and an affiliate for $700,000 in 1969.
   The Superior Court suit Monday charges Irving Music and A&amp;M with
fraud and Wilson's former attorneys, Mitchell, Silberberg &amp; Knupp of
Los Angeles, with legal malpractice in connection with the sale.
   It seeks more than $50 million in compensatory damages _ the
amount Wilson alleged A&amp;M earned in publishing royalties from the
songs he authored and recorded with the Beach Boys _ and $50 million
in punitive damages, said Wilson's attorney, James P. Tierney.
   ``Brian Wilson was an established writer in 1962 at the age of
19,'' Tierney said. ``A performer who has hit songs does not
transfer all publishing rights to his future songs to a publishing
company for no consideration.''
   The suit covers publishing rights to up to 200 songs recorded by
the Beach Boys before 1969, Tierney said, among them ``Surfin'
USA,'' ``Help Me Rhonda,'' ``Good Vibrations'' and ``California
Girls.''
   A spokeswoman at A&amp;M said Monday the firm and its affiliate would
have no comment on the suit. Attorneys at Mitchell, Silberberg &amp;
Knupp could not be reached for comment in repeated telephone calls
to their offices.
   The suit contends that
   Wilson was unable to assert his rights to the songs because of
his drug and alcohol abuse and psychological illness, the suit
claims. The diagnosis of paranoid psychosis that still affects the
singer stemmed from childhood abuse by his father, Murry Wilson,
Tierney said.
   Murry Wilson sold the songs because he was upset over his firing
as the band's manager in 1964, Tierney said in an interview. Brian
Wilson's attorneys, aware of their client's condition, never advised
him of his right to assert ownership to the songs, Tierney said.
   In 1962, the year he formed the Beach Boys, Wilson verbally
agreed to allow his father, Murry Wilson, administrative control of
his songs, with Brian retaining 100 percent ownership, Tierney said.
   Murry Wilson set up Sea of Tunes Publishing Co. to administer the
songs. In 1969, upset over his firing as the band's manager five
years earlier, Murry Wilson sold his son's publishing rights to the
songs to Irving Music for $700,000, Tierney said.
   ``Brian never saw a penny of it,'' he said.
   Murry Wilson died in 1973.
</TEXT>
