<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed in quiet, early European
trading today as market participants held off taking new positions
ahead of new U.S. economic data scheduled for release later in the
day.
   Gold prices fell.
   Foreign currency dealers said the release of the U.S. Consumer
Price Index for August at 8:30 a.m. EDT, expected to show a slight
rise in inflation, has slowed the trading session.
   Dealers are also looking ahead to Thursday's council meeting of
the West German central bank, and to the weekend meeting of the
Group of Seven industrialized nations.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.70 yen to a closing 145.73 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 145.95 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Monday:
   _1.9539 West German marks, up from 1.9525
   _1.6890 Swiss francs, up from 1.6850
   _6.6000 French francs, up from 6.5890
   _2.2005 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2180
   _1,408.75 Italian lire, down from 1,417.40
   _1.1828 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1834
   In London, the dollar rose slightly against the British pound. It
cost $1.5678 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5695 late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $361.30 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $361.65. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $360.65.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $360.70, down from $361.00 late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 86 cents to close at a bid
$360.90.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.08 a troy ounce,
unchanged from late Monday.
