<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Mozambique-Flogging     09-19 0102</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Mozambique-Flogging,0103</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Assembly Repeals Law Which Allowed Flogging</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The national assembly has repealed a
1983 law that allowed courts to order public flogging as part of the
sentence for certain crimes, the Mozambican news agency reported
today.
   The law, repealed Monday on a unanimous vote, had allowed judges
to impose flogging, in addition to prison sentences, in cases
involving security offenses, black marketeering, armed robbery and
the rape of minors.
   International human rights groups had criticized the law and
Mozambican authorities reported cases where policemen improperly
carried out floggings on their own, without any court proceedings.
