<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 0622EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WingCracks     09-19 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wing Cracks,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wing Cracks Send C141 Fleet for Inspection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROBINS AIR FORCE BASE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Small metal fatigue cracks
found in the rear wing joints of more than a third of the Air
Force's aging C-141 transport planes have sent the fleet in for
inspections and repairs.
   It is the second time in two years that wing cracks forced the
Air Force to restrict flights of its workhorse ``Starlifters,''
which are repaired at Robins Air Force Base.
   The cracks were discovered by Robins inspectors last month and
led the Military Airlift Command to order checks of its 266 C-141s,
some of which are delivering military supplies to Colombia for the
push against drug kingpins.
   All of the C-141s are more than 22 years old.
   As of Monday, cracks had been discovered on 79 of 204 planes
inspected, said Capt. Tom Dolney, a spokesman for MAC headquarters
at Scott Air Force Base near Belleville, Ill.
   Sixty-four of the planes have been repaired and returned to
service.
   Dolney said the restrictions have not affected operations.
   Military Airlift Command also flies C-5 and C-130 transport
planes.
   The cracks range in length from one-eighth of an inch to 1{
inches. They have been found on rear wing joints that connect the
inner and outer portions of the plane's 159-foot wings.
   ``Cracks were predicted to occur in this area. However, they were
discovered sooner than anticipated,'' said Robins spokesman Dale
Brinkman.
   Last year the Air Force grounded and inspected its Starlifter
fleet because of extensive corrosion and cracks in center wing
structures.
   The plane was originally designed by the Lockheed Georgia Co. for
a lifetime of 30,000 flying hours. Most already have flown more than
29,000 hours.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
