<FIRST>r a PM-NursingHomeDeaths     09-19 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nursing Home Deaths,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witness: Former Nurse Aide `Joked' About Killing Patients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former nursing home aide charged
with smothering five patients often joked about having committed
murder, her former lover testified.
   Heather Baragar testified Monday in the trial of Gwendolyn
Graham, who is charged with five counts of first-degree murder and
one count of conspiracy to murder for allegedly suffocating five
severely incapacitated patients at Alpine Manor Nursing Home in
Walker.
   Baragar, also a former nurse's aide at Alpine Manor, testified
that she and Graham became lovers around the time the alleged
slayings began in January 1987. Their relationship continued until
December 1988, when Graham was arrested, she said.
   When the 26-year-old Graham first told her she had killed six
patients at the nursing home, Baragar said she didn't believe it and
``just let it go.''
   But Graham then began telling other friends, Baragar testified.
   ``She joked around about it,'' Baragar said. ``She'd say, `I
killed six people.'''
   Graham was visibly shaken during Baragar's testimony, dabbing her
eyes with a tissue.
   Baragar said Graham admitted smothering the patients with a
pillow while her live-in lover, former nurse's aide Catherine Wood,
stood guard outside the door.
   After Baragar and Graham moved to Tyler, Texas, in July 1987,
Graham heard that an autopsy was being conducted on one of the
alleged victims, Baragar said.
   ``She wanted to know if it was true and if it was true, she
wasn't going to take the whole blame for (the slaying),'' Baragar
said. ``Cathy was part of it.''
   In other testimony, Ms. Wood's ex-husband, Ken Wood, testified
that she confessed to him shortly after Baragar and Graham moved to
Texas. The Woods separated in 1986 and divorced the following year.
   ``She said, `You wouldn't believe some of the things we've
done,''' Wood testified. ``She said that they had killed six people
at Alpine Manor.''
   The patients' deaths were ruled natural until Wood told police of
his ex-wife's confession in October 1988, about 14 months after
their conversation. Ms. Wood has pleaded guilty to one count of
second-degree murder and one count of conspiracy to murder. In
exchange for her testimony against Graham, two counts of
first-degree murder were dropped. She has yet to be sentenced.
   Outside court, Wood told reporters he waited before going to
police because he had promised his ex-wife he wouldn't tell anyone.
   ``I thought about the families of the victims; so many people
were going to get hurt,'' Wood said. ``But Cathy wasn't getting any
better. I sensed a lot of guilt. She couldn't let go of what had
happened. ... I went to police because she needed help.''
   The prosecution was expected to rest today, after which Graham is
expected to testify in her own behalf. If convicted, Graham faces a
mandatory life prison term without parole.
</TEXT>
