<FIRST>r p PM-VoterLawsuit     09-19 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Voter Lawsuit,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Approves Lawsuit Settlement, Avoids Delay of Today's Council
Primaries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city held its first district-only primary
elections today after officials approved a settlement in a voters'
rights lawsuit.
   The city council decision Monday evening ended a year-long legal
battle and negotiations with lawyers representing black and Hispanic
voters in the federal class-action suit.
   ``At last we've resolved it,'' Mayor Maureen O'Connor said. ``I
think it is a fair compromise, and I am pleased the election will
proceed. I hope everybody goes out and votes.''
   Voters approved district-only elections last year. Today's
primary in four of the city's eight council districts is the first
election since then.
   The lawsuit contended the voting power of minorities in San Diego
was diluted unconstitutionally by a city-wide council election
system.
   Terms of the settlement require June 1990 ballot initiatives on
redistricting the city and on increasing the size of council from
eight to 10 seats.
   ``This increases the opportunity for minorities to elect who they
want to elect, and it increases the opportunity for minorities to
get elected,'' said Jess Haro of the Chicano Federation, which filed
the lawsuit.
