<FIRST>r a PM-SterileMedflies     09-19 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sterile Medflies,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sterile Medflies Released in California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two million sterile Medflies have
been set loose with a mission to protect California's fruit crop by
messing up the sex lives of their fertile relatives.
   State officials aboard slowly moving flatbed trucks Monday
released the hot-pink irradiated flies from buckets, beginning the
state's final assault on a small but worrisome infestation here of
the Mediterranean fruit fly, which destroys fruit crops.
   ``We want to flood the area with enough sterile flies so that
there's almost no possibility that two fertile flies will meet and
mate,'' said state entomologist Gary Agosta.
   Twenty-three wild Medflies have been found since Aug. 31. On
Sept. 8, helicopters sprayed Mountain View, Sunnyvale and Los Altos
in northern California. But Medfly maggots inside fruit and in the
ground were not affected by the pesticide.
   The Medflies are flown in, unhatched, every night from a
laboratory in Hawaii and are taken to an insect nursery at NASA's
Ames Research Center here to hatch.
   By the time the Medfly eradiction program ends early next year,
as many as 600 million sterile flies will have been released in a
47-square-mile area.
</TEXT>
