<FIRST>r w PM-AIDSCommission 1stLd-Writethru a0447 09-19 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Commission, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0447,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Koop Says ``Mean'' Attitude Towards AIDS Victims Must End</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2nd graf to set context of following quote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retiring Surgeon General C. Everett Koop is
urging that the new national AIDS commission try to turn around the
``mean-spiritedness'' some Americans show towards people with AIDS.
   And the outspoken physician suggests that those who act hatefully
toward victims of the incurable disease should be treated in the
same way by society.
   ``You could isolate the mean-spirited people in this country and
if the rest of society could treat them with the same repugnance
that those people treat persons with AIDS, I think that should be
your goal,'' Koop told the commission Monday.
   Koop, who has sought to heighten awareness about AIDS during his
tenure as the nation's top health adviser, also said the government
must find a better way to reach teen-agers who are ignoring AIDS
warnings.
   ``We know that sexual activity is rampant and that people of the
group I'm talking about are not listening to us,'' he said.
   Koop spoke to the National Commission on Acquired Immune
Deficiency Syndrome as it held its first day of testimony from
experts, including researchers, advocates and AIDS patients. The
panel was created by Congress last year to advise the president and
Capitol Hill on AIDS issues.
   The latest figures from the federal Centers for Disease Control
there are 105,990 Americans diagnosed as having AIDS. Of those, 60
percent are homosexual or bisexual males and 20 percent are
intravenous drug users.
   Koop caused an uproar with his October 1986 report on AIDS in
which he advocated sex education for young children. ``I still
believe in that very firmly,'' he told the commission.
   Parents, he said, ``should be joining with and not fighting the
schools in getting this done and getting it done properly.''
   ``I do believe if we taught sexuality in kind, loving,
compassionate, caring ways in a family context that we could raise a
generation of teen-agers to be less sexually active than the ones we
have today,'' he said.
   The panel, which met for the first time last month, will take up
the work of an earlier AIDS commission formed by President Reagan
and chaired by Adm. James Watkins. That panel called for a major
escalation of federal efforts to treat, cure and prevent AIDS and
for legislation to protect victims from discrimination.
   Commission member Belinda Mason, a 30-year-old mother of two who
contracted AIDS through a blood transfusion, said the panel can make
a difference in the lives of people with AIDS.
   ``We all want nothing more and nothing less than what all of you
take for granted today: a place to live, the right to have a job,
decent medical care and to lead their lives without invisible
barriers,'' she said.
   She said she would like to see the commission work for federal
protections against discrimination for people with AIDS and for
policies that get expensive drug treatments to those who need them.
   ``Compassion isn't going to happen because of a report we make or
an edict that somebody in Washington delivers,'' she said. ``It'll
begin in the small towns and quiet country throughout America where
people who live with AIDS and HIV infection are just like us,
because they are us.''
</TEXT>
