<FIRST>r a PM-LandlordConvicted     09-19 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Landlord Convicted,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Landlord Convicted in Fire Deaths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A landlord whose rooming house was
gutted in a fire that killed eight tenants has been convicted of
criminally negligent homicide for code violations that included a
door locked with a key from the inside.
   Two tenants were found dead at the door in the Jan. 15 blaze in
Yonkers.
   Supreme Court Justice Nicholas Colabella on Monday convicted
Frank Thomas on two counts of criminally negligent homicide and
acquitted the 67-year-old landlord on five others. An eighth count
was dismissed earlier.
   It was believed to be the first time in Westchester County that a
landlord was held liable for a death because of failure to comply
with safety codes. Thomas could receive one and one-third to four
years in prison on each count at sentencing Nov. 2.
   Thomas, who lives in New Rochelle, had been charged with the
eight deaths because of fire code violations that included a missing
fire door and a dead bolt on the front door that required a key from
the inside to unlock.
   He was convicted in the deaths of the two men, ages 52 and 61,
who were found at the locked door of the four-story building.
   Investigators said the fire started in the basement and was
caused by careless smoking by a drunken resident. The resident died
in the blaze.
   Defense attorney Neal Comer said the lack of case law on landlord
liability made an appeal ``absolutely necessary.''
   Comer had argued that the special lock had been requested by
tenants worried about the drug addicts hanging out on the steps. He
had also noted that several tenants had been drunk and said that
contributed to their inability to get out.
   District Attorney Carl Vergari's office seized records of city
agencies to determine why full inspections had not been done in as
much as a decade.
</TEXT>
