<FIRST>r a PM-CoalStrike     09-19 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coal Strike,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Fines UMW As Members Continue Demonstrations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEBANON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 100 miners occupied a Pittston Coal
Group control room for a third day today despite a $13.5 million
fine and a court order.
   Circuit Judge Donald McGlothlin imposed the fine against the
United Mine Workers on Monday for a variety of violations in July
and August during the strike begun against Pittston in April. He
also barred union members and supporters from impeding Pittston
operations.
   But on the other side of Copper Ridge, UMW members continued to
occupy the control room, where they barricaded themselves Sunday
with padlocks and steel cables.
   State Police made no immediate attempt to remove the
demonstrators _ 98 UMW members and a religious leader who carried
sleeping bags, toilet articles and enough food for about 10 days.
   Union leaders said the takeover would remain peaceful and
promised that no damage would be done to the plant, where coal is
sorted, cleaned and shipped.
   About 1,200 supporters rallied outside Monday, State Police
spokesman Charlie Vaughan said. ``Until something develops, we're
just observing and hoping nothing gets out of hand,'' Vaughan said.
   Pittston's 1,695 UMW employees from Virginia, West Virginia and
Kentucky are involved in the strike, which has become a cause for
organized labor across the country because the workers believe
Pittston is trying to break the union.
   The UMW now has been fined roughly $22 million by state and
federal judges for illegal demonstrations and acts of violence
against company property and employees.
   Late Monday, the National Labor Relations Board filed court
papers to have the sit-in declared unlawful. A court official said
the NLRB is seeking heavy fines, jail terms and an end to the $200
weekly strike benefits to members.
   A hearing was set for this afternoon in Big Stone Gap.
   The demonstration was designed to persuade Pittston Co. Chairman
Paul Douglas to come to the bargaining table and as a statement
against unfair labor laws, union officials said.
   Negotiations have been stalled for six weeks and no talks are
scheduled.
</TEXT>
