<FIRST>r a PM-Bush-ForeignPolicy 1stLd-Writethru a0453 09-19 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Foreign Policy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0453,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Not Ready to Set Date for Summit With Gorbachev</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts grafs 10-13, Senate Majority Leader, to include Mitchell
comments Monday.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, accusing the Soviet Union
of interfering in the Western Hemisphere by sending arms to
Nicaragua, says he's not ready to set a date for a summit meeting
with Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev.
   ``I feel under no rush on that subject,'' Bush told reporters
Monday at a news conference in Helena, Mont., before flying here for
the night.
   The president, on a two-day tour of western states celebrating
their 100th anniversary, also said he was not about to be pressured
on the issue of arms control by reports of a new Soviet proposal.
   Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze is expected to meet with
Bush at the White House on Thursday, before Shevardnadze's meeting
beginning the following day in Jackson Hole, Wyo., with Secretary of
State James A. Baker III.
   Bush conceded he had heard, but could not personally confirm,
speculation that Shevardnadze would bring with him a new proposal
for limiting long-range nuclear missiles.
   However, Bush said, ``We're not going to just react to his
proposals. We're going to be very interested and welcome them, but
we just simply cannot and will not keep reacting.''
   Bush denied he was dragging his feet on entering negotiations
with the Soviets on limiting ballistic missiles, although he
conceded this might be the perception because had focused attention
earlier in his administration ``into getting conventional force
stability'' in Europe.
   Asked about a summit with Gorbachev, Bush said he first wanted to
await results of the Baker-Shevardnadze meeting. A superpower summit
is expected to be one issue on the agenda.
   Suggesting that Soviet intentions still leave a lot to be
desired, Bush said: ``We have interests in this hemisphere where the
Soviets are continuing to send ... increased amounts of arms going
into Nicaragua right now over last year. That's not very good.
That's not a very kind and gentle approach to this hemisphere.''
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell said Monday that the Bush
administration has reacted timidly to events in Eastern Europe and
should actively support the forces of democratic change in the
communist world.
   He called on Bush to support the entry of communist nations into
Western economic institutions, ``once their internal reforms merit
such participation.''
   ``Now is the time for the United States to encourage and
capitalize upon the changes we have sought for so long,'' Mitchell
said in a Senate speech. ``The administration's timidity in the face
of these opportunities is puzzling and dismaying. Instead of
encouragement and engagment, the administration has adopted an
almost passive stance.''
   On another issue involving Latin America, Bush said he did not
fear for his safety or for that of his family because of reported
death threats from Colombian drug lords, saying he had confidence in
the Secret Service.
   He said there was ``no hard intelligence evidence'' of the
targeting of his family or of any other Americans by drug interests
in Colombia.
   ``But, clearly, any such action would, I think, just bring down
the total wrath of the American people and the American
government,'' he said.
   On another topic, Bush said he was not ready to restore normal
relations with the People's Republic of China, saying there has been
little apparent change in that government's attitudes since Chinese
troops fired on unarmed demonstrators in Beijing's Tiananmen Square
last spring.
   ``It's not a time for total normalcy,'' Bush said.
   His administration announced on Monday it intends to give
most-favored-nation trade status to Hungary. Bush praised Hungary's
communist government at his news conference for allowing thousands
of East Germans to flock across its borders en route to freedom in
West Germany.
   Asked whether he favors the reunification of Germany, Bush said:
``I would think it's a matter for the Germans to decide.''
   But, he added: ``If that (reunification) was worked out between
the Germanys, I do not think we should view that as bad for Western
interests.''
   Bush, returning to Soviet issues, said he was not ready to relax
trade restrictions on the Soviet Union like he is doing for Hungary.
   He said that, despite some reported progress, the Soviet Union
still is not permitting free emigration of Soviet Jews and other
minorities.
   ``I think things are improving, but I think as long as someone is
held in a country against their will because they can't get out, it
is a matter of human concern,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
