<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--DrugWarnings     09-19 0130</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Drug Warnings,0134</SECOND>
<HEAD>Employers Required To Post Drug Warnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employers in San Francisco will soon be
required to post warnings about the perils of drug use.
   The Board of Supervisors unanimously adopted an ordinance Monday
night requiring such notices. It will take effect next week after a
procedural second reading.
   The warnings will be displayed in offices, businesses and other
workplaces. They will contain information such as ``even one line of
cocaine has been known to kill the user'' and ``marijuana can cause
serious psychotic problems.''
   The ordinance contains no enforcement mechanism or penalties for
noncompliance.
   The legislation is similar to state laws that require warnings
about alcohol at places where liquor is sold. The postings will also
include a list of drug treatment centers.
</TEXT>
