<FIRST>r i PM-China-Deng 2ndLd-Writethru a0523 09-19 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Deng, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0523,a0475,0720</SECOND>
<HEAD>In Second Appearance In Three Months, Deng Laughs At Reports Of His
Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf after 4th pvs: `Deng's re-emergence ...' to UPDATE
with television report; picks up 5th pvs: `Ito, who...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's senior leader Deng Xiaoping today laughed
about foreign reports of his death and spoke of how his reappearance
in public had helped the Hong Kong stock exchange.
   Deng, 85, also told Japanese lawmaker Masayoshi Ito that among
the politicians he most respected were former President Nixon, Henry
Kissinger and Japan's former Prime Minister Kakuei Tanaka. All three
men led the way in improving their countries' relations with China.
   The meeting at the Great Hall of the People was the second for
China's reclusive leader in three days.
   On Saturday, Deng appeared in public for the first time in three
months when he held talks with Chinese-American physicist T.D. Lee.
   Deng's re-emergence after the long absence has, for the moment,
dispelled speculation that he is gravely ill with cancer and may not
have long to live.
   The nationally televised evening news showed Deng walking unaided
to meet Ito, whom he called ``an old friend'' as the two shook hands.
   Ito, who heads Japan's Parliamentarians League for Japan-China
Friendship, opened the meeting by commenting that Deng appeared to
be in the same good health as when they met a year ago, despite
reports that he was seriously ill.
   Deng replied that the foreign mass media had already declared him
dead or very sick. Such reports caused the Hong Kong stock market to
fall, he said, adding that the market had recovered when he
reappeared Saturday with Lee, a Nobel Prize-winning physicist.
   ``In reality I have always been healthy,'' Deng said.
   Yoshiro Hayashi, a Japanese lawmaker and member of the
delegation, provided details of the meeting to the Japanese press.
   Deng praised the ``high political consciousness'' of Nixon,
Kissinger and Tanaka, who helped bring about the normalization of
relations with China even though China was then in the throes of the
leftist Cultural Revolution.
   Kissinger, then National Security Adviser, made a secret trip to
Beijing in 1971 to set the stage for Nixon's dramatic visit in
February 1972.
   Tanaka, who like Nixon was later to be forced out of office by
scandal, traveled to China in September 1972 to normalize relations
between the two countries.
   Drawing an apparent comparison with the leaders of the West
today, Deng criticized the participants of the recent seven-nation
summit of industrialized nations in Paris for calling on China to
cease its crackdown on those who sought democratic reforms.
   He also said Japan's attitude has been different from that of the
United States, which has been vocal in calling for China to end its
suppression of dissent and ensure the human rights of its citizens.
   Japan, like the United States, has curtailed high-level official
contacts and suspended talks on new loans since the army killed
hundreds of unarmed civilians June 3-4 in clearing central Beijing
of pro-democracy protesters.
   But Japan has also muffled its public criticisms of the Chinese
government's actions.
   Deng stressed the importance of China's relations with its
biggest trading partner outside Hong Kong, and said ties should
continue despite China's recent domestic turmoil.
   Ito, the highest-level Japanese official to visit China since
June, said the June events had put a damper on relations between the
two countries and his mission was to find out how these problems
could be overcome.
   Since arriving Sunday, Ito has also met with Premier Li Peng,
Communist Party General Secretary Jiang Zemin and other top leaders.
He was to return to Japan later today.
   On Saturday, Deng said the crushed pro-democracy movement ``has
taught us a major lesson ... After the turmoil, all of us have
become sober-minded.''
   Deng stressed China's commitment to the market-oriented reforms
he initiated 10 years ago, but added that some officials ``did not
pay enough attention to ideological and political developments.''
   It was an apparent reference to ousted party chief Zhao Ziyang,
who has been accused of encouraging ``bourgeois liberalization,'' or
acceptance of Western liberal ideas, in pushing ahead with rapid
reform without duly considering ideological matters.
</TEXT>
