<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1113EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Rape-Marriage     09-19 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rape-Marriage,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Recants Rape Charge, Plans to Marry Defendant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEDIA, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors dropped rape charges after a woman
announced in court she plans to marry the man she accused of
attacking her.
   Karen Drake, 25, in June testified she was ``pinned down'' and
raped by Donald Farmer, 31. But on Monday, she said she plans to
marry him Sept. 30.
   Assistant District Attorney Colleen Marsini moved to dismiss the
charges because Ms. Drake would not testify.
   ``She's in love and they're getting married,'' defense attorney
David Breen said. ``She posted bail for him and paid his legal fees.
It's the first time I've ever had a victim pay my fee.''
   While rape and related offenses were withdrawn, Farmer did plead
guilty to stealing a diamond ring from Ms. Drake and received two
years' probation.
   Breen said the woman met Farmer at a tattoo parlor and set up a
dinner date.
   When Farmer arrived at her apartment, her friend gave him a
prescription drug, which she blames for his aggressive behavior,
Breen said.
   ``He's now undergoing drug rehabilitation,'' Breen said.
</TEXT>
