<FIRST>u i PM-Egypt-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0519 09-19 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Egypt-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0519,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir and Rabin Meet, Coalition in Dispute Over Egyptian Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede CAIRO</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads thruout to UPDATE with today's developments, removes outdated
material. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and Defense
Minister Yitzhak Rabin met today to discuss Rabin's trip to Egypt,
and the government's two main parties appeared locked in a dispute
over Egypt's plan to sponsor Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
   Rabin left Shamir's office without speaking to reporters after an
hour-long meeting. He spent seven hours in Cairo on Monday.
   Shamir's spokesman Avi Pazner refused to divulge details of the
meeting, but repeated Shamir's remark Monday that he could not
maintain his governing coalition between his rightist Likud bloc and
the center-left Labor Party ``at any price.''
   Israeli newspapers reported that Labor leaders were negotiating
secretly with smaller religious parties to try to form a governing
coalition if the current coalition falls.
   The controversy centers on Likud's opposition to Mubarak's
proposal for breaking a stalemate in the Middle East peace process.
   Shamir is also concerned about Rabin's remarks at a Cairo news
conference hinting at Israeli recognition of an indirect PLO role in
peace talks, Israeli radio stations reported.
   Israel officially refuses to deal with the Palestine Liberation
Organization, which it views as a terror group.
   In those remarks, Rabin said Israel agreed to Egypt arranging an
Israeli-Palestinian meeting. He said Egypt could put together the
Palestinian delegation ``after coordinating with various elements .
.. including Israel.''
   Palestinian leaders interpreted Rabin's remarks as consenting to
Egypt's suggestion that the delegation include Arabs deported by
Israel from the occupied territories.
   That would be a compromise between Israel and the PLO, because
Israel wants to include only Palestinians from the West Bank and
Gaza and the PLO wants Palestinians from outside.
   Shamir did not respond directly today to Rabin's remarks, except
to hint that his fractious governing coalition, put together last
December, was in trouble.
   ``I personally would like to see the coalition remain, but I must
say that unity is not worth any price,'' he said.
   Shamir also is under heavy pressure from Likud hard-liners who
oppose Egypt's plan because it urges Israel to accept the principle
of trading territory for peace.
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens tried to play down the crisis today.
``We have coalition crises here an average of about once a month, so
we need another crisis today,'' Arens said.
   Two peace plans were discussed at the Cairo meeting, Rabin and
Mubarak said in separate news conferences Monday.
   According to Israel's plan, approved by the government in May,
1.7 million Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip would elect
delegates to negotiate with Israel on an interim autonomy solution,
with the final status of the territories to be decided later.
   Mubarak's plan is more specific. It calls for Israel to trade
land for peace and requires that the building of Jewish settlements
be halted in the occupied lands, which Israel seized in the 1967
Middle East war.
   Labor supports Mubarak's 10-point memorandum as way of breaking
the impasse in the peace process, and it is inclined to agree to
talk with the deportees or with compromise candidates such as one
defined by Rabin as ``a (Palestinian) professor from the United
States.''
   Mubarak said he will conduct the next round of peace talks in New
York, where he is to meet with Labor leader Shimon Peres and also
with Arens.
   The Israeli Cabinet will discuss the Egyptian initiative in two
to three weeks, when both ministers return to the country, Rabin
said.
</TEXT>
