<FIRST>u i PM-Auschwitz-Convent 4thLd-Writethru a0565 09-19 0822</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auschwitz-Convent, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0565,0846</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vatican Supports Moving Nuns from Auschwitz Site</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 6th pvs, `The agreement...' to UPDATE
with Glemp comment in Britain. Pick up 7th pvs, `The archbishop...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican said today that a Roman Catholic
convent of Carmelite nuns near the Auschwitz death camp in Poland
should be moved to another site, as Jewish groups have sought.
   Breaking its silence on an issue that has severely strained
Jewish-Catholic relations, the Vatican said it would help to pay for
a prayer center in which the nuns would live.
   Jewish leaders in the United States applauded the statement and
said it would improve Jewish-Catholic relations.
   A February 1987 accord between Jewish and Roman Catholic
representatives stipulated that the nuns would be moved to the
prayer center from a convent just outside Auschwitz. Jews have
objected to their presence at a site where 2.5 million Jews were
murdered by the Nazis during World War II.
   However, the Polish primate, Cardinal Josef Glemp, has called for
renegotiating the agreement and said the Polish church did not have
the money to build a new home for the nuns.
   The agreement, signed in Geneva, called for the nuns to have been
moved by Feb. 22, but the deadline passed and the nuns remained.
   Glemp, on a 24-hour visit to Bristol, England, to consecrate a
Polish Catholic church, indicated he had not read the Vatican
statement.
   Based on what reporters had told him about the statement, he
said: ``this would seem to be a forceful resolution of the problem
and I don't think that would be a very positive way of resolving
it.''
   But Glemp also said ``there is a possibility that the nuns could
move elsewhere.''
   ``But if they were to be moved, this should be done with charity
because even if we were to transfer these nuns to a different
location, that would also be crossing out their rights,'' he said.
   The archbishop of Krakow, Cardinal Franciszek Macharski, said
last month that the church was abrogating the agreement since it
could not be fulfilled in an atmosphere of aggressive demands.
   The Vatican's Commission for Religious Relations with Judaism
said in a communique today that it was pleased with a declaration
from Poland's bishops earlier this month that Roman Catholics and
Jewish groups should resume talks on building a prayer center in
which the nuns would live.
   ``The Holy See is convinced that such a center would contribute
in an important way to development of good relations between
Christians and Jews,'' the communique said.
   The Rev. Pier Francesco Fumagalli, secretary of the commission,
told reporters he expected the Geneva declaration would be honored.
But he added ``I can't forsee what will happen in Poland.''
   He said the questions of exactly where, when and how the prayer
center would be built were being left to Polish church officials.
   Asked whether the pope had approved the communique, a Vatican
spokesman, the Rev. Giovanni D'Ercole, noted the statement had been
published in the official Vatican bulletin _ implying papal
acceptance.
   Elan Steinberg, executive director of the World Jewish Congress,
said that because of the Vatican communique, his organization had
decided to recommend to its constituencies around the world that
they suspend their freeze on contacts with the Vatican.
   ``We welcome this very important step in restoring the good word
of the church. It's time to move on and implement the agreement,''
he said.
   Rabbi Marvin Hier, dean of the Simon Weisenthal Center in Los
Angeles, said the communique was a major policy reversal by the
Vatican that would remove a stumbling block in Catholic-Jewish
relations.
   ``The issue was never over the rights of non-Jews to pray at
Auschwitz,'' Hier said. ``The issue was the building of permanent
structures at Auschwitz.''
   An estimated 2.5 million of the 4 million victims of
Auschwitz-Birkenau were Jewish, and the convent's opponents argue
that it is deeply offensive that Christian religious symbols tower
over what is in effect their gravesite.
   Glemp has called the Geneva accord ``offensive,'' and he provoked
further controversy with remarks deemed by many to be anti-Semitic.
   An estimated 1.5 million Christians also were killed at Auschwitz.
   The proposal to remove the convent founded in 1984 just outside
the Auschwitz fence has found little sympathy among Poles. They
argue that the nuns are not harming anyone and that thousands of the
victims at Auschwitz were Polish political prisoners, including many
priests and nuns.
   The issue has also caused divisions among cardinals.
   Last weekend, Cardinal John J. O'Connor, archbishop of New York,
said he supported Jewish efforts to move the nuns and that he was
exploring talking to Pope John Paul II about the dispute.
   Jewish groups have asked the Polish-born pope to step in and
settle the controversy. But until today's announcement, the pope had
left it up to the Polish church to settle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
