<FIRST>r a AM-ZaccaroHearing     09-19 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zaccaro Hearing,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vermont Supreme Court Hears John Zaccaro Drug Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Zaccaro, the son of former vice
presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro, cited sloppy police
tactics when he asked the Vermont Supreme Court to overturn his
conviction on a cocaine charge.
   ``The issue is how freely the government can enter a house in
disguise,'' Kathleen Sullivan, Zaccaro's lawyer, said Monday during
oral arguments.
   Zaccaro, 26, was convicted last year of selling a quarter gram of
cocaine to an undercover police woman at his off-campus apartment in
Middlebury in 1986. He served his sentence, but has appealed the
conviction in an effort to clear his record.
   The court is not expected to rule before December.
   Sullivan, a Harvard law professor, said state police should have
found a witness or come up with solid evidence before sending an
undercover officer to Zaccaro's home while he was a student at
Middlebury College.
   Prosecutor Susan Harritt contended before the court that police
did not violate Zaccaro's rights because the undercover officer was
invited into his home, clearly stated her intention to buy cocaine
and made the purchase without disguising her identity.
   ``The state sees this in a fundamentally different way,'' she
said. ``This case, in fact, does not involve a search. If the court
believes that a search did take place, no warrant was needed because
the officer was invited into the home.''
   Zaccaro, who recently opened a New York pasta shop, appeared at
ease during the hearing, talking and laughing with lawyers. He would
not comment before or after the hearing, other than to compliment
his lawyers and express confidence the court would be fair.
   Zaccaro was sentenced to a term of one to five years, with all
but four months suspended. He served the four months in a so-called
``house arrest'' program that allowed him to live in a
$1,500-a-month apartment with maid service and cable television.
   The trial followed legal wrangling over whether Zaccaro was
selectively prosecuted due to his mother's fame. Sullivan's state
Supreme Court brief again raised the claim, but she did not cover
the issue during oral arguments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
