<FIRST>r i AM-MotherTeresa     09-19 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mother Teresa,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Teresa's Illness May Curtail Her Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CALCUTTA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After she recovers from a heart attack,
Mother Teresa will have to give up the hectic schedule that earned
her a Nobel Peace Prize and adapt to a slower pace, her doctors said
Tuesday.
   ``Her heart is old and she's not young,'' Dr. George Lombardi, an
infectious disease specialist from the United States, told a news
conference. ``At least for the time being, she will have to change
her lifestyle.''
   A medical bulletin issued late Tuesday said Mother Teresa's
condition is improving and she has had no chest pains since Monday.
Her temperature also has been normal, one of her physicians said.
   Despite recent health problems, the 79-year-old Roman Catholic
nun has traveled the world incessantly to offer care and comfort to
the poor.
   Mother Teresa, who won the 1979 Nobel Peace Prize for her work,
suffered a heart attack on Sept. 8, three days after she was
admitted to Woodlands Nursing Home with a high fever and acute
vomiting.
   Doctors attached a temporary pacemaker, but it was removed after
she developed chest pains. She has been taking steroids since then,
they said.
   ``Her temprature has been controlled, but the problem remains
with her intermittent chest pains. We are rather concerned about
that. Otherwise, she is comfortable,'' said Dr. Rajen Watts.
   ``The angina pain is serious but not critical,'' he said.
   Watts said Mother Teresa's temperature is now 97.6 and that she
is conscious, eating well and resting comfortably.
   Watts also said a viral infection that triggered the fever now is
under control. He said doctors still do not know the cause and are
awaiting results from blood samples sent to the Tropical Disease
Institute.
   ``The virus, however, has affected her heart,'' he said.
   Doctors also said the frail nun had developed a secondary
infection, which also has not been diagnosed.
   ``We are hopeful that this will go in a couple of days,''
Lombardi said.
   Although they gave no time frame, doctors said Mother Teresa's
recovery probably will take longer than the normal four to six weeks.
   The Yugoslav-born nun developed chest pains and a high fever
Thursday, a week after the heart attack. Doctors said the setback
may have been caused partly by a steady stream of visitors to the
hospital's intensive care unit. On Monday, doctors said no one would
be allowed to see her.
   Mother Teresa founded the Missionaries of Charity in October 1950
in an abandoned hostel donated by the city. The order, formally
recognized by the Vatican in 1965, expanded and now has 3,000 nuns
working in 87 countries.
</TEXT>
