<FIRST>r a PM-ZaccaroAppeal     09-19 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Zaccaro Appeal,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vermont's High Court Hears John Zaccaro Drug Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for John Zaccaro Jr. asked
Vermont's Supreme Court to throw out his cocaine-peddling
conviction, arguing that police set up the undercover buy on the
basis of campus rumors, not hard evidence.
   ``The issue is how freely the government can enter a house in
disguise,'' Kathleen Sullivan argued Monday. ``This undercover was
arranged solely on the basis of rumor, nothing like hard evidence,
nothing like reasonable suspicion.''
   The 26-year-old son of former vice presidential candidate
Geraldine Ferraro was convicted last year of selling a quarter gram
of cocaine to an undercover police woman at his off-campus apartment
in 1986 while a student at Middlebury College.
   Zaccaro served four months' house arrest in a $1,500-a-month
apartment with maid service and cable television but is seeking to
clear his record.
   Sullivan said State Police should have found a witness or located
solid evidence before sending an undercover officer into Zaccaro's
home.
   But Assistant Attorney General Susan Harritt countered that
police did not violate Zaccaro's rights because the undercover
officer was invited into his home, clearly stated her intention to
buy cocaine and made the purchase without disguising her identity.
   ``(The officer) said, `I understand I can buy some drugs from
you,' and he said, `Sure, come on in,''' Harritt told the court.
``She was not asked to explain anything about herself. He didn't ask
her whether or not she was police.''
   Associate Justice John Dooley told Harritt he was troubled about
some aspects of the probe, noting that rumors abound on college
campuses.
   Zaccaro, who has recently opened a New York pasta shop, declined
to comment other than to compliment his lawyers and express
confidence the court would render a fair decision.
   His lawyers have argued also that Zaccaro was selectively
prosecuted because of his mother's fame.
</TEXT>
