<HEAD>Seattle Holds Mayoral Primary</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with balloting under way; PICKS
UP 5th graf, pvs, `Royer, who ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID AMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters went to the polls today in a 13-way primary
that could bring a city councilman one step closer to becoming
Seattle's first black mayor.
   Norm Rice, who is black, was considered the frontrunner in the
non-partisan race, in which the top two vote-getters will advance to
the general election. The councilman's opponent in November was
expected to be city Attorney Doug Jewett or former King County
Executive Randy Revelle.
   Bob Bruce, King County election superintendent, predicted 103,000
of Seattle's 295,000 registered voters would go to the polls in the
race to replace Mayor Charles Royer. That's a moderate turnout of
about 35 percent.
   Royer, who beat Rice four years ago, is not seeking a fourth term
and has accepted a post at Harvard University's Kennedy School of
Government.
   Rice, 46, is a former broadcast reporter, Urban League official
and a banker. He said he jumped into the race because of what he
called a divisive anti-school busing initiative. The measure will be
on the November ballot.
   Jewett is co-sponsor of the initiative, and backers say he can
ride it into the mayor's office.
   In Spokane, where President Bush was to help celebrate the state
centennial today, two City Council members were favored to advance
to the November general election.
   In Tacoma, where Mayor Doug Sutherland is stepping down after two
terms and eyeing a gubernatorial bid, six candidates were vying for
two runoff spots.
