<FIRST>u w AM-Hugo-Pentagon     09-19 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Pentagon,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Assesses Hugo Damage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon said Tuesday that some of its
facilities had sustained ``very heavy damage'' from Hurricane Hugo
and that it was evacuating about 600 U.S. workers and dependents
from a submarine center in the Bahamas as a precaution.
   ``Virtually every structure received some damage, some of it
severe,'' at the U.S. Naval Station at Roosevelt Roads in Puerto
Rico, Pentagon spokesman Fred Hoffman told reporters.
   No significant injuries were reported, he added.
   The spokesman said a lack of full information meant that no cost
estimates of the damage had been drawn up.
   Hugo hit northeastern Puerto Rico and then skirted its populous
northern coast Monday. Hurricane warnings were in effect for the
southern Bahamas.
   Since Sunday, the storm also has caused widespread damage in
Guadeloupe, Antigua, St. Kitts, Montserrat and the U.S. and British
Virgin Islands.
   The Navy's airfield at the Roosevelt Roads station was closed
overnight, but has since been reopened. Many of the runway's lights
were damaged, Hoffman said.
   He said the military was evacuating approximately 600 people from
the Naval Undersea Center on Andros Island in the Bahamas as a
precautionary measure.
   The evacuees are a mix of U.S. government personnel, civilians
and dependents of those who work at the center, which focuses on
anti-submarine warfare, officials said.
   Hoffman said an Air Force satellite tracking center on Antigua
``suffered very heavy damage'' while a solar observatory at Ramey
Air Force Base in Puerto Rico was also hit.
   The spokesman said U.S. forces were participating in offering
airlift support of relief cargos to St. John in the U.S. Virgin
Islands and Antigua in the British Virgin Islands.
</TEXT>
