<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1348EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Auction-TeddyBear     09-19 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auction-Teddy Bear,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teddy Bear Sold for Record $86,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An under-cuddled German teddy bear fetched a world
record $86,000 at an auction Tuesday, more than four times the
previous highest price for a teddy bear and 60 times its catalogue
estimate, Sotheby's said.
   ``When I told the owner the news, he said: `I think that works
out at 1,000 pounds ($1,570) a hair.' He was very pleased and very
happy,'' said Sotheby's appraiser Bunny Campione.
   The two-tone bear, made by German manufacturer Steiff in 1920,
has unusually large eyes that ``make it look a little forlorn'' and
is in such good condition ``it doesn't look as if it has been
cuddled very much,'' she said.
   Mrs. Campione said the bear had been expected to sell for up to
$7,800 but had earlier been listed in an auction house catalogue at
$1,100 to $1,400.
   ``There is no justifiable reason why it made so much money,'' she
said in a telephone interview.
   The previous highest auction price for a teddy bear was $19,000,
paid at a Christie's auction in London on May 18 for a Steiff bear
made between 1906 and 1909 for Princess Xenia, a cousin of Czar
Nicholas II.
   Sotheby's record-busting bear is 24 inches long, has plush fur in
blond and brown, amber-and-black glass eyes measuring about 1 inch
in diameter, swivel joints, a humped back and widely spaced ears.
   The buyer, represented by a British agent, insisted on anonymity.
The bear had belonged to an unidentified British man who inherited
it from his grandmother, Mrs. Campione said.
   ``The grandmother considered him (the bear) to be very much her
own and kept him away from the children who were allowed to see him
but not to play with him,'' she said.
   Mrs. Campione, a fine-doll expert, said she was baffled by the
sale price for a bear that was hardly rare.
   ``A few thousand were made in 1920 instead of a few million,''
but it is in unusually ``superb condition,'' she said. ``Most of
them are cuddled or kissed on the nose so much that the nose gets
dented in, or get dragged around the garden by children.''
   She speculated that the buyer may want the bear as a prototype
for limited edition.
   At the first teddy bear auction organized by Mrs. Campione at
Sotheby's in 1982, the most expensive teddy went for $630.
   Richard Steiff's lovable creations took the world by storm at the
Leipzig toy fair in 1903, and valuable teddies are now almost
exclusively made by Steiff at the village of Giengen in southern
Germany.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
