<DOCNO> AP890919-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1354EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Spain-Plane 3rdLd-Writethru   09-19 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spain-Plane, 3rd Ld - Writethru,a0611,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plane Forced to Land by Gunman</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with all passengers, crew freed,
CORRECTS make of aircraft; picks up 4th pvs: An official.. .</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS PALMAS, Canary Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunman forced a Moroccan
passenger plane flying across the Western Sahara to land today on
Grand Canary island, officials said.
   The police officer at Gando Airport said the two crew members and
six passengers were allowed to leave the ATR-42 twin-engine
turboprop about two hours after it touched down on this Spanish
archipelago at 2:45 p.m.
   The unidentified gunman gave himself up about six hours after the
aircraft landed, said the officer, speaking on condition of
anonymity. He said no concessions were made to the gunman but had no
information on a possible motive for the hijacking.
   The Royal Air Maroc aircraft was initially identified as a Fokker
by police.
   An official in the Gando Airport control tower, who would not
give his name, said by telephone that the gunman had demanded to
talk with the local representative of the Moroccan national airline
in Las Palmas.
   An attendant at the Royal Air Maroc office in Las Palmas said the
flight had left the eastern town of Smara in the Moroccan-occupied
Western Sahara on a scheduled domestic flight west to the city of El
Aaiun.
   Grand Canary Island is 135 miles west of the Western Sahara in
the Atlantic Ocean.
   The incident occurred prior to the first official visit to Spain
on Sunday by Moroccan King Hassan II.
   Spain abandoned the Western Sahara in 1975, and Hassan sent
thousands of civilians to occupy the area. The Western Sahara is
also claimed by the Polisario National Liberation Front, which has
been waging a desert guerrilla war against the Moroccan army since
1975.
</TEXT>
