<FIRST>r a PM-SilverHeist     09-19 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Silver Heist,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Arrest Suspect in 1.25-Ton Silver Heist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Montana man has been charged with stealing
1.25 tons of silver shaped like Hershey Kisses from a Nevada mine
where he once worked, authorities said today.
   Sheriff James McIntosh said officials hoped to get arrest
warrants today or Wednesday for two other Montana people wanted in
the Trinity Mine heist Aug. 26.
   John Aiden, 22, of Billings, Mont., was arrested Saturday and
jailed on $105,000 bail on charges of embezzlement and conspiracy,
McIntosh said.
   The $200,000-plus cache of partially processed silver is still
missing.
   The heist occurred when two shotgun-toting masked robbers bound
two mine employees with duct tape and then took more than an hour in
the middle of the night to haul the 1.25 tons of silver into a
waiting pickup.
   The robbers then left spikes in the road to flatten tires of
pursuers.
   Police immediately theorized the heist was commited by people
with inside information.
   Authorities were led to Aiden based on interviews with past and
present mine workers that revealed several small silver thefts at
the mine, McIntosh said.
   ``Once information about some other minor silver thefts began
surfacing, people started getting nervous and talking,'' McIntosh
said.
   Officials gave lie detector tests to past and present employees
of the mine, 90 miles northeast of Reno.
</TEXT>
