<FIRST>u w PM-US-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0452 09-19 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0452,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDs: Top 8 grafs new with Baker comments on Soviet aid to Nicaragua.
Picks up 7th graf pvs, The State Department.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III said
today continued Soviet weapons shipments to Nicaragua will be a
priority issue when he meets later this week with Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard Shevardnadze in Wyoming.
   ``We're a little disappointed in what's going on down there,''
Baker said, referring to the role of the Soviets and other East bloc
countries in building up the Sandinista military arsenal.
   Baker told a news conference that most of the Soviet weaponry
arrives in Nicaragua via third countries. He added that the Soviets
could put a stop to the practice if they so chose.
   President Bush said Monday in Helena, Mont., that the increased
flow of Soviet bloc arms to Nicaragua indicates ``not a very kind
and gentle approach to this hemisphere.''
   Bush spoke after the State Department said Soviet bloc weapons
deliveries to Nicaragua have continued at a rate of more than one a
week this year, despite a cease-fire dating back 18 months.
   Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev pledged early this year to cut
off weapons deliveries to the Sandinistas. But administration
officials, insisting on anonymity, said Soviet weapons were spotted
last week being loaded onto a Nicaraguan vessel at a port in Cuba.
The equipment has since been delivered to Nicaragua.
   The officials declined comment on a published report that the
weapons consisted of three torpedo-carrying boats and four Mi-24
Hind helicopters.
   The leak of that sensitive information seemed calculated to
influence the upcoming meeting Friday and Saturday between Baker and
Shevardnadze. One purpose of the meeting is to lay the groundwork
for a summit meeting between Gorbachev and President Bush.
   The State Department said Monday that Soviet bloc deliveries to
Nicaragua for the first eight months of this year totaled about $350
million. The equipment weighed an estimated 12,000 tons and was
delivered during 41 ship visits to Nicaraguan ports, the State
Department said, adding that the value of such shipments during all
of 1988 was $515 million.
   Earlier Monday, spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler expressed
irritation that overall deliveries to Nicaragua appear to have
increased this year compared with a similar period in 1988.
   Officials had expected a decline since the Sandinista government
and the Nicaraguan resistance reached agreement on a truce in March
1988. Although there have been some violations of the truce, the
level of fighting is down sharply from 1987.
   Ms. Tutwiler said the level of Soviet bloc shipments is well
beyond the legitimate defense needs of Nicaragua.
   ``It is inexplainable to us why the East Bloc feels that it must
provide Nicaragua with even more weapons while a cease-fire is in
effect than it provided the Nicaraguans when they were actively
engaged with Contra forces,'' she said.
   ``The basic pattern in recent years has been transshipment of
Soviet weapons through Cuba,'' Ms. Tutwiler said. ``This year, the
weapons out of Cuba has increased dramatically.''
   Ms. Tutwiler also said Cuba and Nicaragua continue to supply arms
to the leftist FMLN guerrillas in El Salvador.
   ``The FMLN has come to rely chiefly on Soviet bloc weapons,'' she
said, adding that such activity defies agreements signed by Central
American presidents which call for an end to outside support for
insurgencies in the region.
</TEXT>
