<FIRST>r a AM-Rape-Marriage     09-19 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rape-Marriage,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wedding Plans Halt Rape Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEDIA, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They met in a tattoo parlor and the next night
she accused him of raping her. Then she hired a lawyer for him and
posted his bail, and now they plan to get married.
   Karen Drake now blames pills given to Donald Farmer the night of
the May 24 attack.
   ``It wasn't him,'' Ms. Drake said. ``I've talked to people who
know him. And I know him now and he's not the kind of person who
would do that. It was a drug-induced stupor the way he acted that
night.''
   Assistant District Attorney Colleen Marsini moved Monday to
dismiss charges in Delaware County, just outside Philadelphia,
because Ms. Drake would not testify.
   ``I think he's using her,'' Ms. Marsini said Tuesday.
   Ms. Drake, 25, testified in June that she protested when she was
``pinned down'' and raped by Farmer, 31. But on Monday, she said she
plans to marry him Sept. 30 in a civil ceremony.
   ``My mother is not opposed to our marriage. Both of my parents,
deep down, love Donnie a lot. And I get along very well with his
parents and his two children,'' she said.
   ``Both Donnie and I have a lot in common,'' she said. ``We're
both from Virginia, and we both were born in February.''
   While rape and related offenses were withdrawn, Farmer did plead
guilty to stealing a diamond ring from Ms. Drake and was placed on
two years' probation.
   Defense attorney David Breen said Ms. Drake hired him June 3 to
represent Farmer, two days after Farmer's preliminary hearing on the
rape charges.
   ``She posted bail for him and paid his legal fees. It's the first
time I've ever had a victim pay my fee,'' Breen said.
   Ms. Drake said she met Farmer May 23 at a Philadelphia tattoo
parlor, where she had gone with a friend, and set up a date the next
night.
   ``I have green eyes and he convinced me to get a tattoo on my
shoulder of a green eye with a tear,'' Ms. Drake said.
   During the June 1 preliminary hearing, Ms. Drake testified that
Farmer ``violated me.''
   ``I was scared to death. I couldn't move,'' she testified, saying
he pinned her down.
   ``I was too scared to scream,'' she said during that hearing.
   But Ms. Drake said she and Farmer have lived together since she
posted his bail after she found out her roommate had given him
``pills that caused the attack.''
   Ms. Drake said she also received a call from Farmer's ex-wife,
who said rape was out of character for him.
   ``Immediately, I started to cry. I went with her the next day to
the jail. When Donnie came out he was so shocked. He sat down. He
took my two hands. He didn't remember anything that happened that
night. He held my hand and said: `If I did this to you, I deserve to
die.'''
   Breen said Farmer is undergoing drug rehabilitation.
   Ms. Marsini said the drug Farmer is said to have taken the night
of the alleged attack is a painkiller that toxicologists told her is
a depressant that would not cause a violent reaction.
   ``She's recanted her testimony. She said she created the
situation and caused the problem,'' she said. ``She said he is a
victim of circumstances.
   ``He's playing on her sensitivity. She's very vulnerable.''
   Ms. Drake discounted that evaluation.
   ``That's her job to say that. But that's not the case,'' Ms.
Drake said.
   She said that when the charges were dismissed Monday, Farmer had
a smile ``as big as the sky.''
   ``He said, `I feel like I have 100 pounds off of my shoulder,
Karen. It's over. We can finally have a life.'''
</TEXT>
