<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1438EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-SovietRefugees     09-19 0724</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet Refugees,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kremlin Official Says Those Leaving USSR Aren't Refugees</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Teton-Tete-a-Tete, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kremlin's top human rights official took
issue Tuesday with the U.S. definition of Soviet emigres as
refugees, saying it creates ``friction'' in superpower relations at
a time when his government is allowing record numbers of citizens to
leave.
   Yuri Reshetov, chief of the Department of Humanitarian Affairs
and Cultural Relations at the Soviet foreign ministry, was in
Washington for talks with the State Department preparatory to the
meeting later this week between Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze and Secretary of State James A. Baker III.
   Reshetov said the agenda, at the request of the U.S. side, would
include discussion of the cases of several hundred Soviet Jews
denied permission to emigrate. The two sides will also discuss
exchange programs for psychiatrists and law enforcement officers, he
said.
   In an unusual appearance before the National Conference on Soviet
Jewry, Reshetov promised that Soviet Jews would be allowed to
practice their religion freely or leave the country if they want.
   New draft laws on freedom of religion and on emigration seek to
``create the best possibilities for those who want to live in the
Soviet Union. ... But for those who, for some reason, are unhappy
and want to leave, the best civilized conditions should be
created,'' he said.
   In the first eight months of the year, 127,000 Soviets were
allowed to emigrate, he said, about a third of whom came to the
United States as refugees whose expenses were paid by the U.S.
government.
   Speaking to reporters after his speech, Reshetov criticized the
U.S. policy of classifying the Soviet emigres as refugees, saying it
runs ``contrary to the definition of refugee'' accepted by the
international community.
   ``Calling these people refugees creates a considerable,
additional friction'' in U.S.-Soviet relations. ``We are trying to
do our best to solve the situation but then ... we're (portrayed as)
some enemy of mankind from whom all the people are fleeing. It's not
a good thing,'' Reshetov said.
   Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger, addressing the
conference before Reshetov, defended the U.S. plan to allot 50,000
of the 125,000 worldwide refugee slots in fiscal year 1990 to Soviet
emigres.
   Despite the unprecedented surge of Soviets allowed to emigrate,
and the recent improvement in the lives of those staying behind,
there are still hundreds denied permission to leave and a wave of
anti-Semitism has surfaced as a result of the glasnost policies of
free expression, Eagleburger said.
   ``Given the history'' of hundreds of years of officially
sanctioned anti-Semitism, ``tens of thousands of Soviet Jews are
turning to the United States,'' Eagleburger said. ``What Soviet Jews
are looking for now is a plcae where they can be themselves. They
are not economic migrants.''
   The United States is ``a victim of our success'' now that the
Soviets have acceded to years of U.S. demands to allow free
emigration, he said. Unfortunately, budget constraints place a limit
on the number of Soviets the United States can absorb and other
countries, such as Australia, Canada and Israel, should share the
burden, he added.
   Eagleburger promised that Baker would bring up U.S. concerns
about anti-Semitism in his meeting with Shevardnadze and would press
for enactment of legislation that will institutionalize the reforms.
   Once such laws are adopted, he said, the United States will lift
certain trade restrictions on the Soviet Union.
   Reshetov said the Kremlin is ``lobbying'' the Supreme Soviet,
which is the Soviet legislature, to consider the draft laws as soon
as possible and at least one may be taken up at the coming session
starting Sept. 25.
   The United States had anticipated the new laws would have been
enacted already, but Reshetov said the Supreme Soviet has other
items higher on its agenda.
   The Soviet official said that even without the laws, the number
of people denied emigration dropped from 11,000 several years ago to
2,000, the teaching of Hebrew and Yiddish is allowed in schools, and
three million Bibles were recently imported into the Soviet Union.
   Reshetov promised that all violators of the ban on anti-Semitic
activity would be punished. The State Department says that despite
the official outlawing of discrimination against Jews, anti-Semitism
among the lower echelons of the bureacracy and among the general
population has increased.
</TEXT>
