<FIRST>r a PM-RetardedCare 1stLd-Writethru a0495 09-19 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retarded Care, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0495,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Ordered to Fund Services for Retarded Who Live at Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to CORRECT spelling of judge's name in 2nd
graf and CLARIFY that ruling applies to Philadelphia only; PICKS UP 6th
graf pvs, `The ruling ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge ordered Pennsylvania to provide $7.56
million to restore services that had been cut or canceled for more
than 4,000 mentally retarded people living at home in Philadelphia.
   Arguing that cuts in the service had put the retarded people at
risk of institutionalization, Commonwealth Court Judge James
Crumlish Jr. directed the city to restore the program and said the
state must pay 90 percent of the costs.
   He gave the state Department of Public Welfare until Sept. 27 to
ask the Legislature to provide the money.
   ``The crying needs of and imminent harm to the individuals at
issue here, unable to speak themselves, cannot be ignored while the
intricacies of the General Assembly budgetary process unfold,''
Crumlish said.
   The services involved teaching and training the retarded in basic
life and social skills, such as feeding and dressing themselves and
learning a simple job. The ruling applied only to retarded people in
Philadelphia.
   The ruling affected only those persons who had received the
rehabilitative services before they were cut July 1. But attorney
David Ferleger said he hoped that the state recognizes it must also
provide such services for every retarded person who requests them.
   ``It is a great victory, not only in Pennsylvania, but for
retarded persons everywhere in this country,'' said Ferleger, who
was representing retarded people awaiting services. ``Other states,
I'm sure, will begin to provide these services as Pennsylvania now
is required to do.''
   The lawsuit, brought by the city and joined by the Philadelphia
Police and Fire Association for Handicapped Children, was the second
the state has lost over the Philadelphia program. During the last
fiscal year, unhappy with deficits in the program, the Legislature
tried to withhold the appropriation, acquiescing only under court
order.
   Vicki Smink, spokeswoman for the state welfare department, said
no decision on an appeal has been made.
   Crumlish said the state had continually refused to provide
sufficient funds in recent years.
   ``This chancellor is deeply troubled by the department's utter
disregard of the needs of mentally retarded persons and their
families who depend on non-residential serevices and programs,'' he
said.
   Crumlish said that while the state was at fault, the city also
was to blame for failing to prevent the cutoff of the program by
seeking additional funds from federal or private sources.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
