<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1432EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Haiti     09-19 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Life Sentence of Secret Police Chief Commuted in Haiti</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ The president has commuted the life
sentence of Luc Desir, the former secret police chief who directed
hundreds of torture sessions during the Duvalier regime, a state-run
newspaper said Tuesday.
   Human rights activist Jean-Claude Bajeux immediately denounced
the move, saying: ``The commutation is a gesture of conciliation
toward the Duvalierists. The next step is a full pardon.''
   ``Luc Desir, the man who directed torture sessions with a Bible
in his hand, is a symbol of Duvalierist barbarity,'' Bajeux said in
an interview.
   L'Union newspaper carried an Information Ministry statement
saying that on the first anniversary of his rise to power on Sept.
17, 1988, the president, Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril, pardoned or
commuted the sentences of 13 people.
   They included Desir, who was sentenced to life at hard labor
after the fall of dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier in 1986. Desir's
sentence was commuted to 30 years in prison, the Information
Ministry statement said.
   ``The president of the republic has the prerogative to commute a
sentence. If he so wishes, he may even grant full pardon,'' Max
Kernizan, the secretary of the Port-au-Prince Bar Association, told
The Associated Press.
   Kernizan said Desir's trial had been irregular and that he was
``a victim of social pressure.'' Kernizan said Desir's ``victims
could not testify against him, since most of them are dead.''
   One of the few people to be sentenced for crimes committed under
the dictatorship, Desir directed innumerable torture sessions and
executions when he headed the dreaded secret police of Francois
Duvalier, Jean-Claude's father. The number of his victims is not
known, but they are estimated in the hundreds.
   In the 1970s Desir fell out of favor with Jean-Claude Duvalier
and was forced into retirement. He was captured while trying to flee
the country on Feb. 25, 1988. An airport employee alerted a local
radio station of his flight, and thousands of Haitians swarmed the
landing strip to prevent his departure.
   Francois ``Papa Doc'' Duvalier was elected president in 1957
following a year of political turmoil during which six different
governments held power.
   He became president-for-life in 1964 and wielded absolute
political control until his death in 1971, when his son, Jean-Claude
``Baby Doc'' Duvalier, assumed the presidency. On Feb. 7, 1986,
after months of civil disorder, Jean-Claude fled to exile in France.
   Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy led the military junta that assumed power
when Duvalier fled. Presidential elections on Nov. 29, 1987, were
aborted after thugs, protected by soldiers, massacred at least 34
voters at polling stations.
   Civilian Leslie Manigat won army-run elections on Jan. 17, 1988,
and was overthrown by Namphy on June 20, 1988.
   On Sept. 17, 1988, a military coup brought Avril to power.
   In April 1989, loyalist troops foiled a coup attempt and crushed
a rebellion by two army units.
   Haiti comprises the western third of the island of Hispaniola in
the Caribbean Sea, between Puerto Rico and Cuba.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
