<FIRST>u w PM-Baker 1stLd-Writethru a0630-a0641 09-19 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baker, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0630-a0641,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Aims for Progress on Arms Pacts, Raps Mitchell</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs files, edits and adds information throughout; corrects
quote in pvs 5th graf, Baker replied</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III said
today he hoped to conclude a chemical weapons agreement with the
Soviet Union this weekend and make headway on other arms control
fronts.
   Baker, in his first Washington news conference in eight months in
his job, sought to reverse growing criticism in Congress and
elsewhere of the cautious approach President Bush is taking in
response to foreign policy initiatives from Moscow.
   He accused the Senate's Democratic leader of playing politics
with the issue.
   Last week, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze, who
will meet with Baker in Jackson Hole, Wyo., on Friday and Saturday,
accused the administration of ``timidity'' on arms control issues.
   Senate Majority Leader George J. Mitchell, D-Maine, said Monday
that the administration had failed to encourage change in the
Eastern bloc and was ``feeling almost nostalgic about the Cold War.''
   Baker replied today: ``The president is rocking along with a 70
percent approval rating in foreign policy. And if I were the Senate
majority leader I might have something like that to say, too.''
   And yet, in several of his replies to questions, Baker stressed
the cautious stance taken by the administration toward Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev would be maintained.
   ``I hope we have been approaching this relationship with a proper
degree of prudence,'' he said.
   In this regard, Baker lowered expectations that he would set a
date with Shevardnadze for a summit meeting between Bush and
Gorbachev. He said only that the subject would be thoroughly
discussed at Jackson Hole.
   Baker said any increases in U.S. assistance to Poland and
Hungary, which are veering away from a Marxist economy, depended on
the changes undertaken in the two East European countries. ``We
shouldn't be mistaken'' and think U.S. aid could overcome their
problems, he said.
   And, Baker said, it was the Soviets' ``turn to move'' on reducing
troops and non-nuclear armaments in Europe.
   On negotiating arms control with Moscow, Baker said, ``we have to
be careful not to become frantic ....''
   However, Baker said he would propose to Shevardnadze ways to
break a 15-year impasse on verifying the size of U.S. and Soviet
underground nuclear tests.
   In addition, he said, ``We have, I think, a reasonable shot at an
agreement to exchange data on chemical stocks, which I think is a
first practical step toward achieving real controls and eventually a
total ban.''
   On another arms control front, Baker said the administration no
longer would seek a ban on U.S. and Soviet long-range mobile
missiles. He urged Congress to provide funds for development of the
single-warhead Midgetman.
   The move is of limited significance. The Reagan administration
had taken the position it favored a ban only if the elimination of
all U.S. and Soviet mobile missiles could be verified, and no
headway was made on the issue in negotiations in Geneva.
   Baker said continued Soviet weapons shipments to leftist
Nicaragua will be a priority issue in his discussions with
Shevardnadze.
   ``We're a little disappointed in what's going on down there,''
Baker said, referring to the role of the Soviets and other East bloc
countries in building up the Sandinistas' military arsenal.
   He said most of the Soviet weaponry arrives in Nicaragua via
third countries and the Soviets could put a stop to the practice if
they so chose.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
