<FIRST>u a PM-America'sCup 1stLd-Writethru a0647-a0651rmsover 09-19
0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-America's Cup, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0647-a0651,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Awards America's Cup to San Diego</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: COMBINES pvs urgent series, ADDS background, editing throughout.
No pickup. ADDS byline. A version moving on sports wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state appeals court today stripped New Zealand
of the America's Cup and gave the trophy back to the San Diego Yacht
Club.
   The Supreme Court's Appellate Division reversed a lower court
ruling April 7 that stripped San Diego of yacht racing's most
coveted prize for using a catamaran, or two-hull vessel, instead of
a single-hull boat in winning a 1988 match.
   The appeals court said that the catamaran was legal and that the
San Diego Club is entitled to the America's Cup.
   Supreme Court Justice Carmen Ciparick had ruled in April that the
best-of-three race between the New Zealand, a yacht about 90 feet at
the water line sailed by the Mercury Bay Boating Club, and the Stars
and Stripes, a 60-foot catamaran sailed by the San Diego group, was
a ``gross mismatch'' and unfair.
   Ciparick found that competing vessels must be ``somewhat evenly
matched'' in America's Cup competition and that using a lighter,
faster catamaran violated the spirit of the international
competition.
   But in its 4-1 decision today the appeals court said Ciparick had
on her own pronounced a rule that is neither expressed nor implied
in the Deed of Gift, the 102-year-old document that governs the race.
   The squabbling began in July 1987 when Auckland businessman
Michael Fay, on behalf of the Mercury Bay Boating Club, ignored
modern America's Cup tradition and demanded a one-on-one match with
a San Diego defender.
   Fay wanted the race held within one year rather than the usual
three to four; he wanted a one-on-one race instead of the usual
elimination matches, and he wanted to compete in a boat more than 90
feet long at the water line instead of the usual yachts that are
about 45 feet at the water line.
   San Diego rejected the challenge, but Fay went to court. When San
Diego was ordered to accept the challenge, it also went to an
unconventional boat, the speedy catamaran.
   The San Diego Yacht Club became trustee of the Cup in 1987 after
skipper Dennis Conner sailed the 12-meter yacht Stars &amp; Stripes to
victory over the Australian defender, Kookaburra III, in waters off
Fremantle, Australia.
   The victory returned the Cup to America after Conner's 1983 loss
to the Australians ended a 132-year U.S. winning streak.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
