<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1543EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Auschwitz-Chronology     09-19 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auschwitz-Chronology,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Events in the Convent Controversy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Auschwitz-Vatican, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are dates of significant events in the
controversy surrounding the convent of Carmelite nuns near the
Auschwitz death camp site:
   June 1984 _ Ten Polish nuns receive permission from the Polish
government to turn a former Nazi storehouse on the Auschwitz death
camp perimeter into a convent. They move in shortly thereafter.
   Feb. 22, 1987 _ Eighteen Jewish and Roman Catholic leaders sign
agreement in Geneva to move the convent by 1989 to an interfaith
prayer and education center to be located further from the site.
   Feb. 22, 1989 _ Deadline passes and nuns remain in the convent.
   July 14, 1989 _ An American rabbi and six other Jews stage a
five-hour protest and are forcibly removed by workers after trying
to scale a convent wall.
   Aug. 10, 1989 _ Cardinal Franciszek Macharski of Krakow, whose
diocese includes the convent, says the 1987 agreement to move the
nuns is being abrogated because of the ``aggressive'' atmosphere
surrounding the controversy.
   Aug. 26, 1989 _ Polish primate Cardinal Jozef Glemp calls a
Jewish request to relocate the convent ``offensive'' to Poles and
makes other remarks that provoke charges of anti-Semitism by critics.
   Sept. 19, 1989 _ The Vatican says the convent should be moved to
another site and that it would help finance the construction of an
interfaith prayer center for the nuns to live in.
</TEXT>
