<DOCNO> AP890919-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1631EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AbortionPlan     09-19 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Plan,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pa. Lawmaker Unveils Pro-Choice Abortion Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID MORRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition of pro-choice lawmakers
Tuesday proposed legislation designed to strengthen women's rights
to abortion in Pennsylvania and to preempt a planned attempt to
toughen existing laws restricting abortion.
   Pennsylvania is widely viewed as a key battleground state
following the U.S. Supreme Court decision in July that gave states
more leeway in addressing the abortion issue. Historically, the
state General Assembly has overwhelmingly approved bills restricting
abortions, but many of the provisions have been struck down in court.
   The new nine-bill package includes measures calling for a state
constitutional amendment giving women the right to an abortion,
restoring state-subsidized funding for all ``medically necessary''
abortions, and wiping out an existing law requiring rape and incest
victims to file a police report before receiving subsidized
abortions.
   The centerpiece bill, sponsored by state Rep. Karen Ritter, says
government should not interfere with ``a woman's personal choice to
commence, prevent or continue a pregnancy or have an abortion''
before the fetus is viable.
   The proposal mirrors existing law in saying an abortion on a
viable fetus is allowed only if the mother's life or health is
threatened by the pregnancy. Under the proposal, a fetus is
considered viable if the woman's doctor rules there is ``a
reasonable likelihood of sustained survival ... outside the woman's
uterus.''
   In an attempt to placate some abortion opponents, Ms. Ritter said
the bill would also require doctors to ask teen-age patients to
notify at least one parent before having an abortion. If that is not
feasible, the doctor must recommend that the teen-ager discuss the
matter with another relative, school counselor or another adult.
   ``This bill represents mainstream America, and the opinion of an
overwhelming majority of Pennsylvania citizens as well, that
government has no business invading the privacy of people's lives,''
Ms. Ritter said at a news conference.
   The bills are scheduled to be introduced simultaneously in the
House and Senate on Oct. 2. Abortion foes, led by state Rep. Stephen
Freind, are scheduled to introduce legislation outlining further
restrictions on Oct. 3.
   This is the first attempt in several years to offer an organized
pro-choice package of bills. Ms. Ritter and others acknowledged the
proposals would face tough opposition in both chambers, but she said
the public generally supports a woman's right to an abortion, even
though many legislators do not.
   Freind said the parental notification in Ms. Ritter's bill
weakens what already is in Pennsylvania law but is under court
challenge. The law now requires that a parent be notified or the
minor obtain a court order before having an abortion.
   He also said pro-choice advocates want to restore the pre-1985
situation of ``tax-funded birth control by abortion on demand. That
won't happen.''
   Legislation enacted in the early 1980s and upheld by the courts
after years of legal battles restricted Medicaid funding for
abortions except in cases of rape or incest or when the mother's
life was at stake.
   Abortion already is an issue in the 1990 governor's race. Likely
GOP nominee Barbara Hafer is pro-choice. Incumbent Democrat Robert
P. Casey opposes abortion.
   Freind has said his bills will deal with such issues as requiring
spousal notification before an abortion is performed and banning
so-called sex-selection abortions.
   He said he didn't regard the pro-choice announcement as an
attempt to upstage his efforts.
   ``Nobody takes us out of our game plan,'' he said. ``This is one
more battle that has to be won ... It's one more battle that will be
won and take us one step closer to the day when the sanctity of all
human life is protected in Pennsylvania.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
