<FIRST>u a AM-AIDS-Drugs Bjt   09-19 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Drugs, Bjt,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: AIDS Patients Take Risks by Combining Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AIDS patients in San Francisco are taking an
average of five drugs and unapproved treatments without telling
their doctors, posing a risk of potentially fatal drug interactions,
a survey has found.
   One patient admitted using 25 treatments, said Dr. Ruth
Greenblatt of the University of California, San Francisco. She
described her findings Tuesday at a meeting of the American Society
for Microbiology.
   ``There is a significant minority who have a background belief
that new experimental drugs may have more benefit than drugs already
available,'' she said.
   The hidden use of AIDS drugs also makes it difficult for
scientists to determine which drugs have toxic side effects.
   Patients receiving only the recommended, approved treatments for
infection with the AIDS virus or HIV would normally not be receiving
more than one or two drugs unless they were very sick. Then they
might be given up to five drugs, Greenblatt said.
   Dr. Kenneth Dunnigan, medical director of a city-supported AIDS
clinic in San Francisco, said he was a bit surprised at how many
drugs patients were taking, but said he was ``fully supportive of
people with HIV using alternative therapies.''
   ``I also believe care is difficult if we only have bits and
pieces of information'' about what patients are taking, Dunnigan
said. He is on the board of the Community Research Alliance, a San
Francisco group studying alternative treatments.
   Greenblatt's survey found that 37 percent of the patients were
getting prescriptions from a second doctor and 28 percent were using
treatments not approved by the Food and Drug Administration.
   ``The use of FDA-unapproved treatments was common and increased
with the severity of illness,'' Greenblatt said.
   The only government-approved drug to treat AIDS is AZT. Several
other drugs are available for the treatment of AIDS-related
infections.
   The alternative treatments most widely used by patients in the
survey included megadoses of vitamin C and the unapproved AIDS drugs
AL721 and dextran sulfate. One patient was getting injections of
fetal sheep blood.
   Other doctors familiar with the survey were surprised at how many
drugs patients were getting from other doctors and alternative
sources, such as community-organized trials of unapproved drugs.
   AIDS patients have more toxic drug reactions than do other
patients, Greenblatt said. Because of the clandestine use of
multiple drugs, ``it can be hard to sort out which medications are
causing these toxicities,'' she said.
   The hidden use of approved and unapproved AIDS drugs is
complicating scientific research, because subjects in the studies
are not disclosing their use of other drugs, Dunnigan said.
   In some cases, disclosing that use might result in their being
dropped from the study, losing access to medical care associated
with the study, he said.
   ``There are two sides,'' he said. ``From the physician's point of
view, in order to get good data there needs to be some rigor in how
the drugs are used. But from a client's point of view, there's so
little that can be done. And the clock keeps ticking.''
   Greenblatt said patients who use unapproved treatments are not
discharged from her clinic, but are advised to tell their doctors
what drugs they are taking.
   ``I don't think you can ask people to not take something they
think will help them,'' Greenblatt said. ``That's my personal
opinion. But you can ask them to let you know.''
   The key to avoiding problems is a partnership between doctors and
their patients, Dunnigan said, in which patients feel free to
disclose which drugs they're taking.
   ``Hopefully that agreement would be made before therapy is
initiated,'' he said.
   The survey, which began last fall and will continue for two more
years, consists of 30-minute to 60-minute interviews with each
patient every three months. Patients are asked about their use of
various medical services in addition to drug use, Greenblatt said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
