<FIRST>r a AM-House'sFate     09-19 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House's Fate,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Denies Will Request to Have House Leveled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT W. TROTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman's dying wish to leave behind an
unimpeded view of the shore by having her house leveled was denied
Tuesday by a judge who called the will request a waste of money.
   Superior Court Judge Thomas Needham threw out a portion of Ethel
Turner's will that instructed the city of Cranston to raze the old
home and use the property as a right of way to Providence River.
   ``To destroy the house would be to commit substantial waste of
this estate,'' Needham said. ``I declare the provision is void as
being contrary to public policy.''
   Rhode Island Hospital Trust, executor of the woman's estate, did
not want the nine-room home razed and challenged the will in June,
when Needham heard arguments from lawyers.
   In 1973, the Victorian-Queen Anne home built in the 1890s was
made a national historic site, along with the rest of the
neighborhood. Neighbors and the city also opposed leveling the house
and filling in the basement as requested in the will.
   Ms. Turner died in April 1986 at age 86. The will left $5,000 to
the city to maintain the right of way. The Providence River leads to
Narragansett Bay.
   Needham said the area would not be served by tearing down the
house, among $1.4 million in assets left by the woman. Her wealth
was mostly in stocks and bonds.
   David Riedel, Hospital Trust's lawyer, said the ruling ``made a
lot of sense.''
   He added: ``No one wants to see a nice house destroyed. But on
the other hand, some people (would feel) you ought to be able to do
whatever you want in the will.''
   Needham ruled the home should be sold. He said an appeal of his
decision is unlikely. The exact value of the house is unknown, but
real estate agents said waterfront homes in the area were selling
for $400,000 and more.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
