<FIRST>r w AM-DrugTreatment     09-19 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Treatment,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alabama Treatment Program Accepts DC Drug Addicts at No Cost</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two drug addicts from the District of Columbia
have been admitted to a donated treatment program in Alabama that
could be a model for programs elsewhere in the nation, government
and private drug abuse officials announced Tuesday.
   ``This effort has brought a cooperative spirit to the district
that could well be recreated in communities across the nation,''
said Dr. Herbert D. Kleber, deputy director for demand reduction in
the Office of National Drug Control Policy. ``We need everybody to
follow this example of private and public cooperation to win this
war.''
   The two unidentified adult men, who left Washington last
Wednesday to be admitted to a facility of the Bradford Group in
Birmingham, Ala., are the first of 70 that the private drug and
alcohol treatment organization has said it will accept in the first
year of its new program.
   Bradford, a company operated for profit, has had a policy of
making unused beds available to uninsured addicts in the Birmingham
area and announced on May 23 that it would extend the program to the
nation's capital.
   Patients for the treatment slots are selected by a committee of
private citizens working under auspices of the Washington Area
Council on Alcoholism and Drug Abuse.
   Joseph L. Wright, executive director of the council, said the
patients must be residents of the district, must have a
``significant person'' to help them with decisions, must have no
criminal charges pending against them although they may have
criminal records, must certify that no insurance company or third
party will pay for the cost and must not have been through a drug
treatment program before.
   Wright said there is a ``considerable waiting list,'' although he
said he did not know the number waiting.
   Chip Burson, a spokesman for Bradford, said most patients would
stay from 30 to 45 days.
   After that, Wright said, they are to receive two years of
follow-up treatment in the district, which they agree to pay for
through some form of community service.
   Wright said the council is negotiating with three treatment
groups in the Washington suburbs that have approached it about
similar programs.
</TEXT>
