<FIRST>r a AM-Nielsens     09-19 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nielsens,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC's `Roseanne' Wins Big With Season Premiere</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The season premiere of ABC's ``Roseanne'' took
a commanding lead in the A.C. Nielsen Co. television ratings and
pulled the new comedy series ``Chicken Soup'' into second place for
the week ended Sept. 17.
   NBC won the week, by less than one ratings point over ABC, and
became the first network to win every week of a broadcast year from
one season premiere to another. The week CBS broadcast the
miniseries ``Lonesome Dove'' was a tie between NBC and CBS. In all,
NBC has been first for the past 65 weeks.
   ``Roseanne'' was five ratings points ahead of ``Chicken Soup''
and captured 40 percent of the audience.
   NBC's coverage of ``The Miss America Pageant'' was third, and
that network's preview of ``Sister Kate'' was fifth after a rerun of
its ``Golden Girls.'' CBS' ``60 Minutes,'' back with new shows, was
sixth.
   ABC's Monday Night Football game between the New York Giants and
the Washington Redskins was seventh. Its Tuesday preview of the new
fall drama ``Life Goes On'' was tenth. A Friday preview of the same
episode tied for 28th place.
   Reruns of NBC's ``The Cosby Show'' and ``Cheers'' were eighth and
ninth.
   ABC's ``Chicken Soup,'' which follows ``Roseanne,'' stars Jackie
Mason as a former pajama salesman who takes a new job at a community
center. It had been forecast as the biggest hit of the new season.
   Although all three networks previewed some shows last week, the
season officially began Monday.
   ``The Emmy Awards Show'' on Fox Broadcasting landed in 37th
place. Nineteen percent of the audience watched the Sunday night
show. The pre-awards show on the arrival of the stars was 68th. The
Emmys pre-empted Fox's highest-rated shows, including ``Married ...
With Children.''
   NBC was first in the A.C. Nielsen Co. survey with an average
rating of 12.4. ABC was second with 11.8 and CBS third with 11.0.
NBC had an average rating of 14.3 for the past 52-week period, ABC
was second with 11.6 and CBS third with 11.5.
   The rating is the percentage of the estimated 90.4 million homes
with television in the United States. The share is the percentage of
sets in use.
   CBS' preview of ``Wolf'' tied for 17th place with the rerun of an
NBC ``Perry Mason'' movie. ABC's ``Just the 10 of Us'' preview tied
for 26th place with a rerun of NBC's ``L.A. Law.'' A preview of
ABC's ``Homeroom'' was 64th.
   CBS' ``Paradise,'' continuing its new season with another show
featuring Hugh O'Brian reprising his role as Wyatt Earp, was 49th.
The week before a special season premiere with O'Brian and Gene
Barry as Bat Masterson was ninth. NBC threw in a ``Golden Girls''
special against it for a 30th place finish.
   Fox's special broadcast of the rock opera ``Tommy'' starring The
Who was 70th.
   ``The CBS Evening News'' was the top-rated newscast and ABC fell
to third place. CBS had a rating of 9.4, NBC was second with 9.0 and
ABC had 8.9. ABC's ``World News Tonight'' was pre-empted or not
broadcast on 18 West Coast stations Monday because of the return of
``Monday Night Football.''
   Here are the five bottom network shows: ABC's ``Fall Preview''
and ABC News' ``Survival Stories: Growing Up, Down and Out,'' tied;
ABC's ``Homeroom'' preview; NBC's ``Yesterday, Today and Tomorrow;''
and CBS' ``Hot Paint.''
</TEXT>
