<FIRST>r a AM-Hugo-Relief     09-19 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Relief,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal, Private Groups Mobilize to Help with Recovery</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Red Cross organized its biggest
domestic relief effort in four years and the Coast Guard dispatched
ships and planes Tuesday to bring emergency assistance to Puerto
Rican victims of Hurricane Hugo.
   Relief workers gathered blankets, cots, food, medicine and other
supplies for shipment to Puerto Rico, a U.S. commonwealth where
about 27,000 people were reported homeless in the wake of the storm.
   ``We're working with the Air Force, trying to get our supplies on
their planes,'' said Brian Ruberry, a Red Cross spokesman in
Washington. ``The problem right now, of course, is that the airports
are closed, and even when they reopen we don't know what size planes
they'll be able to accommodate.''
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency, the nation's lead agency
for disaster relief, launched a C-141 cargo plane loaded with
government relief workers and communications gear from Martinsburg,
W.Va., bound for St. Croix in the U.S. Virgin Islands, where the
National Guard reported damage to 90 percent of the buildings.
   Coast Guard C-130s from Florida, South Carolina and Guantanamo
Bay, Cuba, headed to San Juan, Puerto Rico, with emergency supplies,
while two Coast Guard cutters assisted with communications and
relief efforts.
   ``We don't know the extent of the mobilization that's going to be
required,'' said FEMA spokesman Bill McAda in Washington. ``That's
essentially what we know at this point. Our radio communications
have been virtually nonexistent across the island since the storm
went across.''
   Five Red Cross supply centers across the nation organized relief
shipments in hopes that Air Force flights would be able to launch
soon from bases in Ohio, New Jersey and South Carolina.
   ``We are sending cots, blankets and comfort kits _ those contain
soap, toothbrushes, shampoo and other toiletries _ to a staging area
in Dayton, Ohio,'' Ruberry said. ``We're sending in all 15,000 of
each of these items.''
   About 400 Red Cross workers in Puerto Rico took care of about
25,000 people Monday night _ offering food, shelter and medical
attention, he said.
   The ferocious storm produced a groundswell of public support,
especially in New York's Puerto Rican community, the largest on the
mainland with an estimated 1.5 million people.
   New York's Christian Community Benevolent Association and Banco
Popular de Puerto Rico scheduled a weekend benefit concert featuring
pop star Lisa Lisa, and television and radio stations planned
marathon fund-raisers.
   Collections of clothing, food and donations are planned Saturday
at two major intersections in New York City, said the Rev. Ruben
Diaz, a native of Puerto Rico and executive director of the
association.
   Community support was ``heavy, heavy, heavy,'' he said.
   ``I just got a call from the Boy Scouts. They're offering 25 kids
to help on Saturday. We will have vehicles from our organization to
go pick up everything,'' Diaz said.
   He said he was in touch through newly restored telephone service
with mayors in several Puerto Rican cities to relay messages from
nervous relatives.
   In Miami, the government tourist office for Puerto Rico was
flooded with calls from people who couldn't reach relatives at home,
but regional manager Teresa Morales said she hasn't been able to
reach anyone either.
   ``We're in the same boat,'' she said. ``I do have all of my
relatives down there, and I haven't been able to get through.''
   A two-member disaster response team from Miami's Metro-Dade fire
department, a specialized unit that routinely travels to some of the
world's worst disasters, had traveled to Barbados on Saturday in
preparation for the storm.
   The pair set up a communications center in Antigua on Tuesday,
paying particular attention to the island of Montserrat.
   ``An airplane that flew over showed that just about everything
was down. There were no standing structures. They feel they've lost
everything,'' said Mel Montes, deputy director of the Metro-Dade
department.
</TEXT>
