<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1708EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Walsh-Secrecy     09-19 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Walsh-Secrecy,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Special Prosecutor Wants Attorney General's Appeal Powers Limited</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney general should not be empowered to
appeal a judge's secrecy order in trials being conducted by
independent counsels, Iran-Contra prosecutor Lawrence E. Walsh told
Congress on Tuesday.
   Walsh, appointed an independent counsel in 1986 to investigate
the Iran-Contra affair, urged the House Intelligence legislative
affairs subcommittee against adopting legislation to specifically
give the attorney general such power under the Classified
Information Procedures Act.
   The independent counsel, speaking to reporters after the closed
hearing, noted that the attorney general already has the power to
file a court affidavit blocking a trial if he feels disclosure of
certain secrets in open court would endanger national security.
   But Walsh, who was forced to jettison three major conspiracy
charges against former White House aide Oliver L. North because of
the government's refusal to release certain classified information,
said the attorney general should not be allowed to appeal
trial-court rulings on secrecy in cases conducted by special
prosecutors.
   To do so would undermine the independence of special prosecutors,
said Walsh.
   ``If the attorney general feels that a case should be interrupted
to protect classified information, that should be a clean-cut act
which the public can understand and for which he takes political
responsiblity,'' Walsh said in an allusion to the Justice
Department's response to secrecy problems arising from his
prosecution of a former CIA agent.
   ``He's not in there to tinker with it. And he should not come in
unless he wants to kill the case,'' Walsh said.
   In a report to the committee released after the hearing, Walsh
pointedly noted that Attorney General Dick Thornburgh threatened to
file an affidavit preventing disclosure of secrets in the trial of
former CIA station chief Joseph Fernandez.
   As jury selection was set to begin on July 24, Thornburgh instead
sought a stay of the trial while he appealed the judge's ruling that
the details of three CIA programs in Costa Rica and the locations of
CIA stations in Latin America could be disclosed in court.
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Richmond is now
considering whether the attorney general has right to appeal such a
ruling. The appellate court has stayed the trial of Fernandez,
accused of lying about his role in setting up a clandestine arms
resupply network for the Nicaraguan Contras.
   Walsh also urged the panel to adopt legislation requiring the
attorney general to notify the intelligence committees of Congress
so those panels ``would be able to look at the so-called secret
information to see whether it's a true secret.''
   ``The basic controversy is as to matters which are classified but
which are publicly known,'' Walsh said.
   ``There are some matters, which even though the public knows it,
the intelligence agencies wish to keep classified, and not release
even for use at trial, even though it may mean that the trial has to
be dropped,'' Walsh said.
   Before the trial of North, who was convicted of three Iran-Contra
coverup charges, intelligence agencies objected to the
identification of countries that helped arm the Nicaraguan Contras.
   Similar secrecy problems have arisen in the Fernandez case, even
though some of the same secrets were disclosed in North's trial.
   Walsh said that the intelligence agencies are apparently
concerned that ``in the framework of the Fernandez case, it might
get into much more nitty-gritty detail.''
   ``While I recognize these problems, but to defeat a case ... to
protect that rather abstract concern, seems to me going too far,''
Walsh said.
   Rep. Matthew F. McHugh, D-N.Y., the subcommittee chairman, said
the panel may draft some legislation but first wants to hear
testimony from Thornburgh, whom he said has refused so far to
discuss the issue.
</TEXT>
