<FIRST>r w AM-CapitalPunishment     09-19 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Capital Punishment,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Victim of Shotgun Rampage Urges Senators: Strengthen Death Penalty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fighting back tears, a South Carolina woman
whose jaw was destroyed by a drug user's shotgun a decade ago told
senators Tuesday the nation needs strong death penalty laws.
   ``The problem I see with the death penalty is the lengthy appeals
process,'' Wanda Summers of Pawley's Island, S.C., told the Senate
Judiciary Committee, which is considering measures to increase the
number of crimes that could result in death sentences under federal
law.
   Senators commended Mrs. Summers for bravery in telling the story
of the Feb. 22, 1979, murder spree by two men that left four dead.
She and a fellow worker at a convenience store were taken to a
deserted road, raped and shotgunned, she testified.
   Her assailant, Ronald Woomer, left her for dead, Mrs. Summers
said. Actually, she turned her head at the moment of the shotgun
blast, which blew away part of her mouth and her jaw. Despite her
wound, she was able find help, but her co-worker died in the
incident.
   The two assailants were found the same night in a Myrtle Beach
motel. One of them, Eugene Skaar, committed suicide. Woomer was
captured, convicted of murder and sentenced to death. He has been on
death row ever since as the appeals process has continued.
   Mrs. Summers said she has been helped by reconstructive surgery
and psychiatric care, but added that it ``is hard to get up in the
morning and look in the mirror.''
   ``It's hard when little kids stare at you and adults try not to.
Its hard to smile when you know how you look when you do.''
   She was asked by Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., a sponsor of the
death penalty legislation, if she considered life in prison
sufficient punishment even for those who commit heinous crimes.
   ``I believe the terrible crimes he committed do warrant the death
sentence,'' she said. ``He did not give the four other people the
option of life or death.''
   South Carolina state Solicitor James C. Anders testified that the
two killers were ``drugged up'' on PCP and alcohol.
   Congress as part of last year's anti-drug legislation approved
capital punishment for drug kingpins whose racketeering activities
result in death.
   A 1972 Supreme Court decision, however, blocked use of a number
of death penalty provisions on the books at that time, calling
unconstitutional the discretion the law allowed juries and judges on
whether to impose death or not.
   At the hearing, Assistant Attorney General Edward S.G. Dennis
told senators that under current law a jury can impose the death
penalty for the murder of a Drug Enforcement agent investigating a
case but not for the murder of an FBI agent responding to a bank
robbery.
   Legislation before the committee would restore the death penalty
for murdering a member of Congress, the Cabinet or the Supreme Court
to espionage. It would extend capital punishment provisions to
murdering foreign officials and official guests, kidnapping
resulting in death, attempted presidential assassination, murder for
hire and murder in aid of a racketeering enterprise.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
