<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1751EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Frank 2ndLd-Writethru a0691 09-19 0861</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Frank, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0691,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>House GOP Leader Says Frank Case A `Stain Upon the House'</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS graf 2 to note Frank hired prostitute as assistant; to
update with Moakley comments, INSERTS 2 grafs after 17th graf, `Ann Lewis'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Republican leader said Tuesday that
the Barney Frank case was becoming ``a stain upon the House of
Representatives,'' as allies of the embattled Democrat tried to
quell suggestions he was near resignation.
   Frank, a liberal who disclosed his homosexuality in 1987, has
come under scrutiny since acknowledging a two-year relationship with
a male prostitute, whom he paid for sex and then hired as a personal
assistant.
   Rep. Robert Michel, R-Ill., asserted that the Massachusetts
Democrat was benefiting from a double standard that would have dealt
more harshly with other members of Congress in similar circumstances.
   ``If it were anyone other than Barney Frank ... If I were to have
a woman prostitute in my employ for my own self gratification, I'd
be run out of town,'' Michel said.
   At Frank's own request, the House ethics committee is
investigating his involvement with Stephen L. Gobie and Gobie's
disputed claim that the congressman was aware he was operating a
prostitution service out of Frank's Capitol Hill apartment. Frank
has said he would await the ethics committee's inquiry.
   Michel, answering questions at a news conference, said he was
``distressed to have anything of that nature become a stain up on
the House of Representatives.''
   Democratic National Chairman Ron Brown, in a breakfast meeting
with reporters, acknowledged Frank was under pressure to resign but
said the congressman was right to await the ethics committee inquiry.
   ``He's done what he should have done,'' Brown said. ``The ethics
committee ought to go forward. Pressure is building to resign. But
we ought to let the quasi-judicial process go forward.''
   Asked if Frank had become an embarrassment to the Democratic
Party, Brown said: ``No, don't think so. There have been issues like
this for years in poitics. But I think we should let the
quasi-judicial process take over, and then we can make some
recommendations.''
   Frank, meanwhile, sought to carry out normal congressional duties
while declining to discuss his case with reporters.
   Frank attended a morning subcommittee meeting without speaking
publicly. He had normal office appointments in the afternoon, said
his administrative assistant, Doug Cahn.
   Gobie, Frank's accuser, breathed fresh life into the story by
recounting his version of their relationship in the airing Tuesday
of a videotaped appearance on the television program, ``Geraldo.''
   House Majority Leader Richard Gephardt also cited the ethics
comittee when asked about Frank.
   ``I don't think we should try people outside of that process,''
Gephardt, D-Mo., said.
   Close political allies of Frank contended he is not weighing an
immediate resignation, despite the Boston Globe's editorial call for
his resignation and private suggestions from political sources that
he was considering such a move.
   Frank said over the weekend he would step aside if he decided his
case was hurting the liberal causes he has worked for.
   Ann Lewis, Frank's sister and a Washington political consultant,
said Frank was wrestling with the question of whether he might not
seek re-election because of diminished effectiveness, but would not
resign before the ethics committee probe was carried out.
   A Massachusetts ally of Frank, Democratic Rep. Joe Moakley,
described the continuing disclosures about Frank as ``like Chinese
(water) torture,'' but defended Frank's decision to await the ethics
committee review.
   ``Some people may resign and cut their losses, but I think it's
up to the individual member who's being charged,'' Moakley said.
``This may very well be the thing Barney Frank is remembered for in
Congress. It's like when (former Ways and Means Committee Chairman)
Wilbur Mills had his tryst with the dancer and ended up in the tidal
basin.''
   Dan Payne, Frank's long-time media consultant in Boston, said
Frank did not intend to resign before the ethics committee acts and
reacted angrily to growing speculation in Washington political
circles about Frank's fate.
   ``There's no way Barney's going to let this end without getting
his day in the ethics committee,'' Payne said.
   ``I think it would be a mistake to resign because the political
kibitzing industry says he should,'' Payne said. ``It's really sick,
almost, that people are now engaged in trying to provide the
definitive wisecrack about Barney.''
   Payne said Frank's support within his district remains strong.
   Frank has become the focus of intense media coverage of his
personal life, including his current long-term relationship with a
male friend. In a reaction to the intensity of coverage, Frank has
declined press interviews about his case this week _ although he
conducted several last week.
   Reaction to Frank's case has been divided within Washington's
homosexual community, although Frank's decision to reveal his sexual
preference two years ago made him a visible symbol of a politically
successful gay person who has acknowledged his homosexuality.
   The Washington Blade, a gay newspaper in Washington, last week
published two letters from writers who said Frank should resign,
including one writer who said ``he owes all gays an apology for his
stupidity.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
