<HEAD>Police Say Detained Man is Not Colombian Drug Baron</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Colombia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Tuesday that a man arrested
near the Colombian border is not Jose Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha, a
Colombian drug baron sought worldwide.
   Police earlier said the detained man had a ``strong resemblance''
to Gacha, a kingpin of Colombia's Medellin cocaine cartel.
   Humberto Giffuni, deputy director of the Judicial Technical
Police, said the man, who he did not identify, would be released
along with three other people arrested with him Monday.
   ``After completing the established identification procedure we
have come to the conclusion that he is not the person wanted in
Colombia,'' Giffuni told reporters.
   Local news reports, which police would not confirm, identified
the man as Alirio Quintero Alvarez, 47, and said the people arrested
with him were Zulima Pena, Flor Maria Saavedra and Carmen Paez.
   All four were seized by police at a ranch in Tachira state, near
the Colombian border, and brought to Caracas where they were held
for 24 hours while authorities questioned them and checked their
identifications.
   The leaders of Colombia's cocaine cartels have been in hiding
since the Colombian government declared war against drug traffickers
after their hired gunmen assassinated Sen. Luis Carlos Galan during
a campaign rally Aug. 18.
   Colombian soldiers raided Rodriguez Gacha's ranch on the
outskirts of Pacho, Colombia, last month and after an exchange of
gunfire arrested 13 people, including Gacha's son, Freddy Rodriguez,
but his father escaped.
