<FIRST>r w AM-HousingNeeds 1stLd-Writethru a0684 09-19 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing Needs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0684,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Says HUD Scandal No Reason For Inaction on Housing Needs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 3 grafs with new initiative to aid low- and moderate-income
homebuyers.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A housing organization on Tuesday said the
problems plaguing the Department of Housing and Urban Development
should not be used as an excuse to dismantle federal programs
necessary to meet the nation's housing needs.
   The investigation of mismanagement and abuse at HUD is no reason
to delay maintainance and development of much-needed housing, said
John Simon, president of the National Housing Conference.
   ``The highest priority of the HUD Secretary and the Congress
should be immediate action to address the critical need for
additional low- and moderate-income housing,'' Simon said at a news
conference. ``The need to investigate should not be an excuse for
inaction in meeting the nation's housing needs.''
   Simon said that with nine months past since the start of the
current congressional session and the Bush administration, ``it's
time to move on ... the housing crisis is getting much worse.''
   More than 500,000 federally subsidized rental housing units could
be lost in the next 15 years due to federal inaction or weakened
national financial conditions, he said.
   The National Housing Conference represents more than 1,000 public
and private builders, developers, planners, architects, housing
financiers and tenant groups.
   Simon said current estimates of the homeless population range
from 700,000 to 4 million, but an additional 4 million to 14 million
American families are ``doubled up and tripled up in apartments of
friends and family.''
   ``Even a mild recession could double homelessness in America
virtually overnight,'' he said.
   Simon said current budget requests for housing are inadequate,
with an additional $13 billion to $18 billion needed for federally
assisted housing programs and $21.5 billion required to repair
dilapidated public housing stock. Another $10 billion should be
included for new housing construction, he said.
   Simon said he believed Housing Secretary Jack Kemp ``has not
gotten the support of the administration'' for funding existing
housing programs.
   Instead of using $50 million from the operating subsidies of
public housing administrations to fight drugs in public housing,
Kemp should have been given a separate allocation, Simon said.
   Meanwhile, one private mortgage insurer announced it would help
low- and moderate-income families purchase almost 10,000 homes in
the next year by insuring $500 million in loans through the a new
program.
   Under the Community Home Buyer's Program, prospective homebuyers
would be allowed to purchase a home with lower down payment and less
savings on hand and using a higher portion of their income for
housing expenses than traditional loans require.
   The cornerstone of the program, developed by GE Capital Mortgage
Insurance Cos., is a home-buying and mortgage credit course
including pre- and post-loan-closing sessions for borrowers.
</TEXT>
