<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-19 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wet On East Coast And Hurricane Looms On Horizon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rain fell along the central Atlantic Coast on Tuesday, with
more than 2 inches in some areas, and Hurricane Hugo roared through
the Bahamas.
   Hugo moved toward the northwest at 12 mph, with a maximum
sustained wind speed of 105 mph. It seemed to be threatening the
coast somewhere from Florida to North Carolina, but meteorologists
could not predict its wobbly path. It lurched to the north and west
because other weather systems seemed to be blocking it from heading
into the open Atlantic.
   Behind Hugo, Tropical Storm Iris approached hurricane strength
with maximum sustained wind speed near 70 mph. It was located
northeast of the northern Leeward Islands.
   A low pressure area off northeastern North Carolina moved
northeastward, spreading moisture from the Atlantic across the mid
Atlantic Coast region.
   A small stream and urban flood watch was issued for the New
Jersey sections of the metropolitan Delaware Valley, where 1.5 to 3
inches of rain was reported and where an additional 2 inches was
possible during the night.
   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included
2.40 inches at Salisbury, Md.; 2.15 at Dover, Del.; 1.93 at Atlantic
City, N.J.; 1.63 at Millville, N.J.; 1.34 at Wilmington, Del.; and
1.31 at Philadelphia.
   Elsewhere, showers and a few thunderstorms were scattered along a
cold front from Minnesota into South Dakota, and across
north-central New Mexico, where up to an inch of rain was reported
around Albuquerque.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 49
degrees at Thompson Falls, Mont., and Sandberg, Calif., to 93 at
Harlingen, Texas, and in Arizona at Phoenix and Tucson. Tuesday's
low in the Lower 48 states was 24 at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Wednesday, widespread rain was forecast over the northern and
central Rockies. Showers and scattered thunderstorms were forecast
from the middle Atlantic Coast into Florida.
   Highs in the 60s were predicted from the northern Rockies into
northern North Dakota; in the 90s across southern Texas and the
southern half of the Florida Peninsula; and in the 70s or 80s across
much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
