<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1912EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HUDProbe     09-19 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Probe,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Asks House Records on HUD</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department's criminal division is
seeking transcripts of a House subcommittee's hearings on
allegations of influence peddling at the Department of Housing and
Urban Development, a spokesman said Tuesday.
   However, the ranking Republican on the House panel, Rep.
Christopher Shays, said he was unsatisfied with the move, and he
continued to say he may call for a special prosecutor in the case.
   Justice spokesman David Runkel said the criminal division had
asked for the transcripts of hearings being conducted by the House
Government Operations subcommittee.
   Earlier this year, prosecutors in the department's public
integrity section made a preliminary conclusion that the HUD
inspector general's report on influence peddling in the Section 8
moderate rehabilitation program, a main focus of the congressional
investigation, showed no instances of criminal wrongdoing.
   The subcommittee has heard testimony that politically connected
developers received approval from high-level HUD officials in the
award of government housing grants.
   So far, the department has been reviewing newspaper accounts of
the hearings, at which a series of witnesses have described lobbying
of high HUD officials on behalf of development firms, Runkel said.
   The subcommittee has also heard conflicting testimony about the
role of former HUD Secretary Samuel R. Pierce Jr. in the awarding of
grants.
   Pierce has been called back for more questioning about whether,
despite his repeated denials, he helped political friends get HUD
grants.
   The subcommittee is expected to vote Wednesday to subpoena
Pierce, who last week abruptly canceled a scheduled appearance. The
former secretary's lawyers said they needed more time to prepare for
the questioning.
   The panel's chairman, Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., has expressed
the view that other witnesses had ``put the lie'' to Pierce's
denials that he ever helped prominent Republicans get HUD backing
for housing projects.
   Lantos has said he wants to give Pierce an opportunity to clarify
testimony that has been contradicted by other witnesses.
   Earlier Tuesday, Runkel rejected a call by Rep. Bruce Morrison,
D-Conn., for a special prosecutor in the matter.
   ``Investigations are proceeding in U.S. attorneys' offices around
the country and there is no reason to believe these cannot be
handled by the U.S. attorneys,'' Runkel said.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh ``has made it clear he wants
these cases given high priority,'' the spokesman added, referring to
investigations of fraud of HUD programs.
   As for Runkel's statement of the request for hearing transcripts,
Shays, R-Conn., said, ``That's not comforting. This should have been
done a long time ago. It just raises questions in my mind about the
veracity of the Justice Department's investigation.''
   He said that because of allegations concerning dealings with HUD
around the country, it is important that any criminal investigation
be centralized in Washington and not be conducted by U.S. attorneys
around the nation.
   He said unless there is a centralized investigation that looks at
the principal former HUD officials involved, including Pierce,
``then I just totally feel we've got to take it away from Justice
and have a special prosecutor. Right now, I just don't know. The
Justice Department hasn't had much communication with committee
members.''
   ``I can assure you that the records of the House subcommittee are
being reviewed closely as a part of the HUD matter,'' Runkel said at
a morning briefing.
   Later in the day, however, Runkel acknowledged that the
department had not yet received any subcommittee records but would
be asking formally for the transcripts of the hearings.
   ``That letter is going up today or tomorrow,'' Runkel said.
</TEXT>
