<FIRST>u a AM-RussianImmigrant     09-19 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Russian Immigrant,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Immigrant Who Staged Hunger Strike Becomes U.S. Citizen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ceremony lasted only a few minutes
Tuesday, but for Soviet immigrant Andrei Frolov, the journey to U.S.
citizenship took years.
   Eight years ago, Frolov staged a hunger strike for 26 days in his
homeland to attract the attention of Soviet authorities, who ignored
his plea to join his American wife. In the United States, his wife
did the same.
   After a year of bureaucratic haggling, Frolov's name was added to
the list of Soviet citizens with a spouse in the West who was
allowed to leave in 1982.
   Years later, Frolov, dressed in a three-piece gray suit, stood
outside a San Francisco courtroom ready to fulfill his dream of
citizenship.
   ``It's a great day,'' Frolov said while waiting for the ceremony.
   Frolov has been working as a translator for a Russian-language
newspaper in San Francisco since March, when he left his position at
the Department of Defense Language Institute in Monterey.
   He is also translating his play about life in the Soviet Union,
``Strangers Don't Enter,'' into English, and hopes one day to have
it produced.
   ``I expected life would be hard here because I did not know
English well and I couldn't use my education here. It's getting
better,'' he said.
   A shy, soft-spoken man, Frolov worked as a taxi driver, furniture
mover and bookstore clerk before he began teaching Russian to
soldiers at the institute in Monterey.
   ``Monterey is a pretty small town, and there is a small community
of Russian instructors,'' he said. ``Sometimes it looks like the
Soviet Union. But it is better to be among Americans.''
   Frolov, 58, joined 150 others for the naturalization ceremony
Tuesday. He stood stiffly, with a stern look on his face. Afterward,
he pulled a voter registration form out of his pocket and proudly
proclaimed his intention to register _ probably as a Democrat.
   Asked how he felt, he said simply, ``Great.''
   Frolov's journey began with a fascination with the United States.
A journalist in the Soviet Union, he read American literature and
watched movies in Moscow theaters. Friends teased him, calling him
an ``Americaniste.''
   Then he met Lois Becker, an American student working on a
dissertation at Moscow's Lenin Library.
   Nine months later, they married. When Becker's visa expired, she
was forced to leave the Soviet Union without her husband when she
was unable to find work.
   It was the beginning of the couple's yearlong struggle against
what became a bureaucratic nightmare. Then, for reasons that remain
unknown, Soviet authorities allowed Frolov to leave, and he and
Becker were reunited.
   The transition was not easy; they separated in 1985 and later
divorced.
   Frolov worked at a string of subsistence-level jobs after he
arrived in the United States. He recalls the early days in America,
when a trip to the supermarket could overwhelm him.
   Living alone in a rundown house in Washington D.C., Frolov would
rise early to practice English, watch television to further improve
his conversational skills, and then set off for work in a bookstore.
   He studied at the University of the District of Columbia three
nights a week, and would walk the streets at any hour to satisfy his
wanderlust.
   Although his life in America has been filled with challenges,
Frolov said he has no regrets about leaving the Soviet Union. ``I
still feel some kind of pain. I don't want even to visit Moscow.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
