<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-Ortega     09-19 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Ortega,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega Admits Receiving Cuban Arms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega said Tuesday
that Nicaragua had recently received a shipment of Cuban arms and
defended his nation's right to arm itself.
   The opposition newsaper La Prensa, in its Monday editions, quoted
the Washington Times newspaper as saying U.S. satellites had
observed the arms shipment.
   ``Nicaragua has normal relations with several countries which
have supply us with arms,'' Ortega told The Associated Press when
asked about the matter.
   When reminded that Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev promised
the U.S. government to suspend arms sales to Nicaragua, Ortega said,
``Yes, but these are replacements. Arms that have to be replaced. If
a helicopter is damaged, it must be repaired or replaced with
another.''
   He added, ``We maintain the same level of arms to guarantee
defense. We can't risk the defense of our country.''
   Ortega said if there is anything illegal about Nicaragua's
action, the U.S. government could pursue legal channels.
   ``If the United States considers it a crime what we are doing in
Nicaragua, they should take the case to the World Court,'' Ortega
said, referring to the court based in The Hague.
   Ortega made his statements following the opening of a farm silo
Tuesday outside Managua.
