<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1916EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-AIDSCommission     09-19 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Commission,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Will Call for Drug Treatment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The national AIDS commission, concerned that
President Bush's anti-drug strategy makes too little mention of
AIDS, on Tuesday agreed to draft a statement calling for treatment
of drug addicts in preventing spread of AIDS.
   The statement will reaffirm the previous AIDS commission's call
for drug treatment on demand as a national goal, said June Osborn,
chairwoman of the new panel.
   Osborn said the statement will be ``carefully worded'' so it does
not appear antagonistic, but she added that the panel ``can be
aggressive ... without being adversarial.''
   ``We want to say something that's a firm reminder in a collegial
sort of way,'' said Osborn, dean of the University of Michigan's
School of Public Health, after she adjourned a two-day meeting of
the panel.
   The previous AIDS commission, formed by President Reagan and
chaired by Admiral James Watkins, now secretary of energy,
highlighted the need for expanded drug treatment capacity to stop
spread of AIDS through sharing of needles by drug users.
   The new AIDS panel, created by Congress last year but not fully
constituted until this summer, will not recommend a specific amount
of funds for drug treatment, but its statement will show that
commissioners ``share the priority judgment of the Watkins
commission,'' Osborn said.
   Commissioner Don Des Jarlais, a New York state coordinator for
AIDS research, estimated that the Bush plan would deliver about a
third of what the Watkins commission said would be needed to treat
all drug addicts.
   The commission, anticipating maneuvering in the House and Senate
for mandatory AIDS testing and tracing of sexual partners, also
agreed to a resolution calling on Congress to block attempts to add
AIDS-policy amendments to appropriations bills.
   This method of attaching ``riders'' to appropriations bills is
often used to win approval of measures that could not be approved in
the normal legislative process.
   Osborn said that based on ``past patterns of behavior and
rumors,'' commissioners expect that the parliamentary tactic will be
attempted again this year as Congress completes action on spending
bills for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1.
   ``We would like to be sure that AIDS policy is taken very
seriously,'' she said.
</TEXT>
