<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1955EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-HershLibelTrial     09-19 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hersh Libel Trial,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kissinger Videotaped Testimony Delayed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLIFF EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Tuesday delayed the use of videotaped
testimony from former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger in the
libel trial of journalist Seymour Hersh, who is accused of defaming
a former Indian prime minister.
   Moraji Desai, who was Indian prime minister from 1977 to 1979,
filed a civil libel lawsuit against Hersh, claiming he was libeled
in Hersh's 1983 book, ``The Price of Power,'' about Kissinger.
   Hersh wrote that Desai served as a paid CIA informant.
   U.S. District Court Judge Charles Norgle called an early recess
Tuesday after Hersh's lawyers said they would object to Desai's
attorneys showing the jury a one-hour taped deposition by Kissinger.
   Lawyers were to present arguments on the admissibility of
Kissinger's taped testimony on Wednesday.
   Kissinger is scheduled to deliver a speech in Chicago on
Wednesday, and might be subpoenaed to testify if the judge bars the
use of the taped testimony, said John Omeara, one of Desai's
attorneys.
   Desai's lawsuit was filed in Chicago in accordance with the
tradition of filing defamation actions in the hometown of the
defendant. Hersh was born in Chicago, but now lives in Washington,
D.C.
   Omeara said Kissinger's testimony could be instrumental to the
case.
   ``It says that, to the best of his knowledge, (Desai) couldn't be
the spy,'' Omeara said, after Tuesday's court session.
   Hersh's lawyers have indicated that they consider Kissinger's
testimony to be invalid and based on hearsay.
   Earlier in the day, Desai's lawyers finished showing excerpts
from 81 hours of videotaped depositions made by Desai during visits
to Chicago in 1984-85.
   Desai, 94, was too ill to travel from India to Chicago to testify
in the trial, said his lawyer, Cyriac Kappil.
   In his deposition, Desai said he met with President Johnson at
least twice in 1968 and with Kissinger once in 1969 in India, but
said he could not recall what they spoke about.
   In excerpts shown Monday, Desai said he had met with top U.S.
officials, but insisted that he did not reveal any secret
information.
   Bernard Nussbaum, an attorney for Hersh, said Monday that the
author had six independent sources who claimed Desai, a bitter enemy
of former Prime Minister Indira Gandhi, received $20,000 a year as a
CIA informant.
   Nussbaum said the Indian politician cooperated with the CIA
because he was opposed to Ms. Gandhi's close relations with the
Soviet Union and her preparations for the 1971 war with Pakistan.
   Under U.S. libel law, Desai's attorneys must convince jurors that
Hersh knowingly printed false, negligent or malicious material.
   Hersh won the Pulitzer Prize for international reporting in 1970
for his articles exposing the My Lai massacre in Vietnam when he was
a reporter for the Dispatch News Service. He was also a reporter for
The Associated Press and for The New York Times. He left the
newspaper to pursue his own writing projects.
</TEXT>
