<FIRST>r a AM-SWBellContract     09-19 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SW Bell Contract,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Southwestern Bell Workers Ratify Three-Year Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the Communications Workers of America
have ratified a new three-year contract with Southwestern Bell
Telephone Co.
   Workers in five states _ Missouri, Kansas, Oklahoma, Arkansas and
Texas _ approved the contract by a 4-1 margin, Burlene Leininger,
spokeswoman for District 6 of the CWA said Tuesday.
   Negotiators reached a tentative agreement on the pact Aug. 13,
avoiding a threatened strike by some 41,000 Southwestern Bell
workers.
   The pact included a 5.25 percent wage increase the first year,
including a $1,000 cash bonus, and a 2.25 percent increase in the
second and third years. It also includes a cost of living allowance.
   The company dropped an attempt to make employees pay a portion of
health insurance premiums for dependents, officials said, but there
were some increases in certain health care costs.
   Southwestern Bell has 11 million customers in its five-state
area. The last strike by its workers was in 1983, before divestiture
by American Telephone and Telegraph Co. Southwestern Bell is one of
the so-called Baby Bells created by the 1984 breakup of AT&amp;T.
