<DOCNO> AP890919-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 2128EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FilmRegistry-Reax     09-19 0863</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Film Registry-Reax,0885</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government List of Significant Films Draws Favorable Response</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Film Registry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Library of Congress' list of 25 films
deemed ``culturally, historically or esthetically significant'' drew
generally favorable reviews Tuesday from James Stewart, Billy Wilder
and other film industry figures.
   ``I'm delighted,'' said Wilder, whose ``Some Like It Hot'' and
``Sunset Boulevard'' are listed. ``I wish things would go forward to
reconstruct those films as they were, not colorized and not
butchered by cuts.''
   ``The first thing that crossed my mind,'' said Stewart, who
starred in the Frank Capra film ``Mr. Smith Goes to Washington,''
also on the list, ``is that I'm glad that Frank is still with us and
can enjoy his vindication.''
   ``I think it's a terrific list; I'd like to see all of them,''
commented George Kirgo, president of the Writers Guild of America.
``The only omission I see is `The Apartment,' but Billy Wilder is
pretty well represented.''
   ``I'm so happy these 25 films have been selected,'' said Arthur
Hiller, president of the Directors Guild of America. ``I'd be even
happier if more films could have been selected, as the
(Congressional) bill intended. I'd be happiest if there were no need
for a bill, and the moral rights of all artists not to have their
works altered or defaced would be protected.''
   The major surprise among the selections for the new National Film
Registry was the 1969 ``The Learning Tree,'' a semi-autobiographical
film of a black boy's rural childhood by Gordon Parks, famed Life
magazine photographer.
   ``I'm surprised, pleasantly so,'' said Parks at his New York
residence. ``I'm very happy. The film was very well received in its
release, and it's still playing in Europe and on television here.''
   The National Film Registry is the outgrowth of protests by
filmmakers over the colorization and the editing for television of
classic films. Congress last year passed the National Film
Preservation Act which called for the naming of 25 classic films
annually for three years.
   ``I'm delighted to be one of the 25, but I'm horrified at the
necessity of the act,'' said Stanley Donen, the director of the
musical ``Singin' in the Rain.''
   Donen said that the act will do nothing to keep broadcasters from
editing movies for length or duplicating them with poor quality
control onto videocassettes.
   The aim, said Librarian of Congress James H. Bilington in
announcing the first 25 Tuesday, was to help promote movies as an
American art form and generate public interest in preserving films.
   ``I think it's as good a list as we can expect the first time
out,'' said Dave Kehr, a member of the National Film Preservation
Board and chairman of the National Society of Film Critics. ``It's a
very safe, conservative list. ... I wish the list had been a little
more reflective of bread and butter Hollywood.''
   Said film critic Leonard Maltin: ``I feel that they've chosen
such generally outstanding titles that whatever omissions one could
argue this year will be rectified next year if not the year after.''
   A board of 13 film figures made the final selection, drawing from
a thousand nominations from the public.
   Jimmy Stewart made his comments in Washington, D.C., between a
bookstore signing for his new volume of poetry and a visit to the
Senate to campaign for more protection for films. He recalled the
premiere of ``Mr. Smith Goes to Washington'' at Constitution Hall in
1939. The invited senators became restive at the film's depiction of
political corruption.
   The film broke during the screening, Stewart recalled, and by the
time Capra returned to his seat after climbing to the projection
booth to repair it, ``half his audience was gone. ... The press was
completely against the picture, too.''
   ``The main thing is that Frank is still here to enjoy his
vindication,'' said the actor. Capra has been in failing health at
his home in La Quinta, Calif.
   Wilder was his usual acerbic self in calling for greater
protection for films: ``The television people call in a butcher, who
has failed at the Ralphs grocery store, to supervise the cutting of
pictures so they can slip in the Noxema commercials. Frankly, nobody
gives a ----.''
   The list of 25 offers some surprises, especially ``The Learning
Tree,'' as well as glaring omissions.
   D.W. Griffith's mishmash of history, ``Intolerance,'' was
selected, but not his great classic, ``The Birth of a Nation,''
perhaps because of its sympathetic portrayal of the Ku Klux Klan.
   King Vidor's ``The Crowd'' was included but not his more
impressive achievement, ``The Big Parade.'' John Ford Westerns are
represented by ``The Searchers'' and not his landmark ``Stagecoach.''
   Other debatable choices: Robert Flaherty's 1922 documentary,
``Nanook of the North''; Stanley Kubrick's 1964 ``Dr. Strangelove'';
F. W. Murnau's 1927 ``Sunrise.'' Among the missing: ``The Treasure
of the Sierra Madre''; ``It's a Wonderful Life''; ``It Happened One
Night''; ``All about Eve''; ``Shane''; ``Top Hat''; ``The African
Queen''; ``Rebecca''; ``From Here to Eternity.''
   Besides Wilder, double selections were Victor Fleming, who
directed both ``Gone with the Wind'' and ``The Wizard of Oz'' in
1939, and Ford, ``The Grapes of Wrath'' and ``The Searchers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890919-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 2130EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Inflation 1stLd-Writethru a0593 09-19 0817</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inflation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0593,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inflation Flat in August, Under 5 Percent So Far This Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS 1 graf after 5th graf pvs, bgng: ``With the...'' to
add April 1986 performance; picks up 6th graf pvs, bgng: ``In another...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices did not rise at all last month
as big declines in the cost of gasoline and women's clothing
combined to provide the best news on inflation since early 1986, the
government said Tuesday.
   The August performance of the Labor Department's Consumer Price
Index followed modest increases of 0.2 percent in both June and July
and left analysts marveling at the better-than-expected showing on
inflation.
   ``The August inflation result was outstanding from the point of
view of the consumer,'' said Allen Sinai, chief economist of the
Boston Co. ``The bread-and-butter categories of food, housing,
transportation and clothing showed either big declines or very small
increases.''
   The modest price increases starting in June represented a sharp
contrast from the first part of the year, when surges in energy and
food costs pushed inflation up to a disturbing annual rate of 6.7
percent.
   With the string of good reports, consumer prices are now rising
at an annual rate of 4.8 percent, up only slightly from the 4.4
percent increases registered in both 1987 and 1988.
   The inflation rate fell by 0.3 percent in April 1986.
   In another economic report Tuesday, the government said that
construction of new homes and apartments dropped by 5 percent in
August, falling to an annual rate of 1.35 million units.
   Economists blamed increases in mortgage rates during August for
the setback. They said that the improved outlook for inflation
should help push mortgage rates down in coming months and should
keep the housing market from going into a tailspin.
   ``Builders saw rates rising and got a case of the jitters, but we
think that interest rates will start moving down again in the months
ahead as various indicators suggest that the inflation threat is
subsiding very quickly,'' said Richard Peach, senior economist at
the Mortgage Bankers Association.
   The Bush administration is predicting a 5 percent inflation rate
for this year, a view supported by many private economists, who
believe that recent increases in crude oil prices will translate
into slighlty higher monthly inflation numbers for the remainder of
the year.
   ``We think that inflation is probably going to move up a little
bit, but we are not looking for anything like the surge we had at
the beginning of 1989,'' said David Berson, chief economist of the
Federal National Mortgage Corp.
   Donald Ratajczak, director of the economic forecasting project at
Georgia State University, said that the underlying inflation rate is
running between 4 percent and 4.5 percent, where it has been for
much of this decade.
   For August, the main moderating force on prices was a steep 4.2
percent plunge in gasoline prices. It was the biggest one-month
decrease in pump prices in three years and followed smaller declines
of 1 percent in June and 2.2 percent in July. Gasoline prices had
shot up 21.2 percent in the first five months of the year.
   Also holding down prices was a 1.5 percent drop in clothing
prices in August, led by a big drop in women's clothing costs. The
decline was credited to larger than normal end-of-season price cuts
and the effect of the stronger dollar, which makes imported goods
less expensive.
   Food costs, which shot up at an annual rate of 9.3 percent at the
beginning of the year because of the lingering effects of the 1988
drought, were well behaved in August, posting a small 0.2 percent
rise.
   Declines in the cost of pork, poultry, fruits and vegetables
helped offset higher prices for beef, fish and eggs.
   Overall transportation costs fell 1.5 percent in August,
reflecting not only the drop in gasoline prices but also declines in
the cost of new and used cars.
   One of the few categories failing to show price moderation during
the month was the cost of medical care, which climbed by 0.7 percent
for the fourth month in a row.
   The price of all goods and services excluding food and energy
rose just 0.2 percent last month, a modest increase which gave
analysts encouragement that the underlying inflation rate is
returning to a more moderate pace as well.
   Analysts said despite the good inflation news, they were not
looking for any immediate move on the part of the Federal Reserve to
lower interest rates. They said that despite the moderating
inflationary pressures, the Fed was under no pressure to cut
interest rates because the overall economy is moving ahead at a
healthy clip.
   The various changes left the overall Consumer Price Index at
124.6 in August, meaning that a hypothetical marketbasket of goods
costing $100 in the base period of 1982-84 would have cost $124.60
last month.
</TEXT>
