<SECOND>AM-Nursing Home Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0713,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Nurse's Aide Denies Killing Patients</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Defense and ..., to UPDATE with jury recessed
for the night.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former nursing home aide charged
with smothering five patients testified Tuesday that the alleged
murder plot was nothing more than a fictitious game that got out of
hand.
   The defense rested after the testimony of Gwendolyn Graham, who
is charged with five counts of first-degree murder and one count of
conspiracy to murder on allegations she suffocated incapacitated
patients at Alpine Manor Nursing Home in Walker between January and
April 1987.
   Defense and prosecution attorneys later finished their closing
arguments and the case went to the jury, which began deliberationa
before adjourning for the night. If convicted, Graham faces life in
prison without parole.
   Graham, 26, denied killing any patients or knowing of any murders
at the home.
   She testified that her former lesbian lover, nurse's aide
Catherine Wood, often concocted stories and spread rumors, and that
she usually went along to humor her. The alleged murder plot was one
of those ``head games,'' Graham said. ``At first it was a joke.''
   But when Graham began seeing another woman, she said Wood
threatened to ``make someone believe the story that we had been
killing patients.''
   Wood, 27, has pleaded guilty to one count of second-degree murder
and one count of conspiracy to murder. In exchange for her testimony
against Graham, two counts of first-degree murder were dropped. Wood
will be sentenced later.
   When police began investigating the deaths after Graham moved
back to her hometown of Tyler, Texas, with the other woman, she said
she realized that Wood ``was going to get even, just like she said
she was.''
   Graham's testimony disputed that of several of her friends and
former lovers, who testified that Graham, on separate occasions, had
admitted suffocating patients at the home.
   Graham said she did not admit killing patients, but related the
story as one Wood had made up. Graham said she only once claimed to
have suffocated patients in an effort to scare another woman, she
said.
   Graham said she decided to leave Wood for another lover because
``I was tired of playing games, hurting people. ... The games just
got out of hand.''
   Graham testified that Wood dominated their relationship, often
starting fights between Graham and other women and once threatening
Graham with a gun. The testimony contrasted Wood's account of the
affair.
   During closing arguments, the prosecutor told the jury that the
case was not a ``referendum on homosexuality.''
   Wood testified that Graham said the killings ``relieved tension.''
</TEXT>
