<FIRST>r a AM-SchoolHostages     09-19 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Hostages,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen Pleads Guilty in Hostage-Taking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>McKEE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen who held 11 students hostage pleaded
guilty Tuesday to kidnapping and endangerment charges and was placed
in state custody for psychological tests, and his classmates
expressed compassion instead of anger.
   ``Nobody seems mad at him,'' said James Issacs, a senior at
Jackson County High School, where the 10-hour standoff Monday ended
peacefully.
   Dustin Pierce, 17, pleaded guilty Tuesday to 13 counts of wanton
endangerment and 13 counts of kidnapping Tuesday, said LaDonna
Williams, a state police dispatcher in Richmond.
   The two additional charges involve a teacher who was released at
the start of the incident; and another student who was held
overnight.
   Police said Pierce took 11 hostages at his high school in a
desperate plea to see his distant father. State Police Detective Bob
Stephens said the incident was a plot directly from Stephen King's
thriller novel, ``Rage.''
   The book, found in Pierce's room at his grandparent's house,
centers on a teen-ager enraged with his father who takes hostages at
a school.
   Pierce, who was armed with two pistols and a shotgun, released
the hostages sporadically, then surrendered. Authorities arranged
for his father to come to Kentucky from his Florida home, but the
boy gave up before his father arrived.
   Interviews with Pierce's classmates and others in this town of
1,000 about 65 miles southeast of Lexington depicted a well-behaved,
quiet teen-ager, a straight-A student.
   ``It's just a mystery, the way it happened,'' said Bruce Neeley,
a Jackson County deputy sheriff. Neeley said officers never had any
problem with Pierce.
   ``He's a real good boy,'' he added.
   Eight counselors were brought to the high school to help students
deal with the aftermath of the hostage-takinga. Pierce blew out a
classroom window with a shotgun blast shortly after taking over his
world civilization class.
   Neither Pierce nor any of the hostages were injured.
   ``Everybody is feeling sorry for him and what he's going
through,'' said Shane Harrison, 17. He said he hoped Pierce would
receive help ``to see what caused it and prevent it from ever
happening again.''
   Betty Bond, principal at the 500-student school, said students
voiced their concern for Pierce rather than anger.
   ``They're already wanting to know if we have heard from (Pierce)
today, how he's doing, can we send him a card, a letter, a video,
anything to let him know that we still care about him, that he is
still our friend,'' said Mrs. Bond.
   She expected students to show some compassion for the youth, but
said she was surprised ``for it to be as strong as it is.''
   Pierce was placed in the custody of the state Cabinet for Human
Resources for psychological tests. He was taken to a treatment
center in Louisville after pleading guilty Tuesday.
</TEXT>
