<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 2211EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Shoreham     09-19 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shoreham,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>NRC Won't Stop Decommissioning Work at Shoreham</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission sees no need
to stop Long Island Lighting Co. from getting ready to decommission
the new Shoreham nuclear power plant in New York, the commission
said in a letter released Tuesday.
   Energy Secretary James D. Watkins has vowed to try to keep the
plant intact, and had asked the commission to stop the company from
dsiabling the reactor before the commission could rule on the
transfer of its operating license to local and state authorities for
decommissioning.
   ``Although LILCO has indicated its intent not to operate Shoreham
and the agreement between LILCO and the state of New York indicates
an intent to decommission the facility, thus far the activities that
LILCO is carrying out are authorized under the existing license,''
Kenneth M. Carr, the commission chairman, said in a Sept. 15 letter
to Watkins.
   Watkins has also called for a full environmental review of the
shutdown plan in an effort to compel New York to keep the plant in
mothballs.
   Carr assured Watkins that the plant would not be allowed to
deteriorate while the commission considers whether to transfer its
license to the Long Island Power Authority. That authority plans to
hire the New York Power Authority to do the actual decommissioning
work.
   The company has removed fuel from the reactor and cut staff,
spurring complaints from Watkins. Carr wrote, ``We do not believe
that reduction in staff at the facility warrants enforcement or
sanction.''
   The fully licensed plant, about 50 miles east of New York City,
has never operated commercially. Gov. Mario Cuomo negotiated a plan
to buy the plant for $1 in order to tear it down, maintaining that
the area could not be safely evacuated in the event of an accident.
In return, LILCO will get a decade of approximately 5 percent annual
rate increases.
</TEXT>
