<FIRST>r a AM-ScoutSlain     09-19 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scout Slain,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sheriff's Anti-Gang Scout Slain In Drive-By Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sheriff's Explorer Scout who touted the
anti-gang message was shot down half a block from his home in a
drive-by shooting, a victim of the raging violence he fought to stop.
   No arrests had been made Tuesday afternoon in the slaying of
Anthony Jerome Gardner, 19, who was shot to death at 1:15 p.m.
Monday by several gang members inside a Cadillac, said Deputy Chris
Wahla.
   Gardner was hit several times in the chest and died at Robert F.
Kennedy Memorial Hospital.
   ``He's seen the streets, he knows what's out there. He knew what
the risks were,'' said Deputy Danny Bullock, an adviser for the
Explorer Scout program at the sheriff's station in Carson, where
Gardner worked as a volunteer.
   Gardner, a minister's son who aspired to a career with the
sheriff's department, had received death threats from gang members,
neighbors said.
   He diligently warned children and residents to stay indoors when
street thugs were on the prowl.
   ``Anthony was very strong on assisting others in staying out of
gang associations,'' said Carson Sgt. Tom Diviak, supervisor in
charge of the scouts. ``He was very outspoken against gangs, that's
the best way of putting it.''
   Bullock stressed that scouts are not told to take a stance
against street hoodlums because of the danger they could face.
   ``We really warn them against telling anyone of their even being
an Explorer,'' Bullock said. ``Anthony did this on his own. He
donated a lot of his time helping deputies. He was a second pair of
eyes in the (patrol) vehicle.''
   Gardner, who planned to enter the Sheriff's Academy on Nov. 17,
conducted his own patrols in his crime-ridden South Los Angeles
neighborhood, said Deputy Bill Wehner.
   Damion Muldrew, 12, said Gardner had warned neighborhood kids
just days before about possible gang retaliation because of his
warnings. ``He said watch out, some gang bangers were trying to kill
him,'' Muldrew said.
   A University High School student who graduated with a 3.7 grade
point average, Gardner became an Explorer Scout in 1986. After
completing the youth citizenship training program, he worked as a
volunteer at the Carson station.
   Gardner also was an active member of the Independent Baptist
Church, where his father, the Rev. Donald Gardner, preached.
</TEXT>
