<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 2233EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Assembly     09-19 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Assembly,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nigerian Who Served in U.N. Peace Force Elected Assembly President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph Garba of Nigeria, a retired army
general who once served in a U.N. peackeeping force, on Tuesday
became president of the General Assembly.
   In a news conference prior to Tuesday's opening of the United
Nation's 44th session, Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
said, ``I think that in the present General Assembly, there are
subjects of great importance politically. There is Namibia, the
Middle East, Afghanistan, Iran-Iraq, Kampuchea (Cambodia), Western
Sahara, Central America, and Cyprus.
   ``On the social aspect, I think it is extremely important that
this year the General Assembly gives importance to real social
questions. Not only human rights, which always is reserved in first
place in our concerns, but the environment, AIDS and terrorism,'' he
said.
   Rain forests were added to the agenda by environmentalists who
pushed 12 wheelbarrows into the marble lobby of the U.N.
headquarters and dumped petitions with 3 million signatures asking
the world body to save the forests.
   Organizers from the World Rainforest Movement refused to leave
without personally meeting Perez de Cuellar. U.N. officials,
confronted by mounds of paper that the organizers said were
petitions from 23 countries, arranged a meeting with the
secretary-general.
   He met with a delegation of representatives from Malaysia, Brazil
India and Britain.
   The Malaysia-based World Rainforest Movement, which says it
represents 60 nongovernmental organizations, is seeking a special
General Assembly session to halt the destruction of rain forests.
   A special session of the 159-nation assembly only can be called
at the request of a majority of its member governments and a costly
special session is considered unlikely.
   Garba, 46, is Nigeria's ambassador to the United Nations.
   He is a former foreign minister and has been chairman of the U.N.
Special Committee Against Apartheid and the U.N. Special Committee
on Peacekeeping Operations.
   Under a system of rotating regional representation, the African
nations nominated the assembly president this year and Garba was
chosen over Paul Engo, Cameroon's ambassador.
   Garba retired from the army in 1980 with the rank of major
general.
   In his address to the assembly he said, ``At the age of 22, as a
captain in the Nigerian army, I participated in the U.N.
India-Pakistan Observer Mission, where I donned the blue helmet for
the first time. That operation enabled me to appreciate first-hand
the laudable role of the United Nations in conflict resolutions.''
   That observer group has monitored the truce between Pakistan and
India since 1949.
   Garba said international peace cannot be secure in a world in
which nations' economies are in decline and inequity exists between
classes and states.
   ``There is now widespread recognition that the external debt
crisis has economic, political and social consequences,'' he said.
   He called for the World Bank and International Monetary Fund as
well as major donor countries to provide resources for debt
reduction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
