<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia 2ndLd-Writethru a0729 09-19 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0729,0752</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Issues Arrest Warrants for Israelis</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with British envoy's comments, cocaine
seized, details. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombia has issued arrest warrants for
two Israelis accused of training hit squads for the drug cartels
waging war on the government, an official said Tuesday.
   Acting on a request by the Department of Administrative Security,
Colombia's equivalent of the FBI, a judge issued the warrants Monday
night for a former Israeli army colonel, Yair Klein, and businessman
Arik Acek.
   ``They are wanted for violating laws against conspiring, teaching
and enlisting civilians in military operations without the approval
of the Defense Ministry,'' said security department spokeswoman
Divas Rojas.
   An Israeli Embassy official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Israel has no extradition treaty with Colombia. ``The
ambassador has been very clear about this,'' he added.
   He said Israeli police have concluded an investigation into the
Klein case and the Supreme Court there has to decide what, if any
action to take. Five other Israelis suspected of training gunmen for
the cartels also were investigated.
   Ms. Rojas said Klein and Acek are thought to have entered
Colombia in August 1988 and to have left the country this year after
reports surfaced that foreign mercenaries were training private
armies for the drug lords, mostly in the Magadelena Medio region in
mountainous, central Colombia.
   British Ambassador Richard Neilson said on Colombian TV on
Tuesday that British and Colombian intelligence had information in
March about British and Israeli mercenaries training assassination
squads for the cartels.
   ``The governmemt of Colombia had information about British
mercenaries in Colombia in March and we were in position to help
them (the government),'' he said.
   He said Britain will try to extradite any British who helped
traffickers train paramilitary groups, but it was not known how many
British may have been involved.
   Klein, now home in Tel Aviv, has said he trained Colombian
farmers to protect themselves against leftist guerrillas. He said he
was unaware they had any involvement with drugs.
   In the northern coastal city of Barranquilla, an army raid
Tuesday in the house of the manager of a milk company turned up a
ton of pure cocaine. Four people were arrested. The owner, Pedro
Rodriguez Munoz, was not at home.
   In Venezuela, police said they would release a man who was
arrested at a ranch near the Colombian border because he bore a
``strong resemblance'' to Jose Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha, a top leader
of Colombia's Medellin cocaine cartel.
   Humberto Giffuni, deputy director of Venezuela's Judicial
Technical Police, said the man and three people arrested with him
Monday would be freed immediately.
   The drug war took a new twist Monday night when a bomb went off
in front of a crowded shopping center in the capital, Bogota.
Another bomb damaged a Bogota telephone company outlet.
   It was the first time a bomb was placed in the early evening in a
populated area. Four people, including a child, were injured.
   Since the crackdown on drug cartels was launched, most bombing
targets have been banks and government buildings and most explosions
went off late at night, when no one was around.
   In the past three weeks, 45 bombs have gone off in Colombia,
killing four people and injuring 118. No one claimed responsibility,
but officials blamed drug barons.
   President Virgilio Barco announced the crackdown after leading
presidential candidate Sen. Luis Carlos Galan was assassinated Aug.
18.
   Barco vowed to extradite traffickers wanted in the United States.
   Colombian Eduardo Martinez Romero was extradited Sept. 6 to
Atlanta in connection with the laundering of more than $1.2 billion
for the Medellin cartel.
   Two other alleged drug traffickers were arrested last week and
await extradition to the United States.
   But drug kingpins on the United States' list of the most wanted,
the so-called ``Dirty Dozen,'' remain at large and there is no
indication the government is close to arresting them.
   Colombia's attorney general, Alfonseo Gomez Mendez, said Tuesday
that is because drug traffickers have infiltrated the army and
national police.
   ``It's not for lack of military power that the big
narco-traffickers haven't been captured,'' Gomez said in an
interview with the radio chain Caracol. ``It's because they have
informants inside the police and army who warn them when there will
be operations to arrest them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
