<SECOND>AM-Zsa Zsa Trial, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0780,0828</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zsa Zsa Breaks Down in Courtroom Sobs, Can't Take `Lies'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to correct writethru sequence; leads with 7 grafs
to UPDATE with officer injured in accident; picks up 4th graf pvs: ``I'm
a ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Zsa Zsa Gabor took the stand
in her cop-slapping trial Tueday, telling a jury she feared she
would be shot by a towering motorcycle officer who handcuffed her
while she was ``screaming like a pig.''
   In a trial dominated by her flamboyant behavior, another bizarre
development occurred Tuesday, the same day Miss Gabor ran from the
courtroom, hearing testimony she didn't like.
   On Tuesday afternoon, Officer Paul Kramer, the officer who
arrested her on June 14, was hospitalized in stable condition
Tuesday after his motorcyle collided with a police car.
   During an emergency call, Kramer's cycle collided with a police
car at the at Rodeo Drive intersection. He was admitted to UCLA
Medical Center in Westwood, where he was in stable condition with
head trauma, severe scrapes and bruises.
   Kramer had already testified, but might be needed for further
testimony. It was not immediately known what effect his injury might
have on Miss Gabor's trial.
   Earlier Tuesday, Miss Gabor collapsed in sobs after stomping out
of court during one policeman's testimony that immediately was
branded a lie by the star of such films as ``Picture Mommy Dead''
and ``Queen of Outer Space.''
   In afternoon testimony, the actress acknowledged scuffling with
Kramer, the 6-foot-4 motorcycle cop who pulled her over on a traffic
stop.
   ``I'm a Hungarian woman ... not a milquetoast.'' But she said she
came to fear the motorcycle officer more than she feared Nazis
during World War II.
   The Beverly Hills officer actually stopped her twice the day of
her June 14 arrest, the second time after she drove away as he
attempted to cite her. When he closed on her a second time, she
testified she feared he was going to shoot her.
   ``I was saying to myself `Uh oh, Zsa Zsa Gabor. Now you've had
it.'''
   She said she sat on a curb, handcuffed. ``I was screaming like a
pig,'' she said.
   Earlier in the day, Miss Gabor bolted from the courtroom when she
disagreed with testimony from another officer who assisted in the
arrest.
   ``I can't take this. It's a lie,'' Miss Gabor blurted as she left
the courtroom seven days into her misdemeanor trial.
   Defense attorney William Graysen immediately led his client back
into the courtroom and she broke down in sobs. Municipal Judge
Charles G. Rubin ordered a recess while the former Miss Hungary
regained her composure.
   The outburst came during testimony by police officer Scott
Thompson, who was called to assist the motorcycle officer Miss Gabor
admitted striking on June 14. Thompson said Miss Gabor cursed him.
   ``She looked at me and said, `You (expletive), I'm having your
job. I'm calling the Reagans on this,''' Thompson testified. Miss
Gabor, a longtime friend and neighbor of the former president, got
up and left at that point.
   Miss Gabor had been relatively calm during the trial, doodling on
a pad and sketching pencil portraits of the judge, clerk, bailiff
and even a respectable rendition of Officer Paul Kramer, the
policeman she struck.
   Her sharp-tongued, out-of-court commentaries to reporters were
finally muzzled by the judge after Deputy District Attorney Elden
Fox complained the actress was violating a gag order in the case.
   ``I have a gagging order,'' Miss Gabor said when questioned as
she left the courthouse Monday night.
   Miss Gabor is charged with battery on a police officer,
disobeying an officer's orders, driving with an expired license and
having an open container of alcohol _ a flask of Jack Daniels
whiskey in the glove compartment _ in her car.
   Kramer testified he was surprised Miss Gabor struck him, saying
the assault was unprovoked. Miss Gabor, a foot shorter and 100
pounds lighter than Kramer, said she struck in self-defense.
   Graysen is expected to contend that Kramer allegedly had a prior
history of being abusive with citizens pulled over for traffic stops.
   If convicted, Miss Gabor faces up to 18 months in jail. Graysen
said he will conclude his case with testimony from Miss Gabor. She
was expected to take the stand Friday or early next week.
   Unable to discuss the case directly, Miss Gabor said last week
she feared jail because they are filled with lesbians. ``I'm afraid
of lesbians,'' she blurted out.
   Before her courtroom collapse, Miss Gabor told reporters that a
homosexual group wrote to protest the remarks.
   ``I never said anything about lesbians. I got a letter from the
lesbians. They are outraged. I have so many friends who are. ... I
don't care who is what, I only like good people.''
</TEXT>
