<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 2303EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua-Carter 2ndLd-Writethru a0753 09-19 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Carter, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0753,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jimmy Carter Negotiates Indian Leader's Return</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS election date in 2nd graf, Under the ... from Feb.
5 to Feb. 25. Picks up 3rd graf, Carter said ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MGA1,2 of Sept. 18</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PUERTO CABEZAS, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jimmy Carter
has successfully negotiated with the leftist Sandinista government
for the return of a rebel Miskito Indian leader after years of exile.
   Under the deal, the Sandinistas dropped a ban on Brooklyn
Rivera's return to Nicaragua after Rivera agreed to renounce his
fight against the government, refrain from illegal activities and
cooperate in the process to hold general elections Feb 25.
   Carter said Rivera accepted the terms that he and Interior
Minister Tomas Borge agreed to Monday during a visit to this
northeastern seaport. Carter said Rivera would return to Nicaragua
shortly.
   Rivera left Nicaragua in 1981 to lead an Indian armed struggle
against the Sandinistas and has been living in neighboring Costa
Rica, and talks between the government and exiled Miskito leader,
head of the most populous tribe of Nicaraguan Indians, had dragged
for four years.
   Miskito, Sumo and Rama Indian groups, largely English-speaking
communities that live along Nicaragua's Caribbean coast, have been
fighting against the Sandinistas alongside the U.S.-supported Contra
rebels since 1980.
   These are basically the same conditions the Sandinistas set for
the return of non-Indian Contras. Under a previous Sandinista offer,
Rivera was to disarm his followers within 30 days of his return to
Nicaragua.
   Rivera said Tuesday that he expected other Indian leaders,
including Steadman Fagoth and Wycliff Diego, to return. The
agreement, however, was specifically for Rivera.
   Carter announced the agreement on the Rivera issue on his return
to Managua, shortly before heading back to Atlanta.
   The announcement was the highlight of the former president's
three-day trip to Nicaragua as head of a delegation that will
monitor elections in February.
   Carter expressed optimism that the elections would be fair.
   The 14-party National Opposition Union, the strongest challenger
to the Sandinista National Liberation Front, delivered a letter to
President Daniel Ortega accusing the government of failing to live
up to agreements reached last month.
   Carter pointed out that the last paragraph of the letter
reiterated the opposition's willingness to continue taking part in
the electoral process. ``Although there are problems, the agreements
reached ... give us optimism that the elections will be free and
fair,'' he said.
   He said his observer team plans to organize an independent
vote-count on elections night of the elections but will not release
its tallies until after the official returns are announced.
   The Nicaraguan government, the Supreme Electoral Council and the
political opposition invited Carter to observe the elections as
chairman of the Council of Freely Elected Heads of State, an
Atlanta-based organization.
   The United Nations and the Organization of American States also
will also sent observer teams.
   Carter also helped monitor the annulled Panamanian elections
earlier this year and has negotiated with Ethiopian officials and
Eritrean rebels to end their civil war.

</TEXT>
