<DOCNO> AP890919-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 2319EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-CongressionalPay     09-19 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congressional Pay,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel to Recommend 35 Percent Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special bipartisan House task force will
present to the leadership this week a call for a congressional pay
increase of about 35 percent over two years, a congressional said
Tuesday night.
   Other recommendations would end fees for making speeches and the
conversion of campaign funds to personal use.
   The source, who is in a position to know the recommendations and
who spoke on condition of anonymity, cautioned that the entire
package of rules changes planned by the task force could be changed
before it is proposed to the full House, which must be done by the
end of October.
   The heart of the package is the pay plan, which would include
about a 10 percent raise in 1990 and an additional 25 percent in
1991. After 1991, members would get cost-of-living pay increases.
   House and Senate members currently earn $89,500 per year, with
leaders earning more. The Senate would have to approve any pay
increases, which would apply to both bodies. A 35 percent increase
would make the salary $120,825.
   A key part of the plan would phase out honoraria _ fees for
making speeches, often to organizations lobbying for legislation _
over two years. Since House members now can keep honoraria totaling
30 percent of their pay, the 35 percent salary increase would mean
no member would lose money by the phase-out.
   The honoraria system has been much criticized by watchdog
organizations such as Common Cause. Critics say the fees, limited to
$2,000 per occasion, too often amount to a reward just for showing
up, sometimes at conventions at plush resorts for which the member's
expenses are picked up by the sponsors.
   The plan also would phase out the ``grandfather clause'' under
which members who were in Congress in January 1980 can convert
leftover campaign funds to personal use when they retire. The date
when the prohibition would take full effect has not been settled,
the source said.
   Other provisions of the package call for tightening requirements
to disclose gifts.
   The ethics panel was appointed by former Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas, after lawmakers earlier this year fought a bitter, divisive
battle over a proposed 51 percent pay raise that was rejected after
a campaign led by consumer advocate Ralph Nader and others who
argued that it was excessive.
   The 51 percent proposal came from an advisory commission and was
recommended by President Reagan. It would have taken effect without
a vote unless rejected by Congress. Wright had devised a plan to
raise salaries by 30 percent in return for dropping honoraria, but
House members overwhelmingly voted to reject such a plan.
   Backers of a raise say members have not taken cost-of-living
increases in recent years and need a substantial increase to catch
up with inflation. Many members feel they must maintain two homes,
one in Washington and one in their districts, and face expenses that
others with similar salaries don't have, the supporters say.
   The task force of 10 members is equally divided between the
parties and chaired by Reps. Vic Fazio, D-Calif., and Lynn Martin,
R-Ill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
