<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--Krishna-Airports     09-19 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Krishna-Airports,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rule Against Giving Out Literature Found Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The three airports serving New York City cannot
prevent people from giving out literature and asking for
contributions, a federal judge ruled.
   The decision by U.S. District Judge Mary Johnson Lowe came in a
1975 suit brought by the International Society for Krishna
Consciousness Inc. against the Port Authority of New York and New
Jersey.
   Lowe on Monday adopted a magistrate's recommendation that the
Port Authority regulation, which prohibited ``continuous and
repetitive'' solicitation, violated the First Amendment rights of
Krishna members, who give out literature about their religion and
ask for contributions.
   Arthur Berg, a Port Authority lawyer, said the ruling would not
be immediately noticeable at Kennedy, LaGuardia and Newark airports
because an interim agreement with the Krishnas allowed two
representatives at each airport while the case was pending.
   He said the agreement would likely continue during the appeal.
``We do not believe airports are a public forum,'' Berg said.
</TEXT>
