<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1109EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-Egypt-TabaResort Adv26   09-19 0705</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Egypt-Taba Resort, Adv 26,0728</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs Sept. 26 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Egypt Now Runs Sinai Beach Resort But Clientele Remains Israeli</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEJLA SAMMAKIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year ago, international arbitration ended
the last border dispute between Egypt and Israel, a squabble over a
250-acre strip of beach and the plush hotel on it.
   Israel lost.
   Now, six months after the Israelis ceded Taba to Egypt, the
former Aviya-Sonesta Beach Hotel is struggling to develop an
Egyptian image while catering to its main clientele, Israelis.
   ``It's still the same hotel,'' said Joe Sultan, the general
manager through successive owners and management chains. But, he
said, ``instead of a waiter called Moshe, we now have Moussa.''
   Opened in 1982 by its builder, the Egyptian-born Israeli Eli
Papouchado, the 10-story, 327-room luxury hotel has panoramic views
of the Gulf of Aqaba and the Sinai Peninsula's rugged mountains. It
quickly became a favorite among Israelis whose army seized the Sinai
in the Arab-Israeli war of 1967.
   Although Taba had been in dispute since early 1982 when Israel
refused to return it with the rest of Sinai under terms of a 1979
peace agreement, Israelis nonetheless were shocked on Sept. 29,
1988, to find the place no longer belonged to them. After
deliberating 18 months, international arbitrators ruled that
Egyptian claims prevailed and ordered Israel to end its occupation.
   Months of haggling followed over special facilities for Israeli
tourists and compensation to owner Papouchado _ the settlement was
$37 million _ but Egypt finally raised its flag over Taba on March
15.
   Egyptian nationals marched into the hotel, Taba's only
significant structure, to claim jobs.
   Outside, Israeli employees burned street barricades of automobile
tires and demonstrated to protest their uncertain future. About 280
of the 306 Israeli workers last March have been laid off to comply
with Egyptian law that limits foreign employment to 10 percent of
the work force.
   But manager Sultan said in a telephone interview the hotel staff
has become a model of co-existence.
   ``This is beautiful,'' he said. ``I wish the governments would
take an example from the harmony.''
   Many details remained unsettled and confusion reigned at the
turnover in March, but much of that has dissipated as technical
problems have been ironed out.
   Israelis stayed away in the first weeks after the turnover, and
the hotel's occupancy rate fell from better than 90 percent to
around 40 percent. Sultan said that by August it had recovered much
of the lost ground.
   Hotel shopowners, mostly Israelis, feared working under Egypt's
more stringent import controls, but they've settled into their new
state of affairs.
   Prices on menus are being changed gradually to Egyptian pounds
from Israeli shekels and U.S. dollars.
   Taba, at the northern tip of the Gulf of Aqaba, 230 miles east of
Cairo, was a wasteland at the end of a desert wadi when Israel
captured the Sinai in the 1967 war.
   Thus, Egypt has no infrastructure there to support the hotel and
must buy water, electricity and some goods from Israel. Taba's
telephone lines are linked through Israel.
   And because there is no housing at Taba other than the hotel,
Egyptian employees must travel 90 miles a day to and from Nuweiba to
go to work.
   The 28 Israeli employees commute from Eilat, the Israeli port
which is close by. They work in positions where Hebrew is necessary
to communicate with patrons.
   The Egyptian personnel manager, Aly Abdel-Aziz, said Israeli
singers and two belly dancers still perform but with fewer Hebrew
songs.
   Although their flag flies over Taba now, Egyptians haven't
flocked to the resort.
   One reason may be room rates of $150 a night. Few Egyptians can
afford even the reduced rate of $54, which is high for a country
with an average monthly take-home pay of $40.
   But Fuad Sultan, Egypt's tourism minister, said plans are under
way to promote Taba worldwide as a warm-weather resort and to equip
a nearby landing strip for large airplanes.
   ``Until Taba was returned to Egypt, it was only a satellite of
Eilat,'' he said.
   ``Now it's our goal to create something that says, `This is
really Egypt.'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs Sept. 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
