<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv20   09-19 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 20,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release PMs Wednesday, Sept. 20</HEAD>
<HEAD>Refinance The House?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indications from around the country show many
homeowners still anxious to exchange variable rate mortgages for
fixed-rate loans, even if the numbers might not add up.
   For many people, they really don't.
   Is it worthwhile for you to dump your existing mortgage in order
to save two percentage points? Even if the lower rate cuts your
monthly payments by enough to allow you to put money in the bank or
go out once or twice a month?
   Maybe not, even if your friends, financial counselor, neighbors
and spouse say go ahead. If you do, be sure you know the cost, the
length of time you'll be keeping the mortgage, and a lot about your
local market.
   1. To refinance usually means a fee of 1 percent or 2 percent of
the total mortgage, and sometimes as much 3 percent. These are
points, but seldom are they the only charge.
   The additional charges might include origination, application,
appraisal, legal and other fees. In some instances they can add
another 1.5 percent of the mortgage amount. If so, your upfront
total is then 3.5 points.
   The cost of these fees should make you think again, especially if
you are remortgaging to lower your interest charges by just one or
two percentage points. The charges might be heftier than the savings.
   Sears Mortgage Corp. offers this formula to clarify your thinking:
   _Add the points being charged by the lender to the total amount
of fees, expressed in points. Two points plus another 1.5 points for
fees is your total upfront cost.
   _Determine the difference between the interest rate you are now
paying and the rate being offered. If you are paying 11.5 percent
currently and have the opportunity for a new rate of 9.5 percent
(unlikely), your answer is 2.
   _Divide that 2, or whatever number applies, into the total points.
   The answer will be the number of years required for you to break
even _ that is, to pay off the points. Thereafter, you are ahead of
the game. But up to that point you are behind.
   If you were saving just one percentage point of interest, and
your total points was 3.5, it would take you 3.5 years to break
even. If you were paying 4.5 points, it would take you about 4.5
years to break even.
   2. These factors have special meanings, depending on the owner's
age and likelihood of remaining in the house. Relatively few people
pay off mortgages. At times, the average mortgage has had a life
span of just seven years.
   3. All this should be considered in relation to what's happening
in your local market, not just on what you hear about national
averages. Prices vary from one neighborhood to another, interest
rates from one city to another.
   Never forget that real estate markets are cyclical. More so than
almost any other segment of the economy, they have ups and downs.
   If your area is down and likely to fall further, then interest
rates might also fall, even if only by a fraction of a point. More
importantly, your lender might become friendlier, perhaps even
knocking off one full point.
   Try to get a feel for what might happen nationally too. If you
think rates will fall, you might consider delaying your refinancing.
The opposite, of course, also applies: Act quickly if you're not
likely to get better terms.
   These factors are extremely important in determing whether to
stay with a variable rate mortgage or transfer to a fixed. If rates
rise, your fixed loan doesn't. If rates fall, you remain at the
higher rate. And vice versa.
   Finally, the best deal might be with your current lender. Lenders
don't like to lose good customers. Conceivably, they might make you
an offer you cannot refuse.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday, Sept. 20.</NOTE>
</DOC>
