<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Agents Adv21   09-19 1177</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Agents, Adv 21,1206</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday AMs, Sept. 21, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hollywood's Superagents: Creative Forces or Money Grubbers?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even in a city where titanic deals are fairly
ordinary, the one the William Morris talent agency cut for itself on
``The Cosby Show'' was a whopper.
   For simply introducing Bill Cosby to the show's producers,
William Morris negotiated a contract bringing the agency 10 percent
of every dollar ``The Cosby Show'' generates, a windfall in excess
of $100 million since 1984.
   The pact dramatizes the power that agencies like William Morris,
the Creative Artists Agency and International Creative Management
now wield in Hollywood, especially through packaging TV shows.
   With packaging, a longtime practice in the movie industry, agents
deliver the key ingredients for a hit movie or TV series. However,
packaging also sometimes provides agents with extravagant payments _
usually a percentage of a show's revenues _ for little more than
introducing one agency client to a producer.
   For some, the practice smacks of artistic extortion, and those
involved in making deals are reluctant to talk about it.
   ``It's Al Capone saying, `Fellas, you wanna open a bar in South
Chicago? This is the deal: My beer. My laundry. My glasses. My
bartender. My union. My trucks,''' said a top TV writer-producer who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   What bothers the production community is that package fees come
from the production itself, taking away funds that could help make a
better project. And for some producers, paying a package commission
can mean the difference between profit and loss.
   ``I think (packaging) is absolutely the worst waste of money that
you could possibly imagine,'' said writer-producer Danny Arnold, one
of the few who would allow his name to be used. ``I think it's an
extortion ... and one of the worst abuses in this business.''
Arnold, whose credits include the old TV series ``Barney Miller,''
``Bewitched'' and ``That Girl,'' recently signed a deal with Disney
Co. to create TV and movie products.
   At one time, and occasionally today, television packaging
represented a real service. A packaged show _ a Perry Como or Danny
Thomas special, ``The Dick Van Dyke Show'' _ might have included a
writer, a director, a star, other related talent and perhaps even
advertisers, bookkeepers and lawyers.
   The movie business still represents an area in which packagers
serve an essential role. For no extra fee _ no package commission _
agents bring together several clients to form an outstanding team.
Such was the case with Oliver Stone and the cast of ``Platoon,'' and
the recent ``Mississippi Burning'' and ``Rain Man.''
   Network executives say privately that as much as they despise
television packaging, they are reluctant to do anything about it
because if one network stops the practice, another network will
accept the deals.
   CBS, however, was so concerned about packaging fees that it held
discussions during last year's writers strike to see whether the
strike could be settled if packaging fees were abolished. The talks
failed to result in any action.
   Several top producers maintain that the three top agencies _
William Morris, CAA and ICM _ sometimes are interested more in
negotiating big packaging commissions for themselves than in
promoting their clients' careers or making good shows.
   ``There are a lot of deals that don't get made that should have
because somebody objects to a package commission,'' said one top TV
executive.
   At least one TV executive has asked California legislators to
address the package issue. But the Department of Industrial
Relations, which regulates agents' fee schedules, does not determine
package fee limits, said spokesman Richard Stevens.
   The top agencies are privately held and declined to be
interviewed. CAA operates with almost comical secrecy. Ray Kurtzman,
head of CAA's business affairs department, would not even decline to
be interviewed unless he could do so off the record.
   Thus, it is hard to pinpoint every packaged show. However,
published reports suggest that ``The Cosby Show,'' ``Roseanne,''
``Golden Girls,'' ``Empty Nest,'' ``Beauty and the Beast'' and ``The
Famous Teddy Z'' are just a few of the packaged shows now on the air.
   The packaged talent in most situation comedies is the
writer-producer. But almost anybody can be packaged in a miniseries
or movie. The payoffs can be tremendous. CAA, more than any other
agency in town, is rolling in money.
   To appreciate CAA's embarrassment of riches, consider the case of
the CAA ficus tree: I.M. Pei, the famed architect who designed the
agency's elaborate new office, selected CAA's huge tree from a
Florida grove and then shipped it to Mexico for a year's
acclimatization.
   The privately held agency, representing more than 600 top clients
like Paul Newman, Bill Murray, Jane Fonda and Madonna, grossed $65
million last year, and CAA president Michael Ovitz himself made $10
million, according to the entertainment industry newsletter Show Biz
News.
   By controlling so many leading actors, writers and directors, the
superagents can cut deals pretty much on their own terms. Producers
not willing to play along often find doors locked.
   Television and movie executives are convinced that anyone
speaking publicly against the superagents will suffer greatly,
perhaps kept from signing an agency's top talent.
   Those few agents who do grant interviews defend packaging, saying
it provides a real service, often helping to create a hit show.
   ``It doesn't need justification, because it works,'' said Arnold
Rifkin, a founder of Triad Artists. ``When a network buys a show
that's successful, they increase their revenues. ... And you've
created that potential for them.''
   Chet Migden, executive director of the Association of Talent
Agents, said package deals generate more work for actors, directors
and writers. ``In order to get work for clients, agents began to
think creatively about putting properties together.''
   Without package fees, agents take a percentage commission _
usually 10 percent _ on their clients' paychecks, and no more. With
packaging fees, agents charge from 6 percent to 10 percent on the
total cost of each and every episode in a TV series.
   With a normal commission, for example, a writer paid $50,000 a
week by a situation comedy would give his agent $5,000 a week. The
packaged clients keep 100 percent of their checks. With a package
deal on that sitcom costing $700,000 a week, the agent collects up
to $70,000 weekly, plus up to 10 percent of everything the series
makes in the fruitful syndication market.
   Producers are trapped by the package commission because networks
will not buy shows unless they have the top talent usually covered
by packages. If one producer refuses to pay a package fee, there is
always another who will.
   ``The agencies aren't fools,'' said one television producer.
``They know if we need these things to make the programs we produce
more noticeable ... they can extract a premium for that.
   ``The networks continue to ask only for the `A' players. ... And
the `A' players are controlled by fewer and fewer agencies.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thurs AMs, Sept. 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
