<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1333EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-DividedChurch Adv24   09-19 1051</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Divided Church, Adv 24 ,1080</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 24, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Christian Churches Divided Along Racial Lines</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<HEAD>By DAVID BRIGGS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   They worked together in the civil rights movement and share a
faith that recognizes no racial boundaries, but Christ's flock in
the United States remains largely divided into black and white sheep.
   Gains in integration in business, government and education have
not been matched in the church, which some observers say may be the
nation's most segregated institution.
   Why?
   ``Isn't it obvious? It's racism. That's what brought about the
black church since its inception _ slavery _ and it hasn't
changed,'' said the Rev. Amos Jones Jr., director of Christian
education for the National Baptist Convention U.S.A. Inc.
   More than seven in 10 black Americans say they are Methodists or
Baptists, according to a 1988 Gallup Poll. Yet, in the nation's
largest Protestant denomination, the 14.8 million-member Southern
Baptist Convention, only an estimated 3 percent are black. In the 9
million-member United Methodist Church, an estimated 4 percent of
members are black.
   In the Roman Catholic Church, a black priest has started his own
church in Washington, D.C., and the nation's black bishops have
condemned racism within the U.S. church, although the 53
million-member body has more black members _ an estimated 2 million
_ than any other predominantly white Christian group.
   The segregation is even greater in the black churches.
   ``A fraction of a fraction of 1 percent'' is the estimated number
of whites in the National Baptist Convention U.S.A. Inc., according
to Jones. Officials in the 3 million-member African Methodist
Episcopal Church estimate one-tenth of 1 percent of its members are
white.
   ``Sunday morning is the most segregated time in the country,''
said the Rev. Charles White, a white Presbyterian pastor who is
co-chairman of the North American Interfaith Network.
   White said there is a profound difference between the teachings
of Christianity and the way it adapts to the society around it.
   ``Religion more often than not serves to bolster our own
identities. If we are at heart racist, and I believe at heart both
blacks and whites are racist, then we ought not to be surprised that
religion bolsters that,'' he said.
   The attempt by the Rev. George A. Stallings to form an
unauthorized parish for black Catholics in Washington is full of
historical precedent. Introduced to Christianity through slavery,
black Americans have for centuries moved away from predominantly
white churches into churches they had more control over and felt
comfortable in.
   Once criticized for serving as a barrier to blacks in their
efforts to make gains in American society, the black church has
enjoyed a resurgence since the late 1960s, when blacks and other
ethnic groups began to question the value of assimilation and place
greater reliance on institutions that preserved their heritage.
   ``In predominantly white groups, people of black heritage often
feel like they're the invisible man. They're there, but not ever
seen,'' said Bishop Cecil Bishop, president of the Board of Bishops
of the African Methodist Episcopal Zion Church.
   Despite the solidarity many within predominantly white churches
showed in the civil rights movement of a generation ago, the racism
that caused the black church remains today, if in more subtle forms,
according to black church leaders.
   Jones said black churches address the needs of black Americans,
while many predominantly white churches embrace the status quo.
   For example, he said, ``Southern Baptists are hard-pressed to say
anything against apartheid, hunger in Mississippi, racism among
elected officials.''
   Some officials in predominantly white churches contend black
churches make exaggerated claims of racism because they are fearful
of losing members to churches actively seeking to integrate their
pews.
   The Southern Baptist Convention is on record as condemning
apartheid, hunger and racism, said the Rev. Sid Smith of that
denomination's Black Church Development Board.
   ``I do not mean to imply we have arrived, for we have not,''
Smith said. ``But we are not the old-school racist denomination of a
generation ago.''
   The black church also is not without its own debates on
prejudice. In the African Methodist Episcopal Church, for example,
there is only one native bishop in the church's six episcopal
districts in Africa. Last year, the church elected three bishops to
serve West Africa, Central Africa and South Africa _ all were from
the United States.
   Robert H. Reid, editor of the A.M.E. Christian Recorder, said
church officials used to say African blacks were not qualified to be
bishops. ``That is no longer true, and that would have been no
longer true for decades,'' he said.
   Still, Jones said, unlike some white churches, the doors of the
black church have always been open.
   ``We've never had a closed-door policy as white Southern
Baptists, southern Methodists, Presbyterians have had. We've been
the ones rejected and turned away,'' Jones said.
   But officials at the nation's largest churches say there has been
some movement toward integration.
   In the Southern Baptist Convention, which split from northern
Baptists in the 1840s because of its defense of slavery, six state
conventions have elected black presidents, and among Protestant
churches, ``we put more money into the black community than any
other denomination today, period,'' Smith said.
   Barbara Ricks Thompson, the general secretary of the Commission
on Religion and Race of the United Methodist Church, said her
denomination is giving blacks greater leadership roles. For example,
while approximately 4 percent of the church members are black, 10 of
the church's 49 active bishops are black.
   As the estimated number of black Catholics has more than doubled
from 900,000 to 2 million in 20 years, the church has established a
national Office for Black Catholics.
   Deacon Ronald Walker, a black clergyman from Buffalo, N.Y.,
recalled his Baptist grandfather telling him, ``Catholicism is the
church that's going to take a mule to heaven.''
   But he stayed within the church, and eventually sought his
vocation there.
   ``I was searching for something all my life. I love the church.
The roots of the church go back to my grandmother and mother,''
Walker said.
   When he was deciding whether to become a deacon, what impressed
him was that ``there was an openness, a reception, and my status as
being black didn't matter.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 24</NOTE>
</DOC>
