<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 0139EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-IndustrialConference     09-19 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Industrial Conference,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sony Chairman Says Trade Imbalance Caused by ``Attractiveness'' of
Goods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trade imbalance between the United
States and Japan is caused by the difference in ``attractiveness''
of the nations' goods, not price, the chairman of Sony Corp. told
world business executives.
   ``The answer does not lie in protection for high-tech
industries,'' Akio Morita said Monday. ``Protectionism runs counter
to free market principles and, with the lack of external
competition, would only encourage inefficient industries, which are
unable to market their products outside of their protected market.
   ``The real key to competitiveness,'' he said, ``lies not in trade
policy but in such areas as increasing investment, strengthening
commercial R&amp;D and above all, increasing the quality and spirit of
the labor force.''
   Akio, speaking to 500 business leaders from 62 countries
attending the International Industrial Conference, said investments
in improving industrial competitiveness must be viewed as a
long-term proposition.
   ``Perhaps my most basic message is that both the U.S. government
and U.S. corporations should shift their time horizons,'' he said.
``Investments are needed today that will pay dividends in 10, 20 or
30 years.''
   Morita also said ``international trade is now being shaken by
emotional politicization of the trade imbalance.''
   ``I must say that the politicians and governments around the
world are not sufficiently aware of the reality of an
ever-developing global-scale economy or a borderless economy,'' he
said. ``The borderless economy has developed in such a speed and
scale exceeding our foresight and imagination.''
   Noting the foreign exchange involving billions of dollars, yen
and German marks, he said imports and exports of tangible goods are
not the only items that generate big money. Intellectual properties,
such as patents, know-how and music, also are valuable, he said.
   ``In my view, bilateral trade is made up of numerous `buy and
sell' transactions between companies in the two nations. An
imbalance is the difference in the sum of these transactions over a
given time.''
   It is important to Americans and the world economy that U.S.
industry regain its competitiveness, he said.
   Later, Jacques Delors, president of the Commission of the
European Communities, discussed the effort to remove trade barriers
between European Community nations by 1992.
   Delors said he saw no reason that the deadline for achieving a
single market would not be reached, despite difficulties in coming
to agreement on the automotive, transportation, energy, and
telecommunications industries.
   ``In those four fields the antagonisms between the nations are
very destructive, and the interests of firms and the interests of
nations are mixed,'' he said. ``I must spend all my time to convince
the 12 governments to fulfill the single market and to not accept
exceptions ... because the advantage of a single market is enormous
in those sectors.''
   Delors provoked nervous laughter among the executives when he
responded to a question about whether Europeans would develop
different trade policies for the United States and Japan.
   ``It depends on the Japanese and the Americans,'' he said. ``For
example, when I explain the process of reciprocity to American
businessmen, they understand. They are very positive about the
concept. Unfortunately, when I explain this global concept to
Japanese, it is more difficult to have an understanding.
   ``And frankly, we must be very tough with the negotiations with
Japan,'' he said, ``because it is very difficult for us, our
businesses, our banks, to penetrate the Japanese market.''
   The remark drew scattered laughs and light applause from the
audience, which included dozens of Japanese _ among them Morita, who
chaired the proceedings and introduced Delors.
   ``Excuse me, but it is a matter of fact,'' Delors said to more
nervous laughter.
   When Delors left the podium, Morita thanked him for his remarks
and added, ``I promise you to make Japanese easier to understand.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890919-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 0141EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-JunkBonds Bjt   09-19 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Junk Bonds, Bjt,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sell-Off in Junk Bonds Could Be Blessing in Disguise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Last week's sharp sell-off in the junk bond
market could be a blessing in disguise for the economy by making it
more difficult for companies to take on much more of the high-cost
debt, some analysts say.
   By scaring off investors, the plunge in junk bonds could make it
nearly impossible for companies to sell new junk issues unless there
is a strong likelihood they are able to make payments on it over the
long run, said John Lonski, senior economist for Moody's Investors
Service.
   ``You can't continue to leverage forever. There has to be some
end to what's taking place, and sooner is better than later,''
Lonski said Monday.
   Issuers of junk bonds _ are high-interest-rate debt securities
often used by companies with poor credit ratings _ must pay high
interest rates to attract investors. In recent years, the securities
have been widely used for such ventures as mergers and acquisitions.
   But if the economy sours, issuers could be forced to default,
adding to the economy's troubles.
   Quoted bids for junk bonds stabilized Monday after last week's
sell-off, although analysts said trading in the most speculative
issues nearly ground to a halt.
   ``People feel it's too late to sell and too early to buy,'' said
Marshall B. Front, an economist at the Chicago investment firm of
Stein Roe &amp; Farnham.
   A cash crunch at Campeau Corp., the Canadian retailing giant,
triggered last week's price plunge, carrying down even relatively
secure issues. Olympia &amp; York Developments Ltd. conditionally agreed
Friday to loan Campeau $250 million in a deal that was expected to
give the Toronto developer greater influence over Campeau's
management and a greater ownership stake.
   After being carried downward by Campeau's problems, the
higher-grade junk bonds such as Stone Container Corp., Kroger Co.,
Owens-Corning Fiberglas Corp. and Harcourt Brace Jovanovich Inc.
were quoted as much as } point higher Monday. A point equals $10 on
a bond with a face value of $1,000.
   Meanwhile, the bid on one issue of Campeau's Allied Stores Corp.
unit was quoted down slightly to 26 cents on the dollar from 27. But
with bond owners not willing to offer the issue at less than 35
cents, there was virtually no trading, market participants said.
   The bid for Campeau's Federated Department Stores Inc. bonds rose
10 to 55, but was still well below the asking price of 65.
   Companies that were planning to issue junk bonds in coming weeks
might postpone or restructure their offerings because of the
sell-off, which pushed up yields and made financing more expensive,
Lonski said.
   If wary investors demand higher and higher interest on junk
bonds, companies may be less able to rely on the low-grade
securities for financing. They then may either pull back from
speculative, riskier ventures or finance them in a less risky way,
such as by issuing stock.
   The economy is approaching the seventh birthday of the longest
U.S. peacetime expansion in history. But some economists say it may
not last much longer.
   Elliot Janeway, in a column in The New York Times on Sunday,
warned that dangerously high levels of inventories are accumulating
in autos, housing, retailing and metals.
   James Buchan, in a column in Monday's editions of the
London-based Financial Times, said the shakeout in junk bonds is the
latest phase of a ``rolling liquidation'' that in past years had
wrung speculation out of agriculture and the energy markets.
   ``The secret is to shake out the speculators in batches not, as
in the 1920s, all together,'' Buchan said.
   James Grant, publisher of Grant's Interest Rate Observer, said he
believed Buchan's assessment seemed on target. ``It's always good
news when false values are exposed for being false,'' he said in an
interview.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890919-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 0118EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BirminghamSteel     09-19 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Birmingham Steel,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harbert Offers $385 Million for Birmingham Steel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harbert Corp. on Monday offered about
$385 million for Birmingham Steel, a 5-year-old company that
prospered by buying older, often financially troubled steel mills at
bargain prices.
   Birmingham Steel President James Todd said the decision to sell
the company to Birmingham-based Harbert stemmed in part from a
desire to keep its headquarters in Birmingham.
   ``We have had a number of people express an interest in buying
out the company,'' he said.
   Harbert Corp. offered $30 a share in cash, or a total of about
$385 million for the company's stock. Harbert, an international
construction company, also would assume and refinance more than $100
million in Birmingham Steel debt.
   The company's stock closed Monday at $29.12{, up $4.50, in
consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading.
   Birmingham Steel had a profit of about $39 million in its latest
fiscal year on sales of more than $343 million.
   Harbert Corp. was founded by John M. Harbert III, a major
Birmingham Steel investor.
   A special committee of outside directors, formed by the company
to study a possible sale, recommended the Harbert offer after
determining there was little room for the stock's price to move
above the low $20s.
   The price has been depressed because of Birmingham Steel's 50
percent investment in redevelopment of a Houston, Texas, rolling
mill, which eventually will make flat-rolled sheet steel.
   Harbert, chairman of the company, said Birmingham Steel's success
and strong management team prompted him to make the offer. He
already owns less than 5 percent of the company's stock and sits on
its board of directors.
   ``We are knowledgable about this industry,'' he said.
   The offer must be approved by Birmingham Steel stockholders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
