<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 0208EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-FordRecall     09-19 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ford Recall,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company to Upgrade Emission Systems, Fix Seat Belts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. says it is recalling nearly
493,000 Escorts and Mercury Lynxes to fix faulty emission-control
systems and 67,156 Tracers because of an apparent seat-belt defect.
   Repairs of either problem will be made at no charge regardless of
a vehicle's age or mileage, Ford and the Environmental Protection
Agency said Monday in separate statements.
   The vehicles recalled for emission-system improvements have
1.9-liter engines and include the 1985 Ford Escort and Mercury Lynx
and the 1986 Escort, Lynx and Ford EXP.
   Excessive emissions of hydrocarbons and carbon monoxide were
discovered during routine EPA tests of 1985 models, EPA spokeswoman
Martha Casey said.
   ``We're constantly checking various classes of vehicle to see if
a few years after leaving the assembly line, they're still meeting
standards,'' Casey said.
   The EPA didn't request the Ford recall but ``we sort of term
these recalls EPA-influenced,'' Casey said.
   Ford spokesman Mike Parris in Michigan attributed the problem to
normal wear.
   ``A few years back, the equipment was not as good as it was
now,'' Parris said. ``Some of the valves and small hoses and pieces
are starting to wear out and we're having to replace them with
upgraded pieces.''
   The Ford repairs will involve changing the choke system,
distributor spark advance and the air-injection system, a
pollution-control system that helps the catalytic converter control
hydrocarbons and carbon monoxide. Dealers also will install more
durable crankcase ventilation valves, also known as PCV valves, EPA
said.
   Cars made for sale in California are excluded from the Ford
recall because they are manufactured to meet that state's emission
standards, which are more stringent than EPA's, Parris said.
   No California cars have been found to fall short of the federal
standards, Casey said.
   The Tracers being recalled were made in the 1988 model year.
There are 66,314 in the United States and 842 in Canada, Ford said.
   In some cases, it has become difficult to extend the front-seat
lap-shoulder belts for buckling unless they are pulled very slowly,
the company said. A few of the belts may lock and be impossible to
pull out.
   Owners having trouble extending the belts are asked to return the
car to the dealer for inspection and repairs if necessary, the
automaker said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890919-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 0210EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Macmillan-Merrill     09-19 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Macmillan-Merrill,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Macmillan Agrees to Buy Merrill Publishing for $260 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Macmillan Inc., the publishing giant controlled
by Britain's Robert Maxwell, has agreed to buy the textbook concern
Merrill Publishing for $260 million in cash.
   The deal would swell Macmillan's share of the educational
publishing market, while enabling Merrill's owner, the
privately-held Bell &amp; Howell Co., to make a graceful retreat from
that fiercely competitive business.
   Merrill Publishing, based in Columbus, Ohio, publishes textbooks,
software and other learning materials for the elementary, high
school and college markets, and officials said it was expected to
post more than $100 million in revenue this year.
   The company, founded in 1842, has been owned since 1967 by Bell &amp;
Howell, which is based in Skokie, Ill.
   Jerry Herb, vice president-administration at Bell &amp; Howell, said
his company decided to sell Merrill Publishing for strategic reasons.
   He said consolidation in the educational publishing field put
Merrill at a competitive disadvantage with larger companies. He said
Bell &amp; Howell considered making some acquisitions in this field but
found few potential candidates and decided several months ago to
sell Merrill.
   The deal is subject to regulatory approval.
   ``We are extremely pleased to acquire this excellent publisher,''
Maxwell was quoted as saying in a two-sentence announcement of the
deal.
   Maxwell had told shareholders of Maxwell Communication Corp. PLC
last week at their annual meeting in London that the company was
negotiating for a medium-sized educational publishing business in
North America.
   Bell &amp; Howell was acquired in May 1988 for $640 million by a
group led by Texas investor Robert M. Bass and including senior
management. Before that deal was completed, Maxwell had indicated he
was interested in pursuing Bell &amp; Howell but never made a formal
offer.
   Maxwell subsequently paid $2.5 billion for Macmillan, which is a
leading educational publisher and has a growing information services
business.
   Earlier this year, Macmillan combined its elementary, secondary
and vocational education publishing businesses with those of
McGraw-Hill Inc. in a 50-50 joint venture called the
Macmillan-McGraw-Hill School Publishing Co.
   Macmillan continues to operate its own college textbook
publishing business separately.
   Buzz Ellis, president of the school division at Merrill, said
Merrill expects to post more than $100 million in revenue this year,
and employs about 650 people at three sites in the Columbus
metropolitan area.
   The news release did not say how the Merrill operations would be
combined with those of Macmillan, and company spokeswoman Suzanne
Cummings said she did now know what the plans were.
   But if Merrill's elementary and secondary school operations were
combined with those of the Macmillan-McGraw-Hill joint venture, it
would become the nation's second largest publisher for elementary
and secondary schools, according to Educational Marketer, a trade
newsletter from Knowledge Industry Publications Inc. of White
Plains, N.Y.
   Educational Marketer estimated that Merrill derived $70 million
in revenue from elementary and secondary school publishing in 1988.
That would lift the Macmillan-McGraw-Hill total for 1988 to $440
million, second only to $476.5 million at Harcourt Brace Jovanovich
Inc.
   In the nation's college publishing rankings, Macmillan ranks 10th
at $58.3 million and the addition of Merrill's estimated $20 million
to $25 million in 1988 revenue would leave the combined operation
far behind the leader, Simon &amp; Schuster at $218.2 million in 1988,
according to Educational Marketer.
   Herb said the proceeds from the sale will be used to reduce part
of Bell &amp; Howell's debt of about $500 million and to finance
internal growth of its remaining businesses, which include
republishing databases and a mail handling operation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
