<FIRST>d f BC-GasRefueling     09-19 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Gas Refueling,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Questar Joins Canadian, Swiss Firms in Marketing Refueling Device</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Questar Corp. has joined with Canadian and
Swiss firms to market a device that allows natural gas-powered
vehicles to be refueled at home and other places where natural gas
is available.
   B.C. Gas of Vancouver, British Columbia, Sulzer Brothers Limited
of Winterthur, Switzerland, and Questar have formed FuelMaker Corp.
to develop, make and market the device, Questar announced Monday.
   The new company will be based in Vancouver with offices in Salt
Lake City and Toronto.
   The compressor developed by Sulzer engineers connects directly to
the natural gas supply at a customer's home or business.
   A small-diameter hose with a quick-disconnect coupling is used as
the gas is boosted to the 3,000 pounds per square inch pressure
needed to fill vehicles' natural gas fuel cylinders.
   Refueling can be done in about five hours, while the car is
unattended, Questar said.
   ``The growing national and international interest in protecting
the environment is creating a lot of interest in natural gas as a
clean alternative to gasoline,'' said Michael E. Benefield,
FuelMaker general manager.
   Mountain Fuel Supply Co., a Questar subsidiary that provides
natural gas service in Utah and southwestern Wyoming, is converting
100 of its service vehicles to natural gas. It recently opened its
second natural gas filling station.
   FuelMaker plans to market the device through natural gas
distrubiton utilities.
   ``We now have a backlog of orders for the first production series
and are very enthusiastic about the prospects for FuelMaker,'' said
Bruce Vernon, FuelMaker marketing manager.
</TEXT>
