<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 0817EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Brazil-Debt     09-19 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Brazil-Debt,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazil Said Seeking 90-Day Extension on Foreign Debt Servicing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brazil plans to ask the International Monetary
Fund for a 90-day extension on payments to service its $110 billion
debt because it cannot meet its obligations, a high-ranking official
of the country's central bank was quoted as saying.
   The Mexican government news agency quoted Wadico Waldir Bucchi, a
governor of the Brazilian Central Bank, as saying President Jose
Sarney's administration is seeking to gain time in order to receive
a $600 loan still pending from the IMF which will be used to service
the debt.
   Bucchi said the loan is part of a credit-line the IMF extended
last year but which Brazil has not received yet. Brazil cannot pay
its creditors until it gets it.
   Bucchi was quoted by Notimex as saying he is sure the IMF will
grant the 90-day extension when he meets Friday with officials of
that organization in New York.
   ``Brazil is certain the great majority of creditor banks will
respond positively to its petition,'' Bucchi said.
   Notimex said that Bucchi spoke with reporters in the Caribbean
resort of Cancun, Mexico, where the heads of central banks from
Latin America, Spain and the Philippines began meeting to discuss
international strategies to deal with the IMF and the World Bank.
   Latin America alone owes an estimated $104 trillion, and Brazil
has the biggest foreign debt in the Third World followed by Mexico
with $107.4 billion.
   The meeting began in a climate of tension caused by rumors that
Brazil may declare a moratorium on $1.6 billion in interest payments
that came due last Friday.
   However, Sergio Amaral, adviser on international relations in
Brazil's Treasury Ministry, said those reports were wrong.
   ``It's not true,'' Amaral told The Associated Press in a
telephone interview. ``We are going to look for a solution quickly
to reach an agreement with banks.''
   Amaral would not elaborate on Brazil's plans.
   Brazil has previously suspended payments and, according to news
reports in Brazil, such a moratorium would help the South American
giant maintain its reserves of $6 billion but would hurt its chances
of obtaining fresh money from international lenders.
   ``It is our own political economic mistakes that have determined
that development in Latin America is lagging behind the rest of the
world,'' said Miguel Mancera Aguayo, director of Mexico's central
bank at the opening of Monday's meetings.
   Mancera said that business activity increased 50 percent over the
past 10 years in Latin America, but has not kept pace with
industrial nations ``because the powerful nations have closed their
markets and paid less for prime materials they import,'' according
to the independent Excelsior news agency.
   He said Latin American nations should find their own solutions
and not wait for outside answers ``because there have been failures
in the management of the political economy that have aggravated the
problems.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
