<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     09-19 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0322</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market inched higher in early dealings
today after two government reports that suggested a further easing
of inflationary pressures.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 1.90 points at
2,689.40 after a half-hour of trading at 10 a.m. EDT.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 4 to 3 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 523 issues up, 400 down and 507 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 21.50 million shares.
   The government reported today that consumer prices remained
unchanged in August, the best inflation performance in more than
three years. The August performance was due mainly to falling
gasoline prices, the Labor Department said.
   The Commerce Department also reported today that housing
construction fell 5 percent in August, the largest decline in six
months.
   Wall Street analysts said the reports were good news for the
stock market because it suggested a slowdown in economic growth and
that the Federal Reserve may ease credit further.
   ``The numbers were favorable; both were below expectations,''
said Larry Wachtel, vice president at Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc.
   Nevertheless, volume was light as players remained cautious,
Wachtel said.
   ``You don't get the sense that we're out of the woods yet after
gains in the last two days,'' Wachtel said. ``There's a sense of
caution prevailing.''
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was up
0.25 to 192.68.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was down
0.19 at 397.31.
   On Monday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 12.92 to
2,687.50.
   Advancing issues slightly outnumbered declines in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with 751 up, 693
down and 512 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 136.94 million
shares, down from 234.87 million Friday.
  
