<FIRST>u f PM-ManufacturersHanover 1stLd-Writethru   09-19 0744</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Manufacturers Hanover, 1st Ld-Writethru,0769</SECOND>
<HEAD>Manufacturers Announces Restructuring, Sale of Unit to Japanese Bank</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 new grafs after 6th graf pvs, Manufacturers Hanover...
to UPDATE with today's comments from Dai-Ichi officials. SUBS 7th graf
pvs, Monday's announcement ..., with one graf to UPDATE with latest stock
price. Picks up 8th graf pvs, Analysts said...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manufacturers Hanover Corp. says it expects a
huge loss after a restructuring that includes the addition of $950
million to its loan-loss reserves, a new-stock issue and the sale of
60 percent of its CIT Group financial services unit to Dai-Ichi
Kangyo Bank Ltd. of Japan.
   But the bank holding company, which made the announcement late
Monday, said its plan should significantly improve its capital and
reserve position.
   ``We view this as a very positive endeavor for Manufacturers
Hanover,'' Chairman John F. McGillicuddy told reporters at a news
conference.
   Manufacturers Hanover, the nation's seventh largest bank,
estimated it would suffer a loss of about $775 million for the third
quarter and $475 million for all of 1989.
   For the first six months of this year Manufacturers Hanover's
profit was down 62 pecent to $209 million, or $3.70 a share, from
the year-earlier period. The 1988 period included about $388 million
in one-time gains from divestitures and tax benefits.
   Manufacturers Hanover said Dai-Ichi Kangyo, the world's largest
bank with assets of $410 billion, agreed to pay $1.28 billion for
the 60 percent stake in CIT. The transaction is the largest purchase
of a U.S. company by a Japanese bank.
   Yuko Oana, a senior managing director of Dai-Ichi, said today
that the investment in CIT allows his bank to offer more services
globally and to expand its customer base to include more medium-size
companies in the United States.
   ``CIT, with its comprehensive range of asset-backed financing
products, will enable us to offer a considerably broader product
line to our customers around the world,'' Oana told a news
conference.
   ``At the same time, we believe that CIT will benefit from the
international exposure and perspective that DKB can provide.''
   Monday's announcements came after the stock market closed. In
composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Manufacturers
Hanover closed up 87{ cents at $41.75 a share Monday. In
late-morning trading today, its shares rose $1 to $42.75.
   Analysts said they weren't surprised by the moves. Manufacturers
Hanover had been coming under increasing pressure to raise capital
and increase reserves for losses on loans to less-developed
countries.
   The addition of $950 million in loan-loss provisions in the third
quarter boosts Manufacturers Hanover's loan-loss reserve to $2.4
billion, or 36 percent of its portfolio of medium- to long-term
loans, up from reserves of $1.5 billion, or 22 percent of its loans.
   On average, other big money center banks have reserves equal to
about 30 percent of their loans to less-developed countries.
   ``This should take some of the sting of LDC exposure away from
Manufacturers Hanover and give it some room to maneuver, said James
J. McDermott Jr., an analyst with Keefe Bruyette &amp; Woods in New
York. ``I think it was a necessary step.''
   McGillicuddy said recent debt negotiations with Mexico and the
U.S. government's plan for reducing the $1.3 trillion Third World
debt, known as the Brady plan, could make it harder for banks to
collect on outstanding loans.
   Manufacturers Hanover said it would issue up to $500 million in
new common stock before year's end. Analysts said the stock sale
coupled with the sale of a controlling stake in CIT should provide
the bank with much-needed capital to handle its Third World debt
problem.
   CIT is the biggest bank-affiliated finance company in the United
States, withassets of $9.7 billion and $120 million in earnings last
year. It provides loans and leases to medium-sized companies through
50 offices nationwide. Manufacturers Hanover acquired the business
from RCA Corp. in 1984 for $1.5 billion.
   The deal also includes a private placement with Dai-Ichi of 2.7
million in newly issued common shares of Manufacturers Hanover at
$45 a share for a total of $120 million. Dai-Ichi promised not to
acquire more than that 4.9 percent stake over a 10-year period.
   The sale of CIT to Dai-Ichi, which had been rumored for days, is
the latest in a series of divestitures in which Manufacturers
Hanover has raised cash to bolster its capital. Last year it earned
about $400 million from the sale of assets.
</TEXT>
