<FIRST>r f BC-Avon-Forecast     09-19 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Avon-Forecast,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuts Earnings Forecast Due to Soft Sales, Strong Dollar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cosmetics maker Avon Products Inc., pursued
earlier this year by several unwanted suitors, Tuesday disclosed it
has lowered 1989 income expectations due to weakening sales and a
strong dollar.
   This year's after-tax earnings per share are now forecast at
about $1.95 to $2.15, down from an earlier estimated range of $2.30
to $2.40. Earnings in 1990 will be an unspecified amount below the
previously projected $3.35 to $3.45 a share, Avon said.
   Last year, Avon lost $404.5 million, or $6.79 a share, reflecting
a loss from discontinued operations.
   ``In the United States, our new products, but especially our new
gifts and jewelry products, are falling behind sales expectations,''
said James E. Preston, Avon's chairman and chief executive officer.
   ``In the fourth quarter, non-cosmetic products account for about
50 percent of sales, so that a shortfall in these categories has a
disproportionate impact on the company's performance,'' Preston said
in a news release.
   The dollar's strength is ``contributing materially to the
shortfall,'' Preston said.
   The beauty products manufacturer has been under pressure to
enhance profitability in the aftermath of unsolicited takeover
proposals that Avon's board rejected.
   Avon over the summer received a $41-a-share, or $2.85 billion,
takeover bid from investor Irwin Jacobs. The Jacobs' offer topped an
earlier proposal from Avon's rival direct seller Amway Corp., which
had proposed acquiring Avon for $39 a share, or about $2.1 billion.
   Avon also shunned takeover advances from Mary Kay Corp., parent
of the door-to-door cosmetics company.
   Under Preston, Avon's management repeatedly has said the company
is better off remaining independent, free to carry out plans aimed
at improving the balance sheet.
   Preston said Tuesday that Avon still is committed to the strategy
outlined at a meeting with financial analysts May 19 and that the
company is achieving many elements of the strategy.
   Avon recently said it is considering the sale of its retail
fragrance subsidiaries, Giorgio Beverly Hills and Parfums Stern.
Preston said the revised earnings projections don't include the
effect of a potential sale of the perfume businesses.
</TEXT>
