<SECOND>PM-UAL,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAL Non-Union Workers Face 10 Percent Pay Cut: Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of United Airlines' 24,000 non-union
employees face a 10 percent pay cut if the $6.75 billion employee
buyout of parent UAL Corp. goes through as planned, a newspaper
reported today.
   The Chicago Sun-Times, quoting an unidentifed adviser to the
buyout group, said the pay cut would apply to managers and most
salaried workers.
   The lowest-paid clerical workers will not be affected, nor will
employees in one or two fields requiring highly specialized skills
and training since those workers could easily find comparable jobs
with another airline, the newspaper said.
   UAL spokesman Joe Hopkins declined comment on the report. The
United chapter of the Air Line Pilots Association, which is
spearheading the buyout effort, said it could not immediately
confirm the story.
   UAL's board of directors accepted the pilot-led, $300-per-share
takeover offer on Thursday, rejecting a competing offer from Los
Angeles investor Marvin Davis.
   The plan, which would make UAL the biggest employee-owned U.S.
company, calls for employees to own 75 percent with management
owning 10 percent and British Airways PLC holding 15 percent.
   The pilots earlier revealed that they would take pay cuts of up
10 percent as part of the buyout plan.
   United's flight attendants are considering management-proposed
contract concessions in exchange for their participation in the
buyout.
