<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet11am     09-19 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 11am,0423</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was slightly higher in moderate
trading today after the government released new economic reports
that pointed to a lowering of inflation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 3.80 points at
2,691.30 at 11 a.m. EDT. The blue-chip indicator was up 1.90 points
an hour earlier.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 4 to 3 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 649 issues up, 504 down and 533 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 47.11 million shares.
   The government reported today that consumer prices remained
unchanged in August, the best inflation performance in more than
three years.
   The Commerce Department also reported that housing construction
fell 5 percent in August, the largest decline in six months. New
homes and apartments were built at a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 1.35 million units, down from 1.42 million units in July.
   Wall Street analysts said the numbers were below expectations and
good news for the stock market because they suggested an easing of
inflation, adding to hopes that the Federal Reserve will loosen
monetary policy by lowering interest rates.
   Nevertheless, many big institutional investors stayed were on the
sidelines, remaining cautious about the viability of the junk-bond
market after last week's sharp declines, analysts said.
   ``You don't get the sense that we're out of the woods yet after
gains in the last two days,'' said Larry Wachtel, vice president at
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. ``There's a sense of caution
prevailing.''
   Despite steep declines over the last two weeks, some observers
warned that the stock market is in for still further weakness.
   ``We expect some sort of correction over the next two weeks,''
said Brad Weeks, head of equity trading for the investment firm of
Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was up
0.53 to 192.96.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was down
0.12 to 379.38.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Manufacturers Hanover
was up 2 to 43} after Monday's announcement that it had agreed to
sell a stake in the company to Japan's Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank. AT&amp;T
was up { to 42, Canadian Pacific had gained \ to 22} and Tucson
Electric had advanced ] to 23~.
   Avon was down ~ to 33, McDonalds was off \ to 30\ and Texaco had
declined \ to 50~.
</TEXT>
