<FIRST>r f PM-BiddingScheme     09-19 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bidding Scheme,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Employee Arrested in Bid-Rigging at Martin Marietta</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former employee of defense contractor
Martin Marietta has been arrested and charged with providing inside
information to a welding company bidding on contracts.
   George H. McDowell, 62, bilked the company of thousands of
dollars through a kickback scheme with Wynn's Welding Inc. of
Orlando, said federal authorities.
   ``We uncovered it, investigated it internally and turned it over
to federal authorities,'' said Martin spokesman Chip Manor on Monday.
   The case is the second alleged kickback scheme Martin has faced
in less than two months. On Aug. 9, a former Martin employment
administrator was indicted in Orlando on charges of defrauding the
company of more than $55,000 in an operation involving employment
agencies in New York and Phoenix, Ariz.
   The U.S. Attorney's office is continuing the investigation into
the McDowell case, said prosecutor Gary Librick, and other charges
may be filed.
   McDowell, charged with conspiracy to commit wire fraud, could not
be reached for comment.
   The alleged scheme took place from Jan. 16, 1987, to Sept. 11,
1987, according to court documents.
</TEXT>
