<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1234EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-US-CigaretteExports 1stLd-Writethru f0027 09-19 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Cigarette Exports, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0027,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Koop Denounces Efforts to Export Cigarettes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New material, editing throughout with Koop testimony. Also on
general news wires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surgeon General C. Everett Koop today denounced
efforts to export U.S. cigarettes as ``the height of hypocrisy.''
   Koop, who is retiring Oct. 1, testified at a hearing of the U.S.
trade representative against a request by the cigarette industry for
government intervention to force Thailand to allow sales and
advertising of American cigarettes.
   ``When we are persuading foreign governments to stop the flow of
cocaine, it is the height of hypocrisy to export tobacco,'' said
Koop, who has conducted a vigorous anti-smoking campaign throughout
his tenure.
   The U.S. Cigarette Export Association has requested the
intervention and the trade representative is to decide the issue by
next May.
   In 1988, U.S. tobacco exports contributed a record $3.5 billion
to helping reduce ``this country's onerous trade deficit,'' said
export association President Owen Smith.
   ``People throughout Asia will continue to buy and smoke billions
of cigarettes each year with or without U.S. presence in the
marketplace,'' said Rep. Robin Tallon, D-S.C. ``The real issue is
whether American companies will be allowed to compete, or if the
playing field will be abandoned to other foreign manufacturers and
local monopolies.''
   But Rep. Chester A. Atkins, D-Mass., said the real issue ``is
about the American government using leverage and tax dollars to
coerce countries into allowing marketing practices that were
outlawed long ago'' in the United States.
   The petition seeks to force Thailand ``to overturn a policy of
banning cigarette advertisements'' in print and broadcast media,
Atkins said.
   The export association represents three major cigarette
companies, Brown and Williamson, Philip Morris and R.J. Reynolds.
   Since 1986, Japan, South Korea and Taiwan have opened markets to
U.S. cigarette brands after being accused of unfair trade and
threatened with retaliation against their products.
   ``I believe that most Americans would be appalled to learn that
their government, which banned cigarette advertisements on TV,
required warning labels on cigarettes ... is aggressively pushing
cigarette addiction overseas through the trade representative,''
Atkins said.
   ``It is simply inexcusable for the U.S. to exert its great
influence to force Thailand to reverse its health policy,'' he said.
   Atkins is sponsoring legislation to require that U.S. cigarette
brands sold abroad carry warnings and advertising restrictions
equivalent to those in the United States.
   The industry argues that foreign countries are competent to make
their own regulations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
