<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     09-19 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Both Off</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar ended weaker in European trading
Tuesday after the Federal Reserve Bank intervened to keep the
currency down.
   Gold prices also waned.
   The dollar was quoted late in the day at 1.9505 Deutsche marks,
down from 1.9525 marks late Monday in London.
   The dollar ended the European trading day at 145.55 yen. That
came after a fall of 0.70 yen in trading in Tokyo, where the dollar
closed at 145.73 yen.
   Dealers said trading was fairly thin and inactive because many
market players remain skittish about jumping back in after Friday'
sharp slide from over 2.00 marks to 1.9350 marks.
   ``People don't have much of a medium-term view about the dollar
now,'' said a corporate dealer at a U.S. bank in Frankfurt, West
Germany.
   Other late dollar rates compared with late Monday: 1.6870 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6850; 6.5875 French francs, down from 6.5890;
2.2000 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2180; 1,406.50 Italian lire, down
from 1,417.40; 1.1833 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1834.
   In London, the pound sterling firmed to $1.5720 compared with
$1.5695 late Monday.
   Gold traded in London at $360.50 a troy ounce late Tuesday, down
from late Monday's $361.65.
   In Zurich, gold traded at $360.50 a troy ounce late Tuesday, down
from $361.00 late Monday.
   In Hong Kong, gold rose 0.86 cents to close at a bid $360.90.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.09 a troy ounce
late Tuesday, up one cent from late Monday.
</TEXT>
