<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1332EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-HousingStarts     09-19 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing Starts,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housing Construction Down in August</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Inflation Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction, depressed by a spike in
mortgage rates, fell by 5 percent in August, the government said
Tuesday in a report many analysts viewed as only a temporary setback
for the housing industry.
   The Commerce Department said new homes and apartments were built
at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.35 million units last
month, down from 1.42 million units in July.
   It was the first decline since May and the largest setback since
a 12.7 percent fall last February. Housing starts had risen 1.3
percent in July and 7.5 percent in June.
   Fixed mortgage rates, which peaked at 11.22 percent in March, had
fallen to 9.68 percent by Aug. 4, but then rose by about one-half
percentage point through August.
   However, in recent weeks they have begun edging down slightly,
now standing at 10.05 percent, according to the weekly survey by the
Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. Economists predicted continued
small declines in mortgage rates for the rest of the year and said
this should bolster sales and construction figures.
   ``The (August) housing starts numbers show builders were waiting
out the recent uptick in interest rates,'' said John Tuccillo, chief
economist of the National Association of Realtors. ``However, the
higher rate of building permits is a good sign that the stalled
activity in August is only temporary.''
   Overall applications for building permits, considered a good
barometer of future activity, rose 3.5 percent after falling 2.1
percent in July.
   David Seiders, chief economist of the National Association of
Home Builders, said the drop in construction and another report
Tuesday showing consumer prices did not rise in August should
convince the Federal Reserve to stop fighting inflation and resume
lowering interest rates to bolster the economy.
   However, other economists said they doubted that the weak
construction number would prompt action on the part of the Fed,
given the fact that other statistics show the economy is continuing
to grow at a healthy rate.
   ``I don't think the Fed will do anything to change policy for the
next several months,'' said David Berson, chief economist of the
Federal National Mortgage Association.
   Richard Peach, senior economist at the Mortgage Bankers
Association, said he believed that interest rates will fall despite
Fed intervention as financial market fears about inflation ease.
   Construction starts fell earlier this year for four straight
months before rebounding in June, the longest string of declines
since activity slowed for five months in a row from February through
June 1987. The May level of 1.31 million starts was the slowest pace
since the 1.30 million rate in December 1982.
   Total housing starts during the first eight months of the year
are down 4.7 percent from the same period of 1988.
   Construction of single-family homes last month fell 2.5 percent
to an annual rate of 1 million units. Single-family starts had risen
5.9 percent in July after falling 0.5 percent in June.
   Apartment construction fell 11.4 percent in August to an annual
rate of 350,000 units. It had fallen 9 percent in July after rising
31.1 percent in June.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
