<DOCNO> AP890919-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1419EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-IBMSoftware     09-19 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IBM Software,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Promises 20,000 Experts to Help With Software Engineering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. said
Tuesday it would make 20,000 experts available worldwide to help its
customers adapt to the coming era of software engineering.
   The statement came as IBM announced, as expected, that it was
committing itself to computer-aided software engineering, or CASE.
IBM's endorsement is expected to give a large boost to the high-tech
field, which already garners about $300 million in annual revenue.
   Software engineering is intended to replace disorganized methods
of software-writing that have led to chaotic, unmanageable and
failure-prone programs for large computers.
   Consultants said IBM's promise of experts to help customers was
an important part of the announcement, since the transition to
software engineering promises to be a real test of programmers'
flexibility.
   ``The limiting factor on the introduction of CASE technology is
the ability of information systems shops to cope with a radically
new culture. It is going to take them quite some years,'' said Ian
Palmer, chairman of James Martin Associates in Reston, Va.
   ``It's going to require an investment, not just of the company's
time but of a person's ability to recycle themselves, re-engineer
themselves,'' said Dick Welsh, the Dallas-based director of
information systems consulting markets for Ernst &amp; Young.
   Some of the 20,000 experts will come from IBM and some from four
outside firms designated by IBM: CAP Gemini America, Computer Power
Group, Computer Task Group and GE Consulting.
   IBM is calling its offering AD-Cycle. Its strategy relies heavily
on existing software-development tools marketed by other companies
that beat IBM to the market, particularly KnowledgeWare Inc.,
Bachman Information Systems Inc. and Index Technology Inc.
   More than 30 companies on Tuesday announced their support for
IBM's plan, which will roll out over the next several years.
   This may be the farthest IBM has ever gone in using other
companies' products as a central part of its own strategy, said
George Conrades, an IBM senior vice president. ``It's a high-water
mark, but it's an ever-rising tide,'' he said in an interview.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
