<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1548EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Disney-Taxes     09-19 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disney-Taxes,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disney Suing Over Tax Bill: $12,000 or $1.4 Million?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KISSIMMEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walt Disney World Co. is challenging a 254
percent property tax increase county officials say was levied to
help pay for huge commercial growth and traffic problems near the
tourist attraction.
   Disney on Monday paid Osceola County $12,000, the company's own
estimate of 1989 property taxes owed. The county plans to bill
Disney for $1.4 million.
   Disney spokesman Charlie Ridgway said Tuesday the company filed a
lawsuit in state circuit court ``to protect our rights to challenge,
although we hope to come to an agreement with county authorities on
the whole subject.''
   Osceola removed the agricultural classification on most of
Disney's undeveloped property in the county and jacked up the tax
bill to $1.4 million. Disney's theme park is located north of the
area, in Orlando in Orange County.
   Disney filed the lawsuit Friday to beat a Monday deadline on
challenges to tax assessments.
   A Disney representative on Monday dropped off checks totaling
$12,012 _ the company's ``good-faith estimate'' of its 1989 taxes.
   ``It's kind of like they're thumbing their nose at us, isn't
it?'' Osceola Property Appraiser Bob Day said. ``I mean $12,000 vs.
$1.4 million. There's a big difference there, wouldn't you say?''
   Until this year, much of Disney's 7,013 acres of undeveloped
property was classified as agricultural because Disney leased a
portion to a cattle rancher and contracted with a timber company to
harvest pine trees.
   The property was assessed at $26.9 million last year, and the
company paid Osceola $395,000 in taxes. After removing the
agricultural exemption, Day in July reassessed the land at $84
million.
   Disney contends even last year's taxes were excessive because the
1988 payment was based on a commercial classification for part of
the property, as well as on the portion classified agricultural.
   Disney's estimated payment Monday represents the total amount of
1989 taxes the company believes it owes because ``all of that land
rightfully should be classified as agricultural,'' Ridgway said.
   ``Under the law, you pay what you feel you should properly pay,''
he said.
   By contrast, Disney paid its other host county, Orange, $24
million in taxes last year and is expected to pay $33.65 million
this year.
   Much of the company's Orange County property contain's its
prosperous tourist attractions. In recent years, Disney has built
the Disney-MGM Studios park, Pleasure Island and Typhoon Lagoon next
in Orange near the Osceola land.
   But Osceola Commissioner Larry Whaley said: ``We have just as
many problems from Disney as Orange County does. And they're getting
$33 million in taxes.''
   Osceola in 1973 tried to strip Disney of its agricultural
classification but Disney won a legal battle. But the tourist
attraction has grown since then, county officials argue, and have
had a greater impact on the county.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
