<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1513EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MacintoshPortable     09-19 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Macintosh Portable,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Apple Announces Portable Macintosh</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release 12:01 a.m. EDT Wednesday; time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Apple Computer Inc.'s first portable Macintosh
computer is more expensive, bigger and heavier than the latest
generation of laptops but the company said Tuesday it makes no
compromises on features.
   Apple hopes to offset the drawbacks of its Macintosh Portable by
giving users all the power and features they would get on a
full-size Macintosh.
   ``It's a Macintosh through and through. Now our customers can
have Macintosh personal computing anywhere,'' Jean-Louis Gassee,
president of Apple Products, said in a statement.
   Analysts have been lukewarm toward Apple's first portable.
   ``I think it'll do well with Apple's existing customer base. I'm
not sure it'll gain share in the overall laptop market, though,''
said Bruce Lupatkin, an analyst at Hambrecht &amp; Quist in San
Francisco. ``It's a little little big and it's also a little
pricey.''
   The portable lists at $5,799, or $6,499 with an optional
40-megabyte hard disk for data storage. A modem for communication
over phone lines is extra at $449. The weight is 13.7 pounds, or
15.7 pounds with the optional 40-megabyte hard disk.
   The screen is one-tone rather than color, but is unusually sharp
because there is a separate transistor for each screen dot, or
picture element. The screen contains more than 250,000 picture
elements in a 640 by 400 array, making it 50 percent larger than the
screen on a Macintosh SE.
   To conserve batteries, Apple used a version of the Motorola 68000
processor chip that requires 80 percent less power. It also used a
low-power kind of memory chip. The lead acid batteries last from six
to 12 hours and can be recharged to capacity at any time, Apple said.
   Apple, based in Cupertino, Calif., also announced the Macintosh
IIci, an advanced version of the Macintosh IIcx, which it billed as
``the most powerful Macintosh that Apple has ever developed.''
   The Macintosh IIci starts at $6,269 and ranges up to $9,152,
putting it in the price range of some computer workstations,
machines designed for scientists and engineers. Apple said it
delivers 55 percent higher performance than the Macintosh IIcx or
IIx. It has built-in video capabilities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
