<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1515EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Ford-Jaguar Bjt   09-19 0692</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ford-Jaguar, Bjt,0717</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Purchasing Up to 15 Percent of Jaguar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. announced plans Tuesday to buy up to
15 percent of Jaguar PLC, saying it wanted a long-term relationship
with the unprofitable British luxury auto maker.
   Jaguar, which has been battered by flagging sales in its
principal U.S. market during the past year, maintained that it
wanted to remain independent but didn't rule out collaborating with
another car company.
   Ford, which already has a huge European presence and is
negotiating a possible transaction with Swedish automaker Saab,
could benefit from an association with the well-known Jaguar luxury
car line, analysts said.
   Jaguar stock soared 97 cents to close at $7.33 a share on
London's Stock Exchange, as some speculated that other companies
also might be assembling stakes in Jaguar.
   Jaguar's articles of association limit individual shareholdings
to 15 percent until the end of 1990, and the government has veto
power over any takeover through the same period.
   ``It has always been our desire to maintain our independence,''
said Jaguar spokesman, who wasn't identified in keeping with company
policy. However, the spokesman also said Jaguar has held out the
possibility of collaborating with another car maker.
   The spokesman said the Coventry-based company was notified of
Ford's plans on Tuesday and that Jaguar wouldn't make any final
comment until its board of directors had a chance to discuss them at
an unspecified date.
   Ford of Europe Chairman Lindsey Halstead, speaking at a London
news conference, said his company's intentions are not hostile. He
characterized contact with Jaguar Chairman Sir John Egan on Tuesday
as ``friendly and open and we agreed to leave the lines of
communication open.''
   The two companies held private, informal talks last year which
failed to produce any sort of working agreement, Halstead said.
   Ford has informed the British government of its plans but has not
gotten a reaction from British officials, said Ford spokesman
Michael Perry.
   The spokesman said: ``It is too early to say what might happen
then (1990), but we regard the acquisition of a minority
shareholding in Jaguar as a basis for a longer-term strategic
association between our two companies as we explained to John Egan
in private discussion.''
   Perry also said Ford respected Jaguar's distinctive British
character and would want to maintain its separate identity and help
strengthen its image.
   Last Wednesday, Jaguar posted an after-tax loss of $1.7 million
on sales of $870 million for the first six months of the year.
   The company expects to sell 20,000 cars in the United States this
year, down from 20,700 in 1988.
   Ford of Europe, which is headquartered in Brentwood, England,
makes 1.8 million vehicles a year. It has 21 European plants, 11 of
them in Britain, and employs more than110,000 people.
   Parent Ford Motor Co. is the second largest U.S. automaker behind
General Motors Corp. Ford posted an industry record profit of $5.3
billion, or $10.96 a share, on revenue of $92.45 billion in 1988.
   Ford confirmed earlier this month that it was negotiating with
Saab-Scania AB, the Swedish airplane, truck and automaker, over a
possible transaction.
   Peter Caldwell, automotive analyst at Smith New Court PLC, said
Ford may have made its move now because it believed Jaguar's share
price was headed higher, or because it wanted to preempt a move by
another auto maker.
   David Blackwood, an automotive analyst at the London investment
firm Hoare Govett Ltd., said he would not be surprised if other
automakers also were buying Jaguar stakes.
   Although Jaguar is losing money, its brand name is highly
valuable, the analysts said.
   Halstead said Jaguar could benefit from Ford's European
production and marketing. Jaguar could benefit from economies of
scale in parts and materials purchasing, as well as from Ford's
engineering research.
   Ford spokesman Perry said the company has begun buying Jaguar
shares on the open market, but he declined to elaborate on Ford's
purchases.
   Under U.S. antitrust law Ford must notify the government once it
acquiresa $15 million worth of Jaguar stock, about a 1.2 percent
stake, and then would have to wait 30 days before buying more.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
