<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     09-19 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0414</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose in moderate afternoon trading
but remained below session highs.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 8.93 points to
2,696.43 at 3 p.m. EDT after rising more than 10 points in
late-morning trading. An hour earlier the blue-chip indicator was up
3.80 points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a margin of about 6 to
5 on the New York Stock Exchange with 759 issues up, 624 down and
553 unchanged. Transportation and pharmaceutical stocks were among
the few standouts in an otherwise featureless session, traders said.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 116.70 million shares.
   Analysts said two new economic reports proved bullish for the
market in early dealings.
   The Labor Department reported today that consumer prices remained
unchanged in August as measured by its Consumer Price Index. It was
the best inflation performance in more than three years. Prices were
up a modest 0.2 percent in both June and July.
   The Commerce Department also reported that housing construction
fell 5 percent in August, the largest decline in six months. New
homes and apartments were built at a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 1.35 million units, down from 1.42 million units in July.
   Wall Street analysts said the data suggested an easing of
inflationary pressures and added to hopes that the Federal Reserve
will loosen monetary policy by lowering interest rates.
   Although institutional trading was light, selling by big
investors early in the afternoon wiped out some of the market's
earlier gains. The junk bond market rallied after Campeau Corp.
announced that it had secured a $250 million loan to pay its
creditors.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was up
0.57 to 193.00.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index had dipped
0.21 to 379.29.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Manufacturers Hanover
was up 2[ to 43~ after Monday's announcement that it had agreed to
sell a stake in the company to Japan's Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank in an
effort to improve its capital position.
   AT&amp;T was up { to 42[, Upjohn had gained { to 36}, Niagara Mohawk
had advanced } to 14 and UAL had added 2{ to 284.
   Avon was down 2 to 31~, Ames Department Stores had slipped } to
16} and First Bank System was off 2[ to 20~.
</TEXT>
