<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   09-19 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans Futures Drop To 22-Month Low</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybeans for spot delivery on the Chicago Board of
Trade dropped to a 22-month low Tuesday as traders liquidated their
holdings for September delivery ahead of the contract's expiration
on Wednesday.
   Other soybean contracts closed mostly higher while most corn and
wheat futures retreated amid increased corn-harvesting activity and
slack export demand for U.S. grains.
   Aside from the drop in the September soybean contract to $5.63
per bushel, the lowest near-month delivery price since Nov. 16,
1987, the markets held up well in the face of the advancing harvest
and forecasts for weather beneficial to the corn and soybean crops.
   ``The market is still pretty resilient,'' said Ted Mao, a grain
specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   The Agriculture Department reported late Monday that 6 percent of
the corn crop had been harvested in the 17 largest corn-growing
states as of Sunday while 1 percent of the soybean crop had been cut
in the top 19 soybean states.
   At the close, wheat futures were 1 cent to 1} cents lower with
the September contract at $3.80{ a bushel; corn was 1{ cents lower
to 2\ cents higher with September at $2.33{ a bushel; oats were 1\
cents lower to 1 cent higher with September at $1.34 a bushel;
soybeans were 9\ cents lower to 3 cents higher with September at
$5.63 a bushel.
</TEXT>
