<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1923EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ZZZZBest     09-19 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ZZZZ Best,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>ZZZZ Best Official Ordered to Repay Profits, Gets Triple Penalties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former ZZZZ Best Co. official was ordered to
return profits he made by trading stock in the rug-shampooing firm
founded by Barry M. Minkow, who was convicted of defrauding
investors in a company-wide scam.
   Jerry Polevoi, 41, of Simi Valley also was ordered Monday to pay
$675,000 in civil penalties by U.S. District Judge Robert H.
Kelleher.
   Kelleher told Polevoi to refrain from violating securities laws,
the same order he issued last month to Polevoi's brother, Jack, who
also was involved in the ZZZZ Best scam.
   The brothers had ordered 54,200 shares of ZZZZ Best stock ``sold
short'' _ a way of betting a stock price will decline _ in mid-1987,
when they knew Minkow's scams were falling apart but before the
public had a chance to know, prosecutors said.
   The brothers jointly were ordered to repay $224,860.75 in
profits. Each also must pay triple that amount in civil penalties,
or $674.582.25, according to Kelleher's order.
   They already are serving 18-month prison terms for stock fraud
and tax fraud for their role in the ZZZZ Best scandal, which used a
``Ponzi scheme'' style scam in which money from later investors was
used to pay early debts while nearly no work was actually performed
by the company.
   Minkow, who started ZZZZ Best as a teen-ager in his parents'
garage, was convicted of 57 counts of fraud, conspiracy and other
charges, and sentenced to 25 years in prison and ordered to pay $26
million in restitution and penalties.
</TEXT>
