<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 2017EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Poland-U.S.Commerce     09-19 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-U.S. Commerce,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commerce Secretary Announces Business Agreements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Commerce Secretary Robert A. Mosbacher
said Tuesday that agreements to generate Polish-American business
and improve tourism will be signed during his visit to Poland.
   Also under way are plans to put retired U.S. executives in Polish
companies to help teach market-oriented management.
   Mosbacher told an audience of Polish and American business
leaders the economic changes in Poland are as impressive as the
political transformations that resulted in the first
non-communist-led government in four decades.
   ``Who would have imagined a short time ago that foreign firms not
only would be able to invest in Poland, but also form 100 percent
foreign-owned enterprises?'' Mosbacher said.
   The commerce secretary met Tuesday with Solidarity Prime Minister
Tadeusz Mazowiecki and Foreign Trade Minister Marcin Swiecicki.
   On Wednesday, he said he is to sign an agreement ``to build close
and growing contacts between Polish and American firms and to
generate bilateral business.''
   Also to be formalized is an accord designed to impove tourism and
expand U.S. tourism-related business in Poland, the secretary said.
   No details were provided on either program Tuesday.
   Mosbacher is to see Solidarity leader Lech Walesa in Gdansk on
Wednesday, and witness the formal creation of a joint fishing
venture involving American, Danish and Polish interests.
   Support from the West, including new trade and investment, is
considered key to the success of the Mazowiecki government and its
efforts to reverse Poland's economic crisis.
   Mosbacher is one of the first guests at the new Marriot Hotel
being completed in a long unfinished Warsaw skyscraper. The hotel is
a joint venture with the Polish airlines LOT and is considered a
major test of the potential for American investment in Poland.
   Numerous obstacles face would-be investors, including an
antiquated telephone system and the scarcity of even basic business
supplies such as paper.
   But Beurt Servaas, an Indianoplis publishing executive who heads
the U.S. -Polish Business Council, said his seven years of
investment in Poland leads him to believe there are opportunities.
   ``It cost us some money to get started, and I call that
education,'' he said.
   There are currently only about two dozen joint ventures between
U.S. And Polish companies. Another two dozen U.S. companies have
offices in Poland.
</TEXT>
