<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     09-19 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar turned mixed in nervous worldwide
trading Tuesday amid reports the Federal Reserve intervened to keep
the currency down.
   Gold prices declined.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery settled at $361.20 a troy ounce, down 50 cents from late
Monday. Republic National Bank quoted a late bid for gold of $360 an
ounce, off 70 cents.
   Zlatko Glamuzina, chief dealer at the New York office of Banco di
Sicilia, said reports that the Fed sold small amounts of dollars
added to the tension of an already nervous market after Friday's
sharp decline. Last week's downturn had followed the release of
mixed economic reports and rumors.
   ``We don't really know what the future lies for the dollar,''
Glamuzina said. ``Today it seems more of a wait-and-see attitude ...
where traders didn't feel comfortable unloading long or short
positions.''
   A corporate dealer at a U.S. bank in Frankfurt agreed, ``People
don't have much of a medium-term view about the dollar now.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.70 yen to close at 145.73 yen. The dollar traded
at 145.55 yen in London, and at 145.85 yen in New York, down from
145.93 yen Monday.
   The dollar was mixed against the British pound. The pound firmed
to $1.5720 in London, compared with $1.5695 late Monday. Sterling
fetched $1.5710 in New York, unchanged from late Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Monday's
quotes, included: 1.9535 West German marks, up from 1.9523; 1.6905
Swiss francs, up from 1.6840; 6.60105 French francs, up from 6.5830;
1.18455 Canadian dollars, up from 1.18335; and 1,406.50 Italian
lire, up from 1,404.50.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with Monday: 1.6870 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6850; 6.5875 French francs, down from 6.5890;
2.2000 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2180; 1.1833 Canadian dollars,
down from 1.1834; and 1,406.50 Italian lire, down from 1,417.40.
   Gold traded in London at $360.50 an ounce late Tuesday, down from
Monday's $361.65. In Zurich, gold traded at $360.50 an ounce late
Tuesday, down from $361.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 0.86 cents to close at a bid
$360.90.
   Silver prices were mixed. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery fell to $5.061 a troy ounce from $5.063 Monday.
Silver rose in London to $5.09 an ounce, up one cent.
</TEXT>
