<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1800EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     09-19 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0704</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spot Soybeans Slump To 22-Month Low</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybeans for spot delivery on the Chicago Board of Trade fell to
a 22-month low Tuesday on a combination of harvest pressure and
position-evening in the September contract ahead of its expiration
on Wednesday.
   Other soybean contracts closed mostly higher while most corn and
wheat futures retreated amid increased corn harvesting and slack
export demand for U.S. grains.
   On other commodity markets, energy futures were sharply lower;
cocoa futures advanced; livestock and meat futures were mixed; and
precious metals inched lower.
   Soybean futures settled 9\ cents lower to 3 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $5.63 a bushel, the lowest
near-month delivery price since Nov. 16, 1987.
   Wheat futures settled 1 cent to 2\ cents lower with September at
$3.80 a bushel; corn was 1{ cents lower to 2 cents higher with
September at $2.33} a bushel; oats were 1\ cents lower to 1 cent
higher with September at $1.34 a bushel.
   Aside from the drop in the September soybean contract, the
markets held up well in the face of the advancing harvest and
forecasts for continued beneficial crop weather.
   ``The market is still pretty resilient,'' said Ted Mao, a grain
specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   The Agriculture Department reported late Monday that 6 percent of
the corn crop had been harvested in the 17 largest corn-growing
states as of Sunday while 1 percent of the soybean crop had been cut
in the top 19 soybean states.
   Support stemmed from scattered forecasts for freezing
temperatures Sunday night in the Corn Belt. But with the crops at or
rapidly approaching maturity, the danger of significant frost damage
is almost past, Mao said.
   Crude-oil futures fell steeply on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, paced by liquidation in the expiring October crude-oil
contract, which goes off the board Wednesday.
   Heating-oil futures also weakened significantly, partly as a
result of mild temperatures in the heavily populated Northeast.
   ``Heating oil is not getting any help from seasonal factors and
supplies seem to be building,'' said Jim Ritterbusch, vice president
of trading and research with Carson Petroleum Co., a Chicago-area
petroleum distributor.
   After the close, the American Petroleum Institute reported that
U.S. stocks of petroleum distillates, including heating oil,
increased by 1.61 million barrels last week. Gasoline stocks rose by
244,000 barrels while crude oil stocks fell 9.61 million barrels.
   Ritterbusch said gasoline futures prices were lightly supported
by fears that Hurricane Hugo could swing into the Gulf Coast,
damaging U.S. oil refineries.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 4 cents to 32 cents
lower with October at $19.56 a barrel; heating oil was .43 cent to
.77 cent lower with October at 54.95 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .34 cent to .50 cent lower with October at 57.67 cents
a gallon.
   Cocoa futures rebounded modestly on New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp;
Cocoa Exchange after tumbling to 14-year lows Monday following the
International Cocoa Organization's failure to repair its battered
price-support mechanism.
   Cocoa settled $9 to $13 higher with December at $1,047 per metric
ton.
   Cattle futures finished mostly lower on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange in the wake of Monday's USDA report showing
lighter-than-expected marketings of cattle off of feed lots last
month.
   Live cattle settled .52 cent lower to .02 cent higher with
October at 71.25 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .50
cent lower with September at 83.17 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent
lower to .38 cent higher with October at 41.67 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .70 cent to .77 cent lower with February at 47.50
cents a pound.
   Precious-metal futures drifted lower in response to the Labor
Department's report of no change in consumer prices last month. Gold
and silver perform best during times of rising inflation.
   Gold futures settled 30 cents to 60 cents lower with September at
$361.20 a troy ounce; silver was 0.1 cent to .03 cent lower with
September at $5.061 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
