<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 2ndLd-Writethru   09-19 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Close Mixed In Late Selling</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates Avon stock quote in 18th graf to 31}, down 2[</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market closed narrowly mixed in
featureless trading Tuesday after getting a boost early in the day
from new economic data that showed good news on inflation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials lost 0.19 point to finish
at 2,687.31 after gaining more than 10 points during the session.
   Advancing issues narrowly outpaced decliners in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with 739 issues
up, 696 down and 536 unchanged.
   The market opened higher and remained above Monday's levels until
the final hour of trading when a mixture of factors pushed the
market lower.
   ``There's no particular reason that the market backed off,'' said
Hugh Johnson, senior vice president at First Albany Corp. ``There
was some program trading but that's not the reason. If there's
anything that explains the late decline I would say it's the slight
retreat in bond prices after their early gains.''
   Blue-chip issues led the stock market after the government
reported on consumer prices and housing construction. But the gains
were limited as the broader market lagged, analysts said.
   The Labor Department reported that consumer prices as measured by
its Consumer Price Index remained unchanged in August. It was the
best inflation performance in more than three years.
   The Commerce Department also reported that housing construction
fell 5 percent in August, the largest decline in six months. New
homes and apartments were built at a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 1.35 million units, down from 1.42 million units in July.
   Wall Street analysts said the numbers suggested an easing of
inflation, and added to hopes that the Federal Reserve will loosen
monetary policy by lowering interest rates.
   Transportation stocks rebounded slightly after being depressed in
recent sessions and pharmaceutical issues showed some strength in an
otherwise dull session lacking in leadership.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 141.61 million
shares, up from 136.94 million in the previous session, with many
institutional investors remaining cautious in light of recent sharp
declines in the junk-bond market.
   ``The junk-bond scare is still a cloud hanging over the market,''
said Brian Luedtke, stock market analyst with Piper Jaffray &amp;
Hopwood Inc.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 168.168 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market advanced $0.031 billion in value,
or less than 1 percent.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks edged
up 0.03 to 192.46.
   Among actively traded issues on the New York Stock Exchange,
Manufacturers Hanover rose 2\ to 44 after Monday's announcement that
it had agreed to sell a stake in the company to Japan's Dai-Ichi
Kangyo Bank in an effort to improve its capital position.
   AT&amp;T rose ] to 42, DuPont gained } to 117 and Phillip Morris
advanced 2\ to 158|.
   Avon, the NYSE's most active stock, fell 2[ to 31}, Varian
declined 1\ to 25} and Ames Department Stores lost ~ to 16|.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index declined 0.20 to 395.98, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index dipped 0.18 to 346.55.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market inched
up 0.16 to 467.05. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 378.83, down 0.67.
</TEXT>
