<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 1901EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     09-19 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices declined Tuesday in trading
dominated by technical factors.
   The October contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, fell 32 cents to settle at $19.56 a
42-gallon barrel after having dropped 8 cents on Monday.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, the October
contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline dropped 0.46 cent to close
at 57.67 cents a gallon after picking up 0.52 cent the previous
session.
   Home heating oil for October delivery, which declined 0.23 cent
on Monday, lost another 0.77 cent to 54.95 cents a gallon.
   Peter Beutel, assistant director of the energy group at Elders
Futures Inc., said some of the declines were due to profit-taking as
traders took advantage of the market's recent rally.
   ``We've been in an advancing market and needed to sell off to
relieve the overbought condition,'' Beutel said.
   There were spates of buying during the day, but prices were
unable to hold at higher levels, Beutel said. The October West Texas
Intermediate contract traded as high as $19.80 during the session
before dropping back.
   Oil traders have become cautious in advance of Saturday's meeting
of the strategy and price-monitoring committee of the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   The eight-member committee, which is expected to discuss OPEC's
overproduction problems, cannot make any changes in the cartel's
policies but can make recommendations to the full 13-nation
organization.
   Many analysts say market prices could weaken significantly if
OPEC fails to show at this weekend's meeting that it plans to act
decisively to contain overproduction.
</TEXT>
