<FIRST>u f AM-MinimumWage 1stLd-Writethru f0170 09-19 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minimum Wage, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0170,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Veto Fight Looming Over Minimum Wage</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to note committee accepts amount but demands
other provisions; PICKS UP 3rd graf, ``Labor Secretary,''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic-controlled House Labor and
Education Comittee bowed Tuesday to President Bush's rejection of
anything more than a $4.25 minimum wage.
   But it coupled the 90-cent increase in the present $3.35-an-hour
wage floor with restrictions on the 80 percent subminimum ``training
wage'' that Bush is demanding _ a move that administration officials
say will prompt another veto.
   On a party-line voice vote, the committee approved a bill
identical to a measure Bush vetoed in June except that it provides
two hourly increases _ one this January and the other in January
1991 _ of 45 cents each. The vetoed bill had provided for three
annual increases to $4.55 an hour by Oct. 1, 1991.
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole reiterated in a memo Bush's
promise to veto any bill which raises the current $3.35 floor to
$4.25 in less than three years or that establishes a subminimum
``training wage'' only for first-time job market entrants. Bush
would allow employers to pay an 80 percent subminimum to any newly
hired workers.
   The committee's chairman, Rep. Augustus F. Hawkins, D-Calif.,
said the reduction from the previous $4.55 wage floor that had been
sought was aimed at garnering support from Southern Democrats and
some Republicans for an override of another Bush veto.
   While both the House and Senate last year approved the $4.55
minimum wage with a 60-day subminimum training wage applicable only
to first-time workers, neither could muster the two-thirds majority
needed to override Bush's veto.
   ``There are some Republican members ready to change their votes
if the president doesn't'' show a willingness to compromise, Hawkins
said.
   Senate sources said the bill could be brought up there within the
next three weeks. Just before Congress recessed in August, the
Senate Labor Committee reapproved the same $4.55 minimum wage bill
that Bush vetoed, but with the understanding that it would likely be
modified on the Senate floor.
   Bush has demanded a six-month training wage compared to the
60-day subfloor Democrats are willing to allow. Both sides have
indicated a willingness to negotiate away differences in the time
span, but neither is budging on the applicability.
   Rep. Austin Murphy, D-Pa., chairman of the House panel's labor
standards subcommittee, said Bush's proposal would allow employers
to pay a $3.40 subminimum wage perpetually by rotating new hires in
and out every 60 days to six months.
   ``I must say to the president, `Read my lips,''' Murphy said,
adopting Bush's campaign motto on higher taxes. ``No way will I
permit that man to sign a fake increase in the minimum wage for some
political purpose two years down the road.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
