<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 2127EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-ConAgra     09-19 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-ConAgra,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>ConAgra Posts Record Quarterly Sales and Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ConAgra Inc., which lost to Tyson Foods Inc.
in the battle to merge with Holly Farms Inc., reported record sales
and earnings Tuesday for the first quarter of its fiscal year.
   Earnings for the quarter ended Aug. 27 increased 31 percent to
$50 million, or 60 cents a share, from $38.2 million, or 48 cents a
share, in the same quarter a year ago.
   Sales rose 43 percent to $4.01 billion from $2.81 billion in the
year-ago quarter.
   Although ConAgra lost to Tyson in the fight for Holly Farms, the
Omaha-based food company received a $50 million payment from Holly
Farms in June as part of an agreement in case the merger with the
chicken processor failed.
   ConAgra reported a $26.9 million one-time, after-tax gain in the
quarter from the settlement, after expenses. It also took a $24.8
million after-tax charge from a realignment of its processed meat
operations.
   Charles M. Harper, chairman and chief executive officer, said the
company is headed for its 10th straight year of record earnings. He
said sales could reach $16 billion in fiscal 1990.
   The major source of ConAgra's sales gain in the fiscal first
quarter was Sipco, formerly known as Swift Independent Packing
Company, which has annual sales in excess of $3 billion.
   ConAgra acquired the remaining 50 percent of Sipco effective the
beginning of fiscal 1990 and all Sipco sales were included in the
fiscal first quarter.
   Harper said gains were made in the quarter in all three of
ConAgra's basic food industry segments. Consumer frozen foods
earnings were up sharply in the largest industry segment, prepared
foods.
   Poultry earnings advanced and operating profit moved up in the
fresh red meat business as strong beef processing more than offset
weak pork results, the company said.
   Tyson Foods assumed control of 20 percent of the domestic poultry
market last month with the completion of its $1.4 billion merger
with Holly Farms. The buyout followed a takeover struggle for Holly
Farms that began last October and pitted Tyson against ConAgra.
</TEXT>
