<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 2127EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Crash-Poll     09-19 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Crash-Poll,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chances of Market Crash One-in-Four, Experts Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chances of another stock market crash in the
United States in the next two years are about one-in-four, according
to a poll of investment decision-makers released Tuesday.
   The poll, conducted by the Wall Street firm Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc., found a higher expectation of a crash now than in
similar surveys conducted in February and last October.
   Drexel surveyed 232 people in the United States who make
investment decisions for institutions. They included chief
investment officers and corporate financial officers at big
companies, institutional portfolio managers for stocks and bonds,
securities industry analysts and economists.
   On the average, the respondents saw a 26.6 percent chance of a
crash in the United States within two years. They also believe there
is a 39.5 percent chance of a stock market slide in Japan in that
period and a 23.9 percent probability of one occurring in Europe.
   That compares with average probabilities of 23.9 percent for a
U.S. crash in a Drexel poll taken last February, 42.7 percent for
one in Japan and 26.4 for one in Europe.
   In October 1988, one year after the crash that rattled both Wall
Street and world markets, the same survey found an average 22.8
percent chance for the United States, 42.3 percent for Japan and
23.7 percent for Europe, Drexel said.
</TEXT>
