<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stock Prices Higher in Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar firmed in early trading Wednesday
against the Japanese yen, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange gained moderately.
   The dollar started trading at 146.23 yen, up 0.50 yen from
Tuesday's close of 145.73 yen. It finished at 145.83 yen in New York
overnight, down from Monday's close there of 145.92 yen.
   A dealer with the Bank of Tokyo, who spoke anonymously, said the
dollar would remain ``steady'' at about the 146-yen level in advance
of an international monetary conference scheduled to start Saturday
in Washington. Participants in the so-called Group of Seven meeting
include monetary officials and central bankers from Japan, the
United States, West Germany, Britain, France, Italy and Canada.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which shed 1.47 points Tuesday, gained 77.89 points, or 0.22
percent, shortly after the market opened to move to 34,548.96.
