<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 2230EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Brazil-Debt 2ndLd-Writethru f0093 09-19 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Brazil-Debt, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0093,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazilians Plan to Meet With Bankers in New York</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Brazilian Treasury minister comments.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANCUN, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brazilian Treasury Minister Mailson de
Nobrega was quoted as saying Tuesday his country will resume
payments on its huge foreign debt only if it receives $3 billion in
pending credits from its lenders.
   ``The position of Brazil now is that if it receives the credits
it will pay. Otherwise, no,'' the Mexican government news agency
Notimex quoted de Nobrega as saying.
   According to Notimex, de Nobrega said Brazil expects to reach a
temporary agreement with the International Monetary Fund to obtain
$3 billion in credits so it can renew service payments on its $110
billion foreign debt, the largest in the Third World.
   ``In May it was impossible to reach agreement with the IMF, but
now there is confidence it can be achieved, which will allow funds
to be liberated to cover our commitments with international banks,''
de Nobrega said.
   ``Brazil has not declared a moratorium. It suspended payments
because we did not have money and we have not received around $3
billion from Japan and creditor banks,'' he added.
   De Nobrega was quoted as saying the credits will tide his country
over until whoever is elected president in November takes office in
March 1990. He said the new government then will formulate a policy
on the debt.
   Brazil has not paid $1.6 billion in interest payments that came
due Friday. Its officials plan to meet with officials of the IMF in
New York later this week.
   Brazilian officials said their country will not be seeking a
deadline extension on on debt payments, as some reports have
suggested.
   The treasury minister is part of a group of Brazilian government
bankers attending a meeting in this Caribbean resort. Heads of
federal reserve agencies from Latin America, Spain and the
Philippines are meeting to discuss international strategies to deal
with the IMF and the World Bank.
   Sergio Amaral, adviser on international relations in Brazil's
Treasury Ministry, who spoke with The Associated Press by telephone,
he denied that his government will ask the IMF for a 90-day
extension on debt payments.
   Notimex on Monday quoted Wadico Waldir Bucchi, a governor of the
Brazilian Central Bank, as saying Brazil cannot meet its
obligations, but is seeking to gain time in order to receive a $600
million loan awaiting IMF approval that will be used to service the
debt.
   Notimex quoted Bucchi as saying he is sure the IMF will grant the
90-day extension when he meets later this week with officials of
that organization in New York.
   However, Amaral called this report ``a misunderstanding.''
   Brazil has the biggest foreign debt in the Third World.
   The South American country has previously suspended payments and,
according to news reports in Brazil, such a moratorium would help
maintain its reserves of $6 billion but would hurt its chances of
obtaining fresh money from international lenders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
