<DOCNO> AP890919-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-89 2306EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Hoylake-Farmers     09-19 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Hoylake-Farmers,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sir James Loses Another Round in BAT Buyout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sir James Goldsmith has lost another
round in his attempt to block state regulators from reviewing his
$21.1 billion bid for BAT Industries PLC, the British parent of
Farmer's Group Inc. and several U.S. retailers.
   U.S. District Judge Dale E. Saffels refused Monday to block the
Kansas Insurance Department review of the hostile takeover bid.
   Los Angeles-based Farmers, the 15th-largest insurance holding
company in the United States, operates in nine states. Insurance
regulators in those states are reviewing BAT's proposed takeover to
assure it is in the best interest of policyholders.
   Federal judges in California, Idaho, Texas and Washington already
have denied similar requests by Goldsmith's company, Hoylake
Investments, for preliminary injunctions blocking review in those
states.
   Goldsmith, who contends state regulators have no constitutional
right to review a foreign takeover, declined a request for comment
Tuesday. Spokesmen said, however, that he intends to continue
appealing the rulings.
   Because of the complexities of the state reviews, a British
takeover monitoring panel last week gave him an unprecedented
yearlong extension of his deadline to complete the takeover.
   As part of Goldsmith's proposal, Farmers Group would be sold to
Axa Midi Assurance, a big French insurer, for $4.5 billion.
</TEXT>
